ngdom. Then, she started her first postdoctoral position at the Department of Cell Biology, Physiology and Immunology under a project leaded by the researcher Catalina Casas. Her scientific work is focused on finding new therapies to prevent motoneuron degeneration for Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis and to improve the knowledge of molecular mechanisms involved on motoneuron degeneration. She has contributed to several scientific articles and also as a co-author of 1 patent.</p>\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	The main goal of her scientific research is to find new therapies for motoneuron diseases, especially for Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis. She works with the motoneuron-like cell line (NSC34), spinal cord organotypic cultures and the transgenic ALS mice SOD1<sup>G93A</sup>.</p>\n<p>\n	<em>PATENTS</em></p>\n<p>\n	<em>New combination therapies for treating nervous system diseases.</em>Mireia Coma, Patrick Aloy, Albert Pujol, Jos&eacute; Manuel Mas, Catalina Casas Louzao, Mireia Herrando-Grabulosa, Xavier Navarro, Jordi Naval. <em>Num. 61/754,186-February 2013</em></p>\n','<ul>\n	<li>\n		Casas, C., Isus, L., Herrando-Grabulosa, M., Mancuso, F.M., Borr&aacute;s, E., Sabid&oacute;, E., For&eacute;s, J., and Aloy, P. Network-based proteomic approaches reveal the neurodegenerative, neuroprotective and pain-related mechanisms involved after retrograde axonal damage. Sci. Rep. <em>5</em>, 9185. (<strong>2015</strong>)</li>\n	<li>\n		Casas, C., Herrando-Grabulosa, M., Manzano, R., Mancuso, R., Osta, R., and Navarro, X. Early presymptomatic cholinergic dysfunction in a murine model of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. Brain Behav. <em>3</em>, 145&ndash;158. (<strong>2013</strong>)</li>\n	<li>\n		Herrando-Grabulosa, M., Casas, C., and Aguilera, J. The C-terminal domain of tetanus toxin protects motoneurons against acute excitotoxic damage on spinal cord organotypic cultures. J. Neurochem. <em>124</em>, 36&ndash;44.(<strong>2013</strong>)</li>\n	<li>\n		Mendieta, L., Bautista, E., S&aacute;nchez, A., Guevara, J., Herrando-Grabulosa, M., Moran, J., Mart&iacute;nez, R., Aguilera, J., and Lim&oacute;n, I.D. The C-terminal domain of the heavy chain of tetanus toxin given by intramuscular injection causes neuroprotection and improves the motor behavior in rats treated with 6-hydroxydopamine. Neurosci. Res. <em>74</em>, 156&ndash;167. (<strong>2012</strong>)</li>\n	<li>\n		Penas, C., Verd&uacute;, E., Asensio-Pinilla, E., Guzm&aacute;n-Lenis, M.S., Herrando-Grabulosa, M., Navarro, X., and Casas, C. Valproate reduces CHOP levels and preserves oligodendrocytes and axons after spinal cord injury. Neuroscience <em>178</em>, 33&ndash;44. (<strong>2011</strong>)</li>\n</ul>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-6685-3220\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/K-5364-2014\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=42561185700\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Mireia_Herrando-Grabulosa\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"https://es.linkedin.com/pub/mireia-herrando-grabulosa/5a/80a/588\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"30\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Linkedin.jpg\" width=\"38\" /></a></td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(80,13,0,'Juan ','Hidalgo Pareja','Full Professor','C2 033','Facultat de Biociències','+34 935 812 037','juan.hidalgo@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Cellular Biology, Physiology and Immunology<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty of Biosciences (room C2-033)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','80JHidalgoFotogrupo.jpg','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Juan Hidalgo finished his Biology Degree in 1982 and defended his PhD thesis, supervised by Drs. Antonio Armario and Rosa Flos, in 1986 at the UAB. He has conducted studies and research at the UAB and has collaborated with different laboratories worldwide. He is an ordinary member of the Spanish Society of Neuroscience (SENC) and Spanish Society of Physiology. He coordinates a group of experimental research studying neuroinflammation in animal models.</p>\n','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>RESEARCH INTERESTS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Neurodegenerative diseases are major problems (social, familial, economical) in western countries since aging dramatically contributes. In many of these disease there are clear signs of neuroinflammation; thus to understand how this is orchestrated is his main research interest. The roles of cytokines such as IL-6 and TNF, and of antioxidants and anti-inflammatory proteins such as metallothioneins, by using transgenic mice, are among his interests. Animal models of Alzheimer disease and of multiple sclerosis as well as of traumatic lesions are among the models used in his laboratory.</p>\n<p>\n	His research has been developed to a great extent thanks to the collaborations with many groups; in the last years:</p>\n<p>\n	<u>International Collaborators</u></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Paul A. Adlard &amp; Ashley I. Bush, The Mental Health Research Institute, The University of Melbourne, Victoria, Australia</li>\n	<li>\n		Iain L. Campbell, University of Sydney, Australia</li>\n	<li>\n		M.A. Febbraio, BakerIDI Heart &amp; Diabetes Institute, Melbourne, Australia</li>\n	<li>\n		Michael Karin, University of California San Diego, San Diego, CA, USA<