B) in 2001 and then (2006) a PhD in Neuroscience from the Department of Pharmacology, Therapeutics and Toxicology (UAB). He was then awarded a postdoctoral Research Fellowship (Ministerio de Educaci&oacute;n, Cultura y Deporte of Spain) to conduct postdoctoral research in the Department of Pharmacy and Pharmacology at the University of Bath, UK (2007-2008) and in the Department of Pharmacology at the University of Oxford, UK (2008-2009). He returned to Spain in 2010 on a postdoctoral research position in the Department of Pharmacology, Therapeutics and Toxicology (UAB), where he was then appointed lecturer in pharmacology. In 2012 he was Visiting Scholar at the Instituto de Ci&ecirc;ncias Biom&eacute;dicas (University of S&acirc;o Paulo, Brazil). &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Dr Jim&eacute;nez-Altay&oacute; principal research interest has been in studying how ischemia/reperfusion episodes alter structural, mechanical, functional and biochemical properties of the vessels. Understanding the mechanisms underlying these alterations is required to generate new therapeutic strategies designed to restore vessel/organ function.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<strong><span style=\"color:#800000;\">COLLABORATIONS:</span></strong></p>\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>Anna Maria Planas</u>. Departament d&#39;Isqu&egrave;mia Cerebral i Neurodegeneraci&oacute;, Institut de Recerca Biom&egrave;dica, Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient&iacute;ficas, Institut d&#39;Investigacions Biom&egrave;diques August Pi i Sunyer, Barcelona, Spain.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>&Aacute;ngel Chamorro</u>. Functional Unit of Cerebrovascular Diseases, Hospital Cl&iacute;nic de Barcelona, Institut d&#39;Investigacions Biom&egrave;diques August Pi i Sunyer, Barcelona, Spain.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>Ana Paula Dantas</u>. Institut Cl&iacute;nic del T&ograve;rax, Institut d&#39;Investigacions Biom&egrave;diques August Pi i Sunyer, Barcelona, Spain.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>Maria Helena Carvalho</u>. Department of Pharmacology, Institute of Biomedical Sciences, University of S&atilde;o Paulo, S&atilde;o Paulo, Brazil.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>Gustavo Egea</u>. Departament de Biologia Cel&middot;lular, Immunologia i Neuroci&egrave;ncies, Facultat de Medicina, Universitat de Barcelona, Spain.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>Alister J McNeish</u>. Reading School of Pharmacy, University of Reading, Reading, Berkshire , UK.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>Rosal&iacute;a Rodr&iacute;guez-Rodr&iacute;guez</u>. Departamento de Ciencias B&aacute;sicas, Universitat internacional de Catalunya, Sant cugat del Vall&egrave;s, Spain.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>Xavier Mu&ntilde;oz-Berbel</u>. Instituto de Microelectr&oacute;nica de Barcelona, IMB-CNM (CSIC), Spain.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 36pt; text-align: justify;\">\n		<u>Omar Boutureira</u>. Department of Chemistry. University of Cambridge, UK.</li>\n</ul>\n','<p>\n	See all Francesc Jim&eacute;nez-Altay&oacute; publications at<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=jimenez-altayo+OR+altayo+fj\" target=\"_blank\"> PubMed.</a></p>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-9034-2041\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/F-1245-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=10139589800\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Francesc_Jimenez-Altayo\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(83,13,0,'Marcel ','Jimenez Farrerons',NULL,'V0 125','Facultat de Veterinària','+34 935 811 566','marcel.jimenez@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'<p>\n	See all M. Jimen&eacute;z publication at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830944/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n',NULL),(84,14,0,'Vanessa','Leo Lopez',NULL,'M1 104','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 813 861','vanesa.leo@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(85,13,0,'José Miguel ','Lizcano de Vega','Professor','M2 110','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 813 076','josemiguel.lizcano@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty&nbsp; of Medicine (room M2-110)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','85DSC01111web.JPG','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Jose M Lizcano received the PhD degree (Biochemistry) in 1994 at the UAB. He completed his training at the Laboratory of Prof. Keith F Tipton, Trinity College Dublin, Ireland (1995-96). Then he moved to the MRC Protein Phosphorylation Unit at the University of Dundee (UK), to work as a MRC Research Associate with Professors Sir Philip Cohen and Dario Alessi, dissecting cellular signalling pathways ruled by new protein kinases that play fundamental roles in driving pathologies such as diabetes or cancer (1998-2004). In 2004, he obtained a <em>Ram&oacute;n y Cajal</em> Senior Researcher contract and he was recruited by the <em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em>, where he founded the Protein Kinase and Signal Transduction Laboratory. From 2005, he is Associate Professor at the UAB Department of Biochemistry &amp; Molecular Biology, where he acted as Deputy Director (2008-2014).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	He has published more than 50 papers in refereed journals, and his work has been cited more than 2.500 times</p>\n','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>RESEARCH INTERESTS</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Lizcano&rsquo;s Lab is interested in dissecting new cellular signaling pathways that control cancer cell proliferation and differentiation. We study the new protein kinases ERK5 (a MAP kinase) and the tumor suppressor LKB1, but we are also interested in the Akt-mTORC1 pathway.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	We use two different perspectives to approach fundamental problems:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	a) Basic Research. Dissection of the mechanisms by which LKB1, Akt and ERK5 kinases exert a control on the proliferation and survival of tumor cells. We have contributed to propose new molecular mechanism for regulation of protein kinase Akt; discovered that tumor suppressor kinase LKB1 functions as a master kinase; or more recently, we have established a new mechanism by which ERK5 translocates to the nucleus and regulates the proliferation of tumor cells regardless of its enzymatic activity</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	b) Research directed to pharmacological intervention in cancer. We are involved in potentiating translational aspects of our resources. We established collaboration with the company NeoPharm Obesity forthe screening of new anti-obesity drugs. Since 2011, we actively collaborate with Ability Pharmaceuticals SL in the preclinical/clinical development of the new antitumor drug ABTL0812, which it just finished Clinical Trial Phase I/Ib, first-in-humans (NCT02201823) in cancer patients with solid tumors.We have discovered a new cellular signaling pathway by which ABTL0812 exerts its antitumor action: ABTL0812 activates PPARa/g-mediated transcription of TRIB3 pseudokinase, which in turn binds and inhibits Akt resulting in mTORC1 inhibition, growth arrest and autophagy-mediated cancer cell death. Finally we actively collaborate with other academic laboratories characterizing new ERK5 inhibitors that show anti-tumor activity.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>CURRENT WORK</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	1. Role of MAP kinase ERK5 in cancer cell proliferation (neuroblastoma and glioma)<br />\n	2. Preclinical development of new drugs for cancer therapy. New inhibitors of Akt-mTORC1 axis and autophagy cancer cell death target therapy. New ERK5 inhibitors with anti-cancer activity.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>COLLABORATORS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Prof. Nathanael Gray, Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA<br />\n	Prof. Dario Alessi, University of Dundee, UK<br />\n	Prof. Ricardo Biondi, University Hospital Frankfurt, Germany<br />\n	Prof. Hing Leung, Beatson Institute Cancer Research, Glasgow, UK<br />\n	Prof. Guillermo Velasco, Universidad Complutense Madrid<br />\n	Dr. Miguel Segura, Vall de Hebron Institut de Recerca (VHIR), Barcelona</p>\n','<p>\n	See all Jose M Lizcano publications at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830948/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"margin-left:14.2pt;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>SELECTED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 14.2pt;\">\n		Erazo T, Llorente M, Lopez A, Mu&ntilde;oz-GuardiolaP, Fern&aacute;ndez-NogueiraP, BragadoP, &nbsp;SalazarM, Hernandez-LosaJ, BayascasJR, &nbsp;CortalM, VidalL, GasconP, Gomez-FerreriaM, &nbsp;Alf&oacute;nJ, &nbsp;VelascoG, DomenechC &amp; <strong>LizcanoJM</strong>. <em>The new antitumor drug ABTL0812 inhibits Akt/mTORC1 axis by upregula