eneration through polyimide regenerative electrodes to interface the peripheral nerve. Biomaterials 2005, 26:2021-2031.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Navarro X, Krueger T, Lago N, Micera S, Stieglitz T, Dario P. A critical review of interfaces with the peripheral nervous system for the control of neuroprostheses and hybrid bionic systems. J Peripher Nerv System 2005, 10:229-258.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		L&oacute;pez-Vales R, For&eacute;s J, Verd&uacute; E, Navarro X. Acute and delayed transplantation of olfactory ensheathing cells promote partial recovery after complete transection of the spinal cord. Neurobiol Dis 2006, 21: 57-68.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Navarro X, Viv&oacute; M, Valero-Cabr&eacute; A. Neural plasticity after peripheral nerve injury and regeneration. Progr Neurobiol 2007, 82:163-201.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Casals-D&iacute;az L, Viv&oacute; M, Navarro X. Nociceptive responses and spinal plastic changes of afferent C-fibers in three neuropathic pain models induced by sciatic nerve injury in the rat. Exp Neurol 2009, 217:84-95.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Penas C, Casas C, Robert I, For&eacute;s J, Navarro X. Cytoskeletal and activity-related changes in spinal motoneurons after root avulsion. J Neurotrauma 2009, 26:763-779.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Bruna J, Udina E, Al&eacute; A, Vilches JJ, Vynckier A, Monbaliu J, Silverman L, Navarro X. Neurophysiological, histological and immunohistochemical characterization of bortezomib neuropathy in mice. Exp Neurol 2010, 223: 599-608.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Soler D, Kumru H, Pelayo R, Vidal J, Tormos JM, Fregni F, Navarro X, Pascual-Leone A. Effectiveness of transcranial direct current stimulation and visual illusion on neuropathic pain in spinal cord injury. Brain 2010, 133:2565-2577.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		&nbsp;Penas C, Pascual-Font A, Mancuso R, For&eacute;s J, Casas C, Navarro X. Sigma Receptor agonist 2-(4-morpholinethyl)1-phenylcyclohexanecarboxylate (PRE084) increases GDNF and BIP expression and promotes neuroprotection after root avulsion injury. J Neurotrauma 2011, 28:831-840.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Badia J, Boretius T, Andreu D, Azevedo-Coste C, Stieglitz T, Navarro X. Comparative analysis of transverse intrafascicular multichannel, longitudinal intrafascicular and multipolar cuff electrodes for the selective stimulation of nerve fascicles. J Neural Eng 2011,8(3):036023.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Allodi I, Udina E, Navarro X. Specificity of peripheral nerve regeneration: interactions at the axon level. Progr Neurobiol 2012, 98:16-37.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Mancuso R, Oliv&aacute;n S, Rando A, Casas C, Osta R, Navarro X. Sigma-1R agonist improves motor function and motoneuron survival in ALS mice. Neurotherapeutics 2012, 9:814-826.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Cobianchi S, Casals-Diaz L, Jaramillo J, NavarroX. Differential effects of activity dependent treatments on axonal regeneration and neuropathic pain after peripheral nerve injury. Exp Neurol 2013, 240:157-167.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Torres-Esp&iacute;n A, Corona-Quintanilla DL, For&eacute;s J, Allodi I, Gonz&aacute;lez F, Udina E, Navarro X. Neuroprotection and axonal regeneration after lumbar ventral root avulsion by reimplantation and mesenchymal stem cells transplant combined therapy. Neurotherapeutics 2013, 10:354-368.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Mancuso R, del Valle J, M&ograve;dol L, Martinez A, Granado-Serrano AB, Ramirez-N&uacute;&ntilde;ez O, Pall&aacute;s M, Portero-Otin M, Osta R, Navarro X. Resveratrol improves motoneuron function and extends survival in SOD1<sup>G93A</sup> ALS mice. Neurotherapeutics 2014, 11:419-432.</li>\n	<li style=\"margin-left: 18pt;\">\n		Brunner S, Farzi A, Locker F, Holub B, Lang A, Mayr JA, Vilches JJ, Navarro A, Lang R, Holzer P, Kofler B. GAL<sub>3</sub> receptor knockout mice exhibit an anxiety-like phenotype. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A, 2014; 111:7138-7143.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n','<table height=\"63\" width=\"94\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<p>\n					<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0001-9849-902X\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/C-9577-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<p>\n					<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=22944812800\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Xavier_Navarro\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(106,21,0,'Yara','Onetti Vilalta',NULL,'M4 112','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 811 952','yara.onetti@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(107,13,0,'Jordi','Ortiz de Pablo','Professor','M2 113','','+34 935 814 827','jordi.ortiz@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty&nbsp; of Medicine (room M2-113)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','107foto jordi 2.jpg','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Dr. Jordi Ortiz is Associate Professor at the Universitat Autonoma de Barcelona, Schools of Medicine and Biosciences, where he teaches Metabolism, Molecular Pharmacology and Neurosciences. He mentors Masters and PhD students of the programs in Neurosciences and Biochemistry, Molecular Biology and Biomedicine. Jordi Ortiz earned the Bachelor of Biological Sciences in 1986 and the PhD degree in 1991, both at the Universitat de Barcelona. He performed postdoctoral research at Yale University, USA (1992-1994) and Universit&eacute; Paris Descartes, France (1995-1996). He joined the Universitat Autonoma de Barcelona in 1997, where he obtained tenure in 2006. During that year he was also Visiting Professor at the University Texas Southwestern Medical Center.</p>\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Jordi Ortiz research focuses on biochemical targets for psychotropic drugs, including drugs of abuse, antipsychotics and antidepressants. He has gained experience in this field by using a variety of experimental approaches, from animal behavior to molecular pharmacology, biochemistry and brain histology, devoted to understand the mechanism of action of these drugs and to improve treatment strategies.<br />\n	Currently his research is coordinated with that of Dr. Jesus Giraldo in a multidisciplinary task devoted to integrate experimental, mathematic and mechanistic explanations of receptor function relevant to neuropharmacology to improve mathematic and mechanistic explanations of receptor function relevant to neuropharmacology.&nbsp;<br />\n	This research is funded by the Spanish Ministerio de Economia y Competitividad (SAF2014 to 2017) under the title &ldquo;Integrated mathematical, computational and biochemical investigation of the crosstalk between metabotropic glutamate receptor 5 and dopamine D2 receptor: Relevance for the treatment of schizophrenia&rdquo;.<br />\n	Jordi Ortiz is also participating in the Spanish Red de Trastornos Adictivos (<a href=\"http://www.redrta.es/\">http://www.redrta.es/</a>) in close collaboration with Drs. Antonio Armario and Roser Nadal in the project &ldquo;Neurobiology, Medical Consequences and Therapeutics of Alcoholism&rdquo;</p>\n','<p>\n	See all J. Ortiz publication at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830996/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	See all Jordi Ortiz research publications at ORCID (<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-9748-2290\">http://orcid.org/0000-0002-9748-2290</a>), Researcher ID (<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/E-9018-2011\">http://www.researcherid.com/rid/E-9018-2011</a>) or Google Scholar (http://scholar.google.es/citations?sortby=pubdate&amp;hl=ca&amp;user=aaPO4uoAAAAJ&amp;view_op=list_works)</p>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-9748-2290\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/E-9018-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7203050650\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://scholar.google.es/citations?sortby=pubdate&amp;hl=ca&amp;user=aaPO4uoAAAAJ&amp;view_op=list_works\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"30\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/googlescholar.jpg\" width=\"30\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://es.linkedin.com/pub/jordi-ortiz/60/717/511\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"31\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Linkedin.jpg\" width=\"36\" /></a></td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(108,13,0,'Marc','Pallarés Anyó',NULL,'B5 051','Facultat de Psicologia','+34 935 812 542','marc.pallares@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'<p>\n	See all M. Pallar&egrave;s publication at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830997/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n',NULL),(110,21,0,'Luis ','Pardo Fernández',NULL,'M2 003.1','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 818 142','',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(112,14,0,'Belen ','Perez Fernández',NULL,'M4 108','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 811 963','belen.perez@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(113,13,0,'Fernando ','Picatoste Ramón',NULL,'M2 111','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 811 574','fernando.picatoste@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'<p>\n	See all F. Picatoste publication at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830787/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n',NULL),(114,13,0,'Olga','Pol Rigau','Senior Researcher','M2 115','','+34 935 818 534','olga.pol@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty&nbsp; of Medicine (room M2-115)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','114Olga Pol .jpg','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Olga Pol obtained her PhD in Biological Sciences in 1991 at the Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona. From 1992-1995, she was Postdoctoral Fellow in the Institut Municipal d&rsquo;Investigaci&oacute; M&egrave;dica-Parc de Recerca Biom&egrave;dica de Barcelona (IMIM-PRBB). In 1995, she made a post-doctoral stage in the University of Washington, Seattle, USA and remained as Scientific Researcher in the IMIM-PRBB until 1998.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	In 1999, she obtained a Miguel Servet contract from the Instituto de Salud Carlos III, Madrid and worked at the IMIM-PRBB, until 2005. During this period, she made a post-doctoral stage in the Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, USA, to study the nitric oxide signaling pathways. In 2005, she moved to the Institut de Recerca Biom&egrave;dica Sant Pau of the Hospital de la Santa Creu i Sant Pau.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	From 2005 to present, she is Senior Researcher and Group Leader of Molecular Neuropharmacology in the Institut de Recerca Biom&egrave;dica Sant Pau, Hospital de la Santa Creu i Sant Pau as well as of the Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies of the Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Olga Pol has been published in the top journals of Anesthesiology and Pharmacology and directed several Master and Doctoral Theses in Neuroscience. She has an European Patent Application and the AQU accreditation as a Full Professor. She is also Evaluator of National and International Agencies, and Member of relevant Scientific Societies.</p>\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Chronic pain affects a high percentage of adult population and is difficult to treat even with the most potent analgesic compounds, being one of the main challenges of the current research. In the last years, the main objective of our group has been to investigate new strategies for the treatment of inflammatory, arthritic and neuropathic pain by using genetic, pharmacological and behavioral approaches.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	With this objective, we have investigated the molecular mechanisms implicated in the analgesic effects of opioid and cannabinoid receptors during acute and chronic pain by evaluating the role played by the nitric oxide-carbon monoxide-cGMP signaling pathway in the modulation of their expression and antinociceptive actions.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	We have demonstrated that the administration of carbon monoxide releasing compounds and heme-oxygenase 1 inductors inhibits the development of acute pain (inflammatory, visceral, response to heat) and chronic pain (arthritis, neuropathy induced by the total or partial sciatic nerve injury) and enhances the analgesic effects of opioid and cannabinoid 2 receptor agonists in animals with chronic pain with little side effects.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Our present interest is to identify new approaches for the treatment of painful diabetic neuropathy, oxidative stress and obesity, three main complications of Diabetes 2, by using specific &nbsp;drug combinations.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	In collaboration with other Groups, we also investigate the contribution of the carbon monoxide-nitric oxide systems in the modulation of emotional and nociceptive responses induced by chronic inflammation in the central nervous system of mice.</p>\n','<p>\n	See all Olga Pol publications <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48831001/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MOST RELEVANT PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Carcol&eacute; M, Castany S, L&eacute;anez S, Pol O. Treatment with an heme oxygenase 1 inducer enhances the antinociceptive effects of &micro;- and &delta;-opioid and cannabinoid 2 receptors during inflammatory pain. J Pharmacol Exp Ther 2014; 351:224-232.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Negrete R, Hervera A, Le&aacute;nez S, Pol O. Treatment with a carbon monoxide-releasing molecule inhibits chronic inflammatory pain in mice: nitric oxide contribution. Psychopharmacology (Berl) 2014; 231:853-861.</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Hervera A, Le&aacute;nez S, Motterlini R, Pol O. Treatment with Carbon Monoxide-releasing Molecules and an HO-1 Inducer Enhances the Effects and Expression of &micro;-Opioid Receptors during Neuropathic Pain. Anesthesiology 2013; 118:1180-1197.</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Hervera A, Gou G, Le&aacute;nez S, Pol O. Effects of treatment with a carbon monoxide-releasing molecule and a heme oxygenase 1 inducer in the antinociceptive effects of morphine in different models of acute and chronic pain in mice. Psychopharmacology (Berl) 2013; 228:463-477.</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Hervera A, Le&aacute;nez S, Negrete R, Motterlini R, Pol O. Carbon monoxide reduces neuropathic pain and spinal microglial activation by inhibiting nitric oxide synthesis in mice. PLoS One 2012; 7(8):e43693.</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Negrete R, Hervera A, Le&aacute;nez S, Mart&iacute;n-Campos JM, Pol O. The antinociceptive effects of JWH-015 in chronic inflammatory pain are produced by nitric oxide-cGMP-PKG-KATP pathway activation mediated by opioids. PLoS One 2011; 6(10):e26688.</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Hervera A, Negrete R, Le&aacute;nez S, Mart&iacute;n-Campos JM, Pol O. Peripheral effects of morphine and expression of &mu;-opioid receptors in the dorsal root ganglia during neuropathic pain: nitric oxide signaling. Molecular Pain 2011; 12;7:25.</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Hervera A, Negrete R, Le&aacute;nez S, Mart&iacute;n-Campos JM, Pol O. The spinal cord expression of neuronal and inducible nitric oxide synthases and their contribution in the maintenance of neuropathic pain in mice. PLoS One 2010; 13;5(12):e14321.</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Hervera A, Negrete R, Le&aacute;nez S, Mart&iacute;n-Campos J, Pol O. The role of nitric oxide in the local antiallodynic and antihyperalgesic effects and expression of delta-opioid and cannabinoid-2 receptors during neuropathic pain in mice. J Pharmacol Exp Ther 2010; 334(3):887-896.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-4621-8457\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/C-9194-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<p>\n					<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6701603494\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Olga_Pol\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(115,13,0,'Isabel ','Portell Cortés','Professor','B5 037','','+34 935 813 220','isabel.portell@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Psychobiology and Methodology of Health Science<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty&nbsp; of Psychology (room B5-037)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','115DSC01002web.jpg','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Isabel Portell studied Psychology in the <em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona</em>, and defended her PhD thesis, supervised by Ignacio Morgado, in 1987. Since 1991 she is associate professor in the same University, where she teaches psychobiology courses. She has been director of the Department of Psychobiology and Methodology of Health Sciences from 2008 to 2011. She has been member of the Local Organizing Committee of 35 Annual General Meeting of the European Brain and Behaviour Society (EBBS, Barcelona, 2003).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	She has conducted and coordinated research to study the facilitatory effects of sleep, post-training epinephrine and physical exercise on learning and memory processes. Currently, she coordinates a group of experimental research focused on the capacity of physical exercise to reduce memory deficits, and on the underlying neurobiological mechanisms.</p>\n','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Research interests</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Her research interests focus on the capacity of physical exercise to reduce cognitive deficits associated to brain injury, and to evaluate its underlying mechanisms of action.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Current work</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Her current work focuses on evaluating the temporal patterns of physical exercise that are able to reduce memory deficits, and the cellular and molecular mechanisms underlying the differential effects. The research group is also interested in studying whether TBI affects several biomarkers related to synaptic plasticity, neuroinflammation and neurodegenerative diseases, and to evaluate whether the observed effects might be reduced by physical exercise. This knowledge might contribute to the introduction of physical exercise as a treatment in patients with brain injury.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n','<p>\n	See all Isabel Portell-Cort&eacute;s publications at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48831024/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>SELECTED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Jacotte-Simancas, A.; Costa-Miserachs, D.; Coll-Andreu, M.; Torras-Garcia, M.; Borlongan, C.; Portell-Cort&eacute;s, I. (2015). Effects of voluntary physical exercise, citicoline, and combined treatment on object recognition memory, neurogenesis and neuroprotection after traumatic brain injury in rats. <em>Journal of Neurotrauma</em>, <strong>32</strong> (739-751).</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Amor&oacute;s-Aguilar, L.; Portell-Cort&eacute;s, I.; Costa-Miserachs, D.; Torras-Garcia, M.; &nbsp;Coll-Andreu, M. (2015). Traumatic Brain Injury in Late Adolescent Rats: Effects on Adulthood Memory and Anxiety. <em>Behavioral Neuroscience</em>, <strong>129</strong> (2), 149-159</li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Jacotte-Simancas, A.; Costa-Miserachs, D.; Torras-Garcia, M., Coll-Andreu, M.; Portell-Cort&eacute;s, I. (2013). Effects of voluntary physical exercise and post-training epinephrine on acquisition in a spatial task in the Barnes maze. <em>Behavioural Brain Research, <strong>247</strong>, 178-181.</em></li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Jurado-Berbel, P.; Costa-Miserachs, D.; Torras-Garcia, M.; Coll-Andreu, M.; Portell-Cort&eacute;s, I. (2010). Standard object recognition memory and &ldquo;what&rdquo; and &ldquo;where&rdquo; components: Improvement by post-training epinephrine in highly habituated rats. <em>Behavioural Brain Research, <strong>207</strong>, 44-50.</em></li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Garc&iacute;a-Capdevila, S.; Portell-Cort&eacute;s, I.; Torras-Garcia, M.; Coll-Andreu, M.; Costa-Miserachs, D. (2009). Effects of long-term voluntary exercise on learning and memory processes: dependency of the task and level of exercise. <em>Behavioural Brain Research, <strong>202</strong>, 162-170.</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://%20http://orcid.org/0000-0002-7710-0101\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/C-5991-2011\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<p>\n					<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6602337878\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Isabel_Portell-Cortes\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(116,14,0,'Mireia','Recasens Torné',NULL,'M1 122','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 868 248','mireia.recasens@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(118,13,0,'José ','Rodríguez Alvarez','Professor','M2 115','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 811 525','jose.rodriguez@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty&nbsp; of Medicine (room M2-116)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','118JRodriguez.jpg','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	I started my scientific career as a Ph.D student in the laboratory of Prof. Isaac Blanco (Dpt. Biochemistry,<em>Universitat&nbsp; Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona;</em> UAB) during 1986-1990. After my Ph.D, I move to the National Institute for Medical Research in London (1991-92) where I investigated long-term effects of glutamate receptor stimulation on glutamate release and presynaptic proteins under the supervision of Prof. A J. Patel and Prof. T.V.P Bliss. My second post-doctoral stage was in Montpellier (1993-94) to work in the laboratory of Prof. Joel Bockaertin a join research unit of the CNRS and INSERM. In Bockaert&rsquo;s laboratory I worked in the regulation by glutamate receptors of neuronal NO synthesis. I came back as an assistant professor to the UAB in 1995 and in 1997 I was awarded a staff position in the Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology of the UAB as Associate Professor. I was able to run my own laboratory and research projects from 2000. Our laboratory is a founder group of the Spanish Center for Translational Research in Neurodegenerative Diseases (CIBERNED) since 2006.</p>\n<p>\n	During all these years at UAB, I&rsquo;ve also been engaged with academic activities. Besides teaching at undergraduate and graduate levels, I will like to remark my appointment as Director of the<em> Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em> (INc) of the UAB from 2002 to 2008. I have been also awarded with the Full Professor accreditation from the Spanish Universities Council (ANECA) in 2010 and the Full Professor Advanced Research accreditation from AQU in 2011. At present I&rsquo;m the Coordinator of the Neuroscience PhD program and member of the Board of Directors of the INc.</p>\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	During the last years, the basic objective of our research team has been the study of the cellular and molecular mechanisms involved in the synaptic dysfunction and neuronal death as a straight approach for the understanding of neurodegeneration in diverse pathologies. At present, the laboratory is focused in the study of the mechanisms involved in early dysfunction of synaptic activity in Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	During the last decade, the idea that the alteration of synaptic function in Alzheimer&rsquo;s Disease (AD) occurs well before neurodegeneration is becoming widely accepted. Moreover, it has been suggested that the progressive accumulation of self-aggregates of A&beta; as oligomers (oA&beta;) would mediate this synaptic dysfunction, leading to the initial cognitive deficits observed in mild cognitive impairment (MCI) and earlier AD stages.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	In this context, we have recently observed that oA&beta; promotes the internalization of synaptic AMPA receptors (AMPAR) and also blocks the increase in synaptic AMPAR elicited by cLTP. Moreover, we have also reported a reduction of GluA1-AMPAR in APP<sub>Sw,Ind</sub> mice in correlation with the early learning deficits previously observed in our laboratory. We postulate that prolonged interaction of oA&beta;with excitatory synapses could cause a deep effect on AMPARs levels through changes in the mechanisms that regulate AMPARs gene expression and trafficking. The identification of the molecular mechanisms involved in oA&beta;-mediated synaptic AMPAR functional alteration is a central issue of research in our laboratory.</p>\n','<p>\n	See all Jos&eacute; Rodr&iacute;guez Alvarez publications at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48831035/public/\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>SELECTED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Xifr&oacute;, X &amp; J. Rodr&iacute;guez-Alvarez. Delineating the factors and cellular mechanisms involved in the survival of Cerebellar Granule Neurons.<em> Cerebellum 14:354-359 (2015)</em></li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Parra-Damas, A., Valero, J., Chen, M., Espa&ntilde;a, J., Mart&iacute;n, E., Ferrer, I., Rodr&iacute;guez-Alvarez, J &amp; C.A. Saura. CRTC1 activates a transcriptional program deregulated at early Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease-related stages.<em> J Neurosci. 34:5576-5787 (2014)</em></li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Fad&oacute;, R., Moubarak, R., Mi&ntilde;ano-Molina, A.J., Barneda-Zahonero, B., Valero, J., Saura, C.A., Mor&aacute;n, J., Comella, J.X. &amp; J. Rodr&iacute;guez-Alvarez. X-linked inhibitor of apoptosis protein negatively regulates neurite outgrowth through interaction with cRAF and Trk.<em> Sci Reports. 3:2397 (2013) doi: 10.1038/srep02397</em></li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Barneda-Zahonero, B., Servitja, J.M., Badiola, N., Mi&ntilde;ano-Molina, A.J., Fad&oacute;, R., Saura, C.A. &amp; J. Rodriguez-Alvarez. Nurr1 is required for NMDA receptor-mediated neuronal survival.<em> J. Biol. Chem. 287:11351-11362 (2012)</em></li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Mi&ntilde;ano-Molina, A.J., Espa&ntilde;a, J., Martin, E. Barneda-Zahonero, B., Fad&oacute;, R., Sol&eacute;, M., Trull&aacute;s, R., Saura, C.A. &amp; J. Rodr&iacute;guez-Alvarez.&nbsp; Soluble oligomers of amyloid-beta peptide disrupt membrane trafficking of AMPA receptors contributing to early synapse dysfunction.<em> J Biol. Chem. 286:27311-27321 (2011)</em></li>\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n		Espa&ntilde;a, J., Valero, J., Mi&ntilde;ano-Molina, A., Masgrau, R., Mart&iacute;n,E., Guardia-Laguarta,C., Lle&oacute;, A., Gim&eacute;nez-Llort, L., Rodr&iacute;guez-Alvarez, J. &amp; C.A. Saura. &szlig;-amyloid disrupts activity-dependent gene transcription required for memory through the CREB coactivator CRTC1<em> J. Neurosci. 30:9402-9410 (2010)</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0001-8582-8082\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"26\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" width=\"26\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/F-8403-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<p>\n					<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7005924608\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jose_Rodriguez-Alvarez\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"29\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"https://scholar.google.es/citations?user=Jzdr4AoAAAAJ&amp;hl=ca&amp;oi=ao\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/googlescholar.jpg\" width=\"31\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://es.linkedin.com/in/peperodriguez\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"31\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Linkedin.jpg\" width=\"38\" /></a></td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(119,14,0,'Maria Jesús ','Nebrera Navas',NULL,'M1 105','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 814 257','mariajesus.nebrera@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(121,13,0,'Josefa ','Sabrià Pau','Professor','M2 122','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 811 574','josefa.sabria@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty&nbsp; of Medicine (room M2-122)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','121pepi.jpg','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Associate Professor at Faculty of Medicine and Faculty of Biosciences, <em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona</em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Teaching Biochemistry, Metabolism and Neurochemistry in the Degree of Medicine and in the Degree of Biomedical Sciences.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Research Tutor for Master and PhD students of the Program in Neurosciences and the Program in Biochemistry, Molecular Biology and Biomedicine.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Besides teaching, since 2012 being engaged as Secretary of the Faculty of Medicine, Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona.</p>\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Current research interest focused on new applications in the field of heteromerization of G protein-coupled receptors, specifically of dopamine and glutamate metabotropic receptors.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Since 2005 joined the group of Dr Jordi Ortiz with whom a close collaboration remains actively working. With Dr. Jes&uacute;s Giraldo and Dr. Carles Gil we have recently established a multidisciplinary group at the <em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em> of the<em> Universitat Aut&ograve;noma</em>: Laboratory of Molecular Neuropharmacology &amp; Bioinformatics, to focus on receptor heteromerization&nbsp; by combining mathematical and molecular models with biochemical data obtained from brain samples.&nbsp;&nbsp; In this line, the group has been granted by the Ministerio de Economia y Competitividad for a research project (SAF2014 to 2017) focused on getting more insight on heteromerization of mGlu5 receptors and D2 dopamine receptors and its relevance in schizophrenia.</p>\n','<p>\n	See all J. Sabri&agrave; publication at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/49229777/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	See all MJ Sabri&aacute; publications at ORCID (<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-1456-4136\">http://orcid.org/0000-0002-1456-4136</a>),&nbsp; Researcher ID (<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/A-2439-2010\">http://www.researcherid.com/rid/A-2439-2010</a>) or Google Scholar (<a href=\"https://scholar.google.es/citations?user=1bUkvoYAAAAJ&amp;hl=ca\">https://scholar.google.es/citations?user=1bUkvoYAAAAJ&amp;hl=ca</a>)</p>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-1456-4136\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/A-2439-2010\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<p>\n					<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7003867773\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"https://scholar.google.es/citations?user=1bUkvoYAAAAJ&amp;hl=ca\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"30\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/googlescholar.jpg\" width=\"30\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(124,21,0,'Daniel ','Santos Rojas',NULL,'M4 129','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 812 020','daniel.santos@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(126,13,0,'Carlos A.','Saura Antolín','Professor','M2 113','','+34 935 818 398','carlos.saura@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty&nbsp; of Medicine (room M2-113)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','126retoc_CSaura4_tamanyok.jpg','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Carlos A. Saura obtained his Ph.D. in Chemistry from the University of Barcelona (Spain) in 1998. Following postdoctoral training at Johns Hopkins University and University of Chicago under the mentoring of Dr. G. Thinakaran, he was appointed Instructor at the Department of Neurology at Harvard Medical School (Boston, USA) in 2000. Under the supervision of Dr. J. Shen, he investigated the role of presenilins in memory and neurodegeneration in novel transgenic and knockout disease mouse models. In 2004, he was appointed Ram&oacute;n y Cajal Research Professor at the Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (Spain). Dr. C. Saura is currently an Associate Professor in the Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology at the Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies of the Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona. Dr. Saura has published more than 30 peer-reviewed articles in molecular aspects of brain function and neurodegeneration, has directed several European research projects and is an active collaborator of several national and international founding agencies and scientific journals.</p>\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Dr. Carlos Saura&acute;s research interest focuses in understanding the molecular mechanisms that regulate neuronal function in the brain during normal and pathological aging. He is passionate in understanding how brain functions during memory processing and the mechanisms involved in synapse and memory dysfunction in age-related cognitive disorders. Particularly, Dr. Saura investigates the role of specific genes and the mechanisms that regulate gene expression programs implicated in Alzheimer&acute;s disease and other dementias. Dr. Saura has used pioneering approaches to generate novel transgenic and knockout mouse models of neurodegeneration that are used for assessing new pharmacological, cognitive stimulation and gene therapy strategies&nbsp; as alternative therapies in dementia. His projects provide knowledge of novel molecular targets and new therapeutic strategies for early treatment of Alzheimer&acute;s and related neurological disorders.</p>\n','<p>\n	See all Carlos A. Saura publications at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48831037/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>SELECTED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<strong>Saura C.A</strong>.*, Yu H.*, Choi S-Y., Sun L.D., Yang X., Handler M., Kawarabayashi T., Younkin L., Fedeles B., Wilson M.A., Younkin S., Kandel E.R., Kirkwood A. and Shen J. APP processing and synaptic plasticity in presenilin-1 conditional (2001). <em>Neuron,</em> 31 (5): 713-726</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<strong>Saura C. A.</strong>, Choi S.-Y., Beglopoulos V., Malkani S., Zhang D., Shankaranarayana Rao B. S., Chattarji S., Kelleher III R. J., Kandel E. R., Duff K., Kirkwood A. and Shen J. Loss of presenilin function causes impairments of memory and synaptic plasticity followed by age-dependent neurodegeneration (2004). <em>Neuron,</em> 42: 23-36.<br />\n		&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		<strong>Saura C.A</strong>., Chen G., Malkani S., Choi S.-Y., Zhang D., Takahashi R.H., Gouras G.K., Kirkwood A., Morris R.G.M. and Shen J. Conditional inactivation of presenilin-1 prevents amyloid accumulation and temporarily rescues associative and working memory impairments in APP transgenic mice (2005). <em>J. Neurosci.</em> 25(29):6755-64.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Espa&ntilde;a J., Gim&eacute;nez-Llort L., Valero G&oacute;mez-Lobo J., Mi&ntilde;ano A., R&aacute;bano A., Rodr&iacute;guez-Alvarez J., LaFerla F.M. and <strong>Saura C.A.</strong>Intraneuronal A&beta;accumulation in the amygdala enhances fear and anxiety in Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease transgenic mice (2010). <em>Biol. Psychiatry</em> 67(6): 513-521.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Parra-Damas A., Valero J., Chen M., Espa&ntilde;a J., Martin E., Ferrer I., Rodr&iacute;guez-Alvarez J. and Saura C.A. &nbsp;Crtc1 activates a transcriptional program deregulated at early Alzheimer&acute;s disease-related stages&nbsp; (2014). <em>J. Neurosci</em>. 34(17): 5776-87.<br />\n		&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		<strong>Saura C.A.</strong>, Parra-Damas A.J. and Enr&iacute;quez-Barreto L. Gene expression parallels synaptic excitability and plasticity changes in Alzheimer&acute;s disease (2015). <em>Front. Cell. Neurosci</em>, 9:318</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0003-3692-5657\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/D-2727-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<p>\n					<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6701471293\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				&nbsp;</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(127,13,0,'Pilar ','Segura Torres','Professor in Physiological Psychology','B5 035','','+34 935 813 221','pilar.segura@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Psychobiology and Methodology of Health Science<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty&nbsp; of Psychology (room B5-035)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','127PSeguraweb.JPG','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>TEACHING TASKS</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Degree in Psychology<br />\n	Master in Neuroscience<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Pilar Segura-Torres finished her Psychology Degree in 1985 and defended her PhD thesis, supervised by Dr. Ignacio Morgado, in 1989 at the UAB. Since 1992 she is associate professor in the same University, where teaches psychobiology courses. She has conducted studies and research at the Heinrich Heine Universit&auml;t D&uuml;sseldorf (Germany) and currently she collaborates with the department of molecular biology at the University of Girona. She has been member of the Local Organizing Committee of 35 Annual General Meeting of the European Brain and Behaviour Society (EBBS, Barcelona, 2003) and she is the current director of the Department of Psychobiology and Methodology of Health Sciences at the UAB.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Currently, she coordinates a group of experimental research on improvement and recovery of learning and memory by intracranial electrical stimulation in normal and brain damaged rats (behavior and neural mechanisms).</p>\n','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>RESEARCH INTERESTS</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Her research interests focus on the capacity of Intracranial Self-Stimulation treatment to improve learning and memory and to reduce cognitive deficits associated to brain injury or aging, and to evaluate its underlying mechanisms of action. The research team aims &nbsp;to continuing the exploration of the therapeutical potential of ICSS on other kinds of memory, phases (consolidation, extinction) or on other conditions (severe amnesia), and to contrasting the hypotheses about the plasticity mechanisms involved in the facilitatory effect of ICSS (structural and synaptic plasticity, neuroprotection and neurogenesis) in those brain regions most involved in memory processes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	In the middle term it is expected that the achievement of these goals through animal research will aid in treatment schedules that might alleviate some memory deficits in human patients.</p>\n','<p>\n	See all Pilar Segura-Torres publications at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48831039/public/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>SELECTED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Chamorro-L&oacute;pez J, Miguens M, Morgado-Bernal I, Kastanauskaite A, Selvas A, Caban&eacute;-Cucurella A, Aldavert-Vera L, DeFelipe J, Segura-Torres P. Structural plasticity in hippocampal cells related to the facilitative effect of intracranial self-stimulation on a spatial memory task. Behavioral Neuroscience 2015 (in press).</li>\n	<li>\n		K&aacute;d&aacute;r E, Ramoneda M, Aldavert-Vera L, Huguet G, Morgado-Bernal I, Segura-Torres P. Rewarding brain stimulation reverses the disruptive effect of amygdala damage on emotional learning. Behav Brain Res. 2014, 274:43-52.</li>\n	<li>\n		K&aacute;d&aacute;r E, Huguet G, Aldavert-Vera L, Morgado-Bernal I, Segura-Torres P. Intracranial self-stimulation upregulates the expression of synaptic plasticity related genes and Arc protein expression in rat hippocampus Genes Brain &amp; Behav. 2013, 12: 771-779.</li>\n	<li>\n		Aldavert-Vera L, Huguet G, Costa-Miserachs D, Pena de Ortiz S, K&aacute;d&aacute;r E, Morgado-Bernal I, Segura-Torres P. Intracranial self-stimulation facilitates active-avoidance retention and induces expression of c-Fos and Nurr1 in rat brain memory systems. Behav Brain Res. 2013, 250: 46</li>\n</ul>\n','<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0001-6963-8625\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/G-2810-2011%20%28\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Pilar_Segura-Torres\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"https://www.mendeley.com/profiles/pilar-segura-torres/\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"28\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/mendeley.png\" width=\"28\" /></a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"https://scholar.google.es/citations?user=ckhQsR8AAAAJ&amp;hl=ca\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/googlescholar.jpg\" width=\"29\" /></a></td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n'),(128,13,0,'Juan','Serra Mari',NULL,'M3 206','Facultat de Medicina','+34 935 818 148','juan.serra@uab.cat',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(130,10,0,'Montserrat','Solé Piñol','Postdoctoral researcher','M2 124','','+34 935 811 624','montserrat.sole@uab.cat','<p>\n	Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology<br />\n	<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies</em><br />\n	Faculty of Medicine (room M2-124)<br />\n	<em>Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB)</em><br />\n	Bellaterra Campus 08193-Cerdanyola del Vall&eacute;s</p>\n','130DSC00598web.jpg','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>PRESENT POSITION</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Postdoctoral Researcher at the Neurosciences Institute and Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology of Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB). (2009 &ndash; present).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>PREVIOUS</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<em>Postdoctoral stay </em>at Department of Neurology. Stanford University School of Medicine. Palo Alto, California (United States). From March to September, 2012. Project: &ldquo;Mechanisms of post-stroke dementia in mice&rdquo;.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<em>Pre-doctoral stay</em> at Unit&eacute; mixte UHP-INSERM U684. Nancy (France). From September to December, 2008. Project: &ldquo;Impact of smooth muscle cells&rsquo; SSAO activity on endothelial cells using a co-culture system&rdquo;.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>EDUCATION</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<em>Ph.D., in Neurosciences</em>; Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB), Barcelona, Spain. 2005 &ndash; 2009. Supervisor: Mercedes Unzeta Lopez. PhD project: &ldquo;Estudi dels mecanismes moleculars implicats en el dany vascular indu&iuml;t per l&rsquo;activitat catal&iacute;tica de la SSAO en el context de l&rsquo;Angiopatia Cerebral Amiloide associada a la dem&egrave;ncia tipus Alzheimer&rdquo; / &ldquo;Study of the molecular mechanisms involved in the vascular damage induced by the SSAO catalytic activity in the context of Cerebral Amyloid Angiopathy related to Alzheimer&rsquo;s type dementia&rdquo;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<em>B.Sc, Biology</em>, Universitat Pompeu Fabra, Barcelona, Spain 1999 &ndash; 2004</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<em>Technical skills</em>: MAIN: cell culture, development of stable transfected cell lines, western blot, immunohistochemistry, immunocytochemistry, human and animal sample processing, enzymology. OTHERS (working sporadically): animal behaviour, molecular biology, immunoprecipitation, confocal microscopy.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<em>Languages</em>: Catalan, Spanish, English, French (basic user)</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<em>Official certificates:</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Supervisor of Radioactive Installations, speciality Laboratories with Non-Encapsulated Radioactive Sources, recognized by the Spanish Nuclear Security Council. March 2013.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Use of Animals for Experimentation and other Scientific Objectives, recognized by the Departament de Medi Ambient i Habitatge de la Generalitat de Catalunya, according to the Federation of European Laboratory Animal Science Associations - FELASA, february 2007 &ndash; Barcelona, Spain.</p>\n','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>RESEARCH INTERESTS</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	The vascular system plays an important role in maintaining the correct function of the different organs in the body, including central nervous system. Actually, a large number of diseases are partly caused or involve a dysfunction of the blood vessels, and this phenomenon occurs also in the brain, where the vascular system has become specialized in maintaining the central nervous system isolated from the peripheral blood forming a &ldquo;barrier&rdquo; that allows a very controlled transport of nutrients and selected substances. Unfortunately, there is nowadays an increasing incidence of pathologies affecting the brain, such as Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease (AD) or Stroke, which produce different disability degrees and high social and economic costs.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	My main research interest is focused on elucidating the role of the cerebrovascular system in the brain pathologies and finding out new therapeutic targets that would contribute to decrease the incidence or severity of these diseases. I am particularly interested in the role of the vascular amine oxidase SSAO/VAP-1 in these processes because this protein has been found abnormally increased in these pathologic conditions.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>CURRENT WORK</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Besides studying the role of SSAO/VAP-1 in several cellular models of endothelia simulating AD and Stroke, I am starting a novel project involving the influence of the vascular system in the neuronal dysfunction in the earliest stages of the AD pathology. In this project, we co-culture brain endothelial cells with primary neuronal cultures and we pretend to study the communication between these two cell systems, as well as the consequences of this cross talk on their function with the objective of identifying new biomarkers or therapeutic targets for the AD delay and/or progression.</p>\n','<p>\n	See all Montserrat Sol&eacute;&nbsp; publications at <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=Sol%C3%A9%20M[Author]&amp;cauthor=true&amp;cauthor_uid=21819380\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Sol&eacute; M, Mi&ntilde;ano-Molina AJ, Unzeta M. A cross talk between A&beta; and endothelial SSAO/VAP-1 accelerates vascular damage and A&beta; aggregation related to CAA-AD.Neurobiol Aging (2014)</li>\n	<li>\n		Sun P, Sol&eacute; M, Unzeta M.Involvement of SSAO/VAP-1 in oxygen-glucose deprivation-mediated damage using the endothelial hSSAO/VAP-1-expressing cells as an experimental model of cerebral ischemia. Cerebrovasc Dis (2014), 37:171-180.</li>\n	<li>\n		Gella A, Sol&eacute; M, Bolea I, Ventriglia M, Siotto M, Durany N, Squitti R, Unzeta M. A comparison between radiometric and fluorimetric methods for measuring SSAO activity. J Neural Transm. (2013), 120:1015-1018.</li>\n	<li>\n		Esteban G, Bolea I, Sun P, Sol&eacute; M, Samadi A, Marco-Contelles J, Unzeta M. A therapeutic approach to cerebrovascular diseases based on 