',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(247,14,0,'Jaume','Ferrer Lalanza',NULL,'M1 122','','+34 935 868 248','Jaume.Ferrer.Lalanza@uab.cat',NULL,'247jaumelalanza.jpg','<p>\n	Jaume Ferrer Lalanza is a lab technician at INC&rsquo;s Behavioural Assessment Unit.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>2009&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BS in Psychology </strong>with honours. Autonomous University of Barcelona (Spain).</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>2010</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>MSc in Health and Sport Psychology</strong>. Autonomous University of Barcelona.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>2013&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pre-Doctoral Research Stay. </strong>BE-DGR 2012 Fellowship. University of British Columbia (Canada).</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>2014&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PhD in Health and Sport Psychology. </strong>FI-DGR 2011 Fellowship.Autonomous University of Barcelona.</p>\n','<p>\n	Jaume is specialized in animal models of exercise and stress, as well as expert in behavioural assessment. He has been recently incorporated to the research technician team of our Institute.</p>\n<p>\n	As a researcher, he has collaborated with Rosa M&ordf; Escorihuela, PhD on healthy lifestyle using animal models, focusing on exercise and cafeteria diet. Nowadays, he is interested in comparative psychology between rodents and humans as well as environmental factors to improve health like green exercise.</p>\n','<p>\n	See all Jaume F. Lalanza publications at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=Lalanza%20JF%5BAuthor%5D\">PubMed</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	<em><u>Selected publications</u></em></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26538081\"><strong>Long-term moderate treadmill exercise promotes stress-coping strategies in male and female rats.</strong></a><br />\n	Lalanza JF, Sanchez-Roige S, Cigarroa I, Gagliano H, Fuentes S, Armario A, Capdevila L, Escorihuela RM.<br />\n	Sci Rep. 2015 Nov 5;5:16166. doi: 10.1038/srep16166.</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25129573\"><strong>Long-term wheel running changes on sensorimotor activity and skeletal muscle in male and female mice of accelerated senescence.</strong></a><br />\n	Sanchez-Roige S,&nbsp;Lalanza JF, Alvarez-L&oacute;pez MJ, Cos&iacute;n-Tom&aacute;s M, Gri&ntilde;an-Ferr&eacute; C, Pall&agrave;s M, Kaliman P, Escorihuela RM.<br />\n	Age (Dordr). 2014;36(5):9697. doi: 10.1007/s11357-014-9697-1</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24482678\"><strong>Effects of a post-weaning cafeteria diet in young rats: metabolic syndrome, reduced activity and low anxiety-like behaviour.</strong></a><br />\n	Lalanza JF, Caimari A, del Bas JM, Torregrosa D, Cigarroa I, Pall&agrave;s M, Capdevila L, Arola L, Escorihuela RM.<br />\n	PLoS One. 2014 Jan 15;9(1):e85049. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0085049.</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22472479\"><strong>Physiological and behavioural consequences of long-term moderate treadmill exercise.</strong></a><br />\n	Lalanza JF, Sanchez-Roige S, Gagliano H, Fuentes S, Bayod S, Camins A, Pall&agrave;s M, Armario A, Escorihuela RM.<br />\n	Psychoneuroendocrinology. 2012 Nov;37(11):1745-54. doi: 10.1016/j.psyneuen.2012.03.008.</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21624506\"><strong>Neurophysiological and epigenetic effects of physical exercise on the aging process.</strong></a><br />\n	Kaliman P, P&aacute;rrizas M,&nbsp;Lalanza JF, Camins A, Escorihuela RM, Pall&agrave;s M.<br />\n	Ageing Res Rev. 2011 Sep;10(4):475-86. doi: 10.1016/j.arr.2011.05.002</p>\n',NULL),(248,21,0,'Antonio Luis','Florido Torres',NULL,'M1 122','','+34 935 868 248','AntonioLuis.Florido@uab.cat',NULL,'248antonioflorido.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(250,22,22,'e','e',NULL,'e','e','e','e',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(251,22,22,'e','e',NULL,'e','e','e','e',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(252,0,0,'','',NULL,'','','','',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(253,0,0,'','',NULL,'','','','',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(254,14,0,'Elisabet','Meg