>\n					<a href=\"index.php#!/Victor J. Yuste_439_1 \"><span style=\"color:#000000;\">Victor Yuste</span></a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\n				&nbsp;</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',1,1,2),(371,44,0,'Hospitals','<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.vhebron.net/es\" target=\"_blank\">Vall d&#39;Hebron</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.gencat.cat/ics/germanstrias/\" target=\"_blank\">Germans Trias i Pujol (Can Ruti)</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.santpau.es/\" target=\"_blank\">Santa Creu i Sant Pau</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.guttmann.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Institut Guttman</a></p>\n',0,2,2),(372,46,0,'Neurodegeneration and Ageing','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Alzheimer&#39;s disease, Parkinson&#39;s disease, cerebral ischemia, and ageing are characterized by the loss or malfunction of neural cells and circuitries. An important idea is that, despite the very disparate disease etiologies, common mechanisms damage and kill cells. Some of our groups thus study inflammation, oxidative stress or apoptosis in the hopes that understanding common deleterious pathways will result in treatments for several pathologies at once. In addition, newcomers to the Institute have raised the local temperature by bringing exciting research on novel cell signaling pathways leading to neurodegeneration: presenilins and kinases. Last, honest to God we do not dare to question the importance of neurons, but several groups at the Institute have long struggled to take other brain cells, namely glia and vascular cells, to the spotlight in the belief that normal and pathological brain function derives from the intricate interaction of all brain cells.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(396,1); \">Bernardo Castellano- Research Group in Glial Cells.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(400,1);\">Jes&uacute;s Giraldo - Laboratory of Molecular Neuropharmacology and Bioinformatics</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(401,1); \">Juan Hidalgo- Neuroinflammation and Oxidative Stress.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(402,1); \">Jos&eacute; M. Lizcano-Cell Signalling mechanisms in health and metabolic, mental and cancer diseases</a><a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(406,1); \"><br />\n	Jos&eacute; Rodr&iacute;guez- Biomedical research group in neurodegeneration</a><a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(407,1); \"><br />\n	Patrocinio Vergara- Research Group for the study of Digestive Motility and its Alteration in Chronic Diseases.</a></div>\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/index.php#!/Research%20Group%20in%20Demyelinating%20Autoimmune%20Diseases_741_1\" target=\"_blank\">Miguel Chillon- Research Group in Demyelinating Autoimmune Diseases</a></div>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<strong>Other groups:</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"index.php#!/Albert Badia &amp; Victoria Clos_410_1 \">Albert Badia and Victoria Clos</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(416,1);\">Ester Fernandez</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(419,1); \">Lydia Gimenez Llort </a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(437,1); \">Mercedes Unzeta</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(438,1); \">Elisabeth Vila</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(439,1);\">Victor Yuste</a><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',1,2,2),(373,46,0,'Neuroregeneration and repair','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Alterations of the peripheral nervous system range from neuropathies caused by certain diseases to spinal cord injury caused by accidents. As of today treatment if difficult and prognosis poor. Researchers at the INc in collaboration with the Institut Guttmann strive to find ways to heal or regenerate nerves, or alleviate secondary effects like neuropathic pain. Strategies under scrutiny are electrical stimulation, cell therapy with enseathing glia or stem cells, or treatment with neurotrophic factors including, as exotic as it may sound, tetanus toxin.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(404,1); \">Jes&uacute;s Giraldo - Laboratory of Molecular Neuropharmacology and Bioinformatics<br />\n	Xavier Navarro- Neuroplasticity and Regeneration.</a><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Other groups:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(431,1)\">Olga Pol</a></div>\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/index.php#!/Assumpci%C3%B3%20Bosch_755_1\">Assumpci&oacute; Bosch</a><br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</div>\n',2,2,2),(374,46,0,'Behavioural Neuroscience','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	A major challenge in the neurosciences today is understanding the mechanisms underlying memory, learning and cognition. A group at the INc undertake this major task from an interesting angle: they look at neural systems endowed with an amazing capacity to facilitate memory formation to the point that their activation can reverse cognitive deficits. They painstakingly explore the molecular and cellular elements of these natural memory enhancing circuitries, and the potential to stimulate them therapeutically. Other groups are interested in mind disorders that seem to plague our times: stress, addiction, psychosis and anxiety. How certain brain circuitries are changed by noxious experience to provoke long-lasting alterations of behaviour, why some individuals may be predisposed to anxiety, or can addiction be treated with a drug are questions under investigation. Answers will come from biochemical psychopharmacology<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/html/neuropharma.html?phpMyAdmin=6504f225ad58155cb3ac9c08159f566e\" title=\"Related Groups\"> </a>fine profiling of genes encoding for individual traits, or the analysis of the epigenetics of memory, which are among other state-of-the art approaches pursued at the Institute.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(395,1);\">Antonio Armario- Neurobiology of Stress and Addiction.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(399,1);\">Alberto Fernandez Teruel- Animal and Human Models in Mental Disorders.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(400,1);\">Jes&uacute;s Giraldo - Laboratory of Molecular Neuropharmacology and Bioinformatics</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(403,1); \">Margarita Mart&iacute;- Memory Potentiation and Recovery in Normal and Brain Damaged Rats.</a><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Other groups:</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(415,1);\">Rosa Maria Escorihuela </a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(430,1); \">Marc Pallar&egrave;s A&ntilde;&oacute;</a></p>\n',3,2,2),(376,51,0,'Hospitales','<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.vhebron.net/es\" target=\"_blank\">Vall d&#39;Hebron</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.gencat.cat/ics/germanstrias/\" target=\"_blank\">Germans Trias i Pujol (Can Ruti)</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.santpau.es/\" target=\"_blank\">Santa Creu i Sant Pau</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.guttmann.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Institut Guttman</a></p>\n',0,2,1),(377,52,0,'Neurodegeneración y envejecimiento','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	La enfermedad de Alzheimer, la enfermedad de Parkinson, la isquemia cerebral, y el envejecimiento se caracterizan por la p&eacute;rdida o el mal funcionamiento de las c&eacute;lulas y los circuitos neuronales. Una idea importante es que, aunque la etiolog&iacute;a de las enfermedades es muy dispar, los mecanismos de da&ntilde;o y muerte celular podr&iacute;an ser similares. As&iacute;, algunos de nuestros grupos estudian la inflamaci&oacute;n, el estr&eacute;s oxidativo o la apoptosis con la esperanza de que la comprensi&oacute;n com&uacute;n de las v&iacute;as nocivas se traduzca en un mismo tratamiento para diversas patolog&iacute;as. Adem&aacute;s, los reci&eacute;n llegados al Instituto han incrementado la temperatura local llevando una excitante investigaci&oacute;n en nuevas v&iacute;as de se&ntilde;alizaci&oacute;n que conducen a la neurodegeneraci&oacute;n: presenilinas y quinasas. Finalmente, aunque no nos atrevemos a cuestionar la importancia de las neuronas, varios grupos del Instituto han centrado su atenci&oacute;n en otras tipos celulares, principalmente en las c&eacute;lulas gliales y vasculares, con la convicci&oacute;n de que la funci&oacute;n cerebral normal y patol&oacute;gica deriva de la intrincada interacci&oacute;n de todas las c&eacute;lulas del cerebro.</p>\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(382,1); \"><br />\n	Bernardo Castellano- Grupo de Investigaci&oacute;n en C&eacute;lulas Gliales.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(387,1); \">Jes&uacute;s Giraldo- Laboratorio de Neurofarmacolog&iacute;a molecular y Bioinformatica</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(388,1); \">Juan Hidalgo- Neuroinflamaci&oacute;n y Estr&eacute;s Oxidativo.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(389,1); \">Jos&eacute; M. Lizcano- Cell Signalling mechanisms in health and metabolic, mental and cancer diseases</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(393,1); \">Jos&eacute; Rodr&iacute;guez- Grupo de investigaci&oacute;n biom&eacute;dica en neurodegeneraci&oacute;n</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(394,1); \">Patrocinio Vergara- Estudio de la Motilidad Digestiva y su Alteraci&oacute;n en las Enfermedades Cr&oacute;nicas.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/Castellano/index.php#%21/Miguel%20Chill%C3%B3n_752_1\">Miguel Chill&oacute;n</a><a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/Castellano/index.php#!/Grupo%20de%20Investigaci%C3%B3n%20para%20Enfermedades%20Autoinmunes%20Desmielinizantes_740_1\" target=\"_blank\"> - Grupo de Investigaci&oacute;n para Enfermedades Autoinmunes Desmielinizantes</a><br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Otros grupos:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"index.php#!/Albert Badia y Victoria Clos_443_1 \">Albert Badia y Victoria Clos</a><a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(449,1);\"><br />\n	Ester Fernandez</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(452,1); \">Lydia Gimenez Llort </a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(470,1); \">Mercedes Unzeta</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(471,1); \">Elisabeth Vila</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(472,1); \">Victor Yuste</a></div>\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',1,2,1),(378,52,0,'Neuroregeneración y reparación','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Las alteraciones del sistema nervioso perif&eacute;rico van desde neuropat&iacute;as causadas por ciertas enfermedades hasta lesiones de la m&eacute;dula espinal causadas por accidentes. Actualmente el tratamiento de estas patolog&iacute;as es dif&iacute;cil y de mal pron&oacute;stico. Los investigadores del INc en colaboraci&oacute;n con el Instituto Guttmann se esfuerzan por encontrar maneras de curar y regenerar nervios, o bien aliviar los efectos secundarios, como el dolor neurop&aacute;tico. Algunas de las estrategias utilizadas son la estimulaci&oacute;n el&eacute;ctrica, la terapia celular con implantaci&oacute;n de c&eacute;lulas gliales o celulas madre, o el tratamiento con factores neurotr&oacute;ficos incluyendo, aunque pueda parecer ex&oacute;tico, la toxina tet&aacute;nica.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(391,1);\"><br />\n	</a><a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(391,1); \">Jes&uacute;s Giraldo- Laboratorio de Neurofarmacolog&iacute;a molecular y Bioinformatica<br />\n	Xavier Navarro- Neuroplasticidad y Regeneraci&oacute;n</a></p>\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<strong>Otros grupos:<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(464,1); \">Olga Pol</a></div>\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/Castellano/index.php#!/Assumpci%C3%B3%20Bosch_757_1\">Assumpci&oacute; Bosch</a></div>\n',2,2,1),(379,52,0,'Neurociencia conductual','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Un reto importante en la neurociencia de hoy es comprender los mecanismos subyacentes a la memoria, aprendizaje y cognici&oacute;n memoria, el aprendizaje y la cognici&oacute;n. Un grupo en el INc trabaja en esta importante tarea desde un punto de vista interesante: contemplan los sistemas neurales dotados de una sorprendente capacidad para facilitar la formaci&oacute;n de la memoria hasta el punto que su activaci&oacute;n pueda revertir el d&eacute;ficit cognitivo. Exploran cuidadosamente los elementos moleculares y celulares de estos circuitos para mejorar la memoria natural, y el potencial de estimularlos terap&eacute;uticamente. Otros grupos est&aacute;n interesados en los trastornos de la mente que parecen ser la plaga de nuestro tiempo: el estr&eacute;s, adicci&oacute;n, psicosis&nbsp;y ansiedad. C&oacute;mo determinados circuitos cerebrales son cambiados por experiencias nocivas provocando alteraciones a largo plazo en el comportamiento, por qu&eacute; algunos individuos podr&iacute;an estar predispuestos a la ansiedad, o si la adicci&oacute;n puede ser tratada con f&aacute;rmacos, son cuestiones objeto de investigaci&oacute;n. Las respuestas llegar&aacute;n de la psicofarmacolog&iacute;a bioqu&iacute;mica, de un cuidadoso an&aacute;lisis de perfiles de genes que codifican rasgos individuales, o bien del an&aacute;lisis de la epigen&eacute;tica de la memoria, que son algunas de las aproximaciones t&eacute;cnicas que se llevar&aacute;n a cabo en el Instituto.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<strong><strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(381,1); \">Antonio Armario- Neurobiolog&iacute;a del Estr&eacute;s y la Adicci&oacute;n.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(386,1); \">Alberto Fernandez Teruel- Modelos Animales y Humanos en Transtornos Mentales.</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(387,1); \">Jes&uacute;s Giraldo - Laboratorio de Neurofarmacolog&iacute;a molecular y Bioinformatica</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(390,1); \">Margarita Mart&iacute;- Potenciaci&oacute;n y Recuperaci&oacute;n de la Memoria en Ratas normales y con Da&ntilde;o Cerebral.</a><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<strong>Otros grupos:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(448,1); \">Rosa Mar&iacute;a Escorihuela </a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(463,1); \">Marc Pallar&egrave;s A&ntilde;&oacute;</a></p>\n',3,2,1),(381,52,0,'Antonio Armario- Neurobiología del Estrés y la Adicción','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2009-0019<br />\n	<br />\n	</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Coordinador del Grupo:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Antonio Armario Garc&iacute;a<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(442,1); \">- Antonio Armario Garc&iacute;a y Roser Nadal Alemany</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/NewPage/DocsCKeditor/images/ArmNadef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',5,2,1),(382,52,0,'Bernardo Castellano- Grupo de Investigación en Células Gliales','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-1464<br />\n	<br />\n	</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Coordinador del grupo:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Bernardo Castellano L&oacute;pez<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(445,1); \">- Bernardo Castellano L&oacute;pez y Berta Gonz&aacute;lez de Mingo</a><br />\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/sgr b.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n',6,2,1),(386,52,0,'Alberto Fernández Teruel- Modelos Animales y Humanos en Transtornos Mentales','<p>\n	<strong>Coordinador del Grupo:</strong> Alberto Fern&aacute;ndez Teruel<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N</strong>:<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(450,1); \">- Alberto Fern&aacute;ndez Teruel</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(469,1); \">- Rafael Torrubia Beltri</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/SGRAFernandezA1_opt.jpg\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 266px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	Los intereses y la actividad de investigaci&oacute;n de nuestro grupo se centran, de manera general, en el estudio de los procesos/mecanismos psicol&oacute;gicos, neurobiol&oacute;gicos y neurogen&eacute;ticos implicados en la vulnerabilidad a diversos trastornos mentales, principalmente &ndash;pero no exclusivamente- aquellos m&aacute;s relacionados con la ansiedad (los miedos y la ansiedad patol&oacute;gica, el estr&eacute;s, la depresi&oacute;n), procesos atencionales y la impulsividad/compulsividad. Con esta perspectiva de dar valor translacional a la investigaci&oacute;n de nuestro grupo-SGR, tanto a trav&eacute;s de modelos animales como experimentales con humanos, estudiamos los posibles mecanismos que intervienen en la g&eacute;nesis, en el mantenimiento y en el posible tratamiento efectivo de estos trastornos. Un ejemplo reciente del valor translacional de esta investigaci&oacute;n es la confirmaci&oacute;n de la asociaci&oacute;n del gen CTNND2 con los trastornos de ansiedad en pacientes humanos (Nivard et al. GENES, BRAIN and BEHAVIOR, 13: 195-201, 2014), poco despu&eacute;s que este gen fuera propuesto como candidato a &ldquo;gen cuantitativo&rdquo; para la ansiedad en un trabajo de nuestro grupo realizado en ratas Baud et al &ndash;Rat Genome Sequencing and Mapping Consortium- , NATURE GENETICS, 45: 767-775, 2013).</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-1587</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',9,2,1),(387,52,0,'Jesús Giraldo- Laboratorio de Neurofarmacología molecular y Bioinformatica','<p>\n	<strong>Coordinador del grupo:</strong> Jes&uacute;s Giraldo<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N</strong>:<br />\n	- <a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(453,1); \">Jes&uacute;s Giraldo </a><br />\n	- <a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(462,1);\">Jordi Ortiz, Josefa Sabri&agrave; y Carles Gil</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/DSC00227.JPG\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	El Laboratorio de Neurofarmacolog&iacute;a Molecular y Bioinform&aacute;tica se compone de dos ramas: la rama computacional (Dr. Giraldo, Dr. Dalton y Dr. Roche) y la rama experimental (Dr. Ortiz, Dr. Sabri&agrave; y Dr. Gil). La rama computacional desarrolla modelos matem&aacute;ticos y moleculares de alosterismo y oligomerizaci&oacute;n de receptores acoplados a prote&iacute;nas G. Esta investigaci&oacute;n est&aacute; contribuyendo al dise&ntilde;o de mol&eacute;culas moduladoras de los receptores metabotr&oacute;picos de glutamato, en particular mol&eacute;culas fotomoduladoras. La rama experimental estudia el entorno lip&iacute;dico de los receptores y obtiene evidencias de la presencia de asociaciones oligom&eacute;ricas de receptores y del papel funcional de las mismas. La combinaci&oacute;n de estas dos aproximaciones constituye una poderosa estrategia de auto-retroalimentaci&oacute;n dentro del grupo orientada a proporcionar ciencia de la m&aacute;s alta calidad con potencial transferencia a la industria. Los olig&oacute;meros de los receptores metabotr&oacute;picos de glutamato son relevantes para el desarrollo de tratamientos para el dolor neurop&aacute;tico, esquizofrenia, adicci&oacute;n a las drogas y otros trastornos psiqui&aacute;tricos y neurol&oacute;gicos.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-1226</strong></span></p>\n',10,2,1),(388,52,0,'Juan Hidalgo- Neuroinflamación y Estrés Oxidativo','<p>\n	<strong>Coordinador del&nbsp; Grupo:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Juan Hidalgo Pareja<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"index.php#!/Juan Hidalgo_455_1\">- Juan Hidalgo Pareja</a><br />\n	<a href=\"index.php#!/Albert QUINTANA ROMERO_675_1\">- Albert Quintana Romero</a><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	La expresi&oacute;n de diferentes citosinas en el cerebro est&aacute; alterada en una gran variedad de patolog&iacute;as con un claro componente neuroinflamatorio como la esclerosis m&uacute;ltiple (EM) y la enfermedad de Alzheimer (EA). Si la presencia y/o alteraciones de citosinas en estos estados patol&oacute;gicos son causa o consecuencia, o si son importantes en el desarrollo y progresi&oacute;n de las alteraciones cl&iacute;nicas, son aspectos a&uacute;n desconocidos pero de importancia capital en el diagn&oacute;stico, tratamiento y prevenci&oacute;n. Con el fin de avanzar en estos estudios, los experimentos realizados en modelos animales de EM (EAE) y EA (Tg2576 y otros) son fundamentales. Nuestro grupo est&aacute; interesado en estudiar el papel de una de las principales citosinas, la interleucina-6 (IL-6), mediante diversos modelos de ratones transg&eacute;nicos. Otro de nuestros objetivos es el estudio de inhibidores selectivos de la fosfodiesterasa del cGMP tipo 5 (PDE5-Is), como el sildenafilo (Viagra &reg;), tratamientos que combinan efectos inmunomoduladores y neuroprotectores y que son beneficiosos para la EM. Finalmente, tambi&eacute;n nos interesan las enfermedades mitocondriales en general y el S&iacute;ndrome de Leigh (LS) en particular, mediante modelos de ratones transg&eacute;nicos con alteraciones de prote&iacute;nas mitocondriales y desarrollando estrategias terap&eacute;uticas como el uso de inhibidores de la quinasa mTOR.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-0709</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',11,2,1),(389,52,0,'José M. Lizcano- Cell Signalling mechanisms in health and metabolic, mental and cancer diseases','<p>\n	<strong>Coordinador del Grupo:</strong>&nbsp; Jos&eacute; M. Lizcano de Vega<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(444,1); \">- Jos&eacute; R. Bayascas Ram&iacute;rez</a><br />\n	- Enrique Claro y Fernando Picatoste<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(457,1); \">- Jos&eacute; M. Lizcano de Vega y N&eacute;stor G&oacute;mez Trias</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(458,1); \">- Jos&eacute; M. L&oacute;pez Blanco</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/SGRJMLizcano_para_INc.jpg\" style=\"width: 450px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-1621</strong></span></p>\n',12,2,1),(390,52,0,'Margarita Martí- Potenciación y Recuperación de la Memoria en Ratas Normales y con Daño Cerebral','<p>\n	<strong>Coordinadora del Grupo:</strong> Margarita Mart&iacute;<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(454,1); \">- Gemma Guillazo Blanch</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(465,1); \">- Isabel Portell Cort&eacute;s</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(468,1); \">- Pilar Segura Torres</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/sgr imorg.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>1. </strong><strong>Potenciaci&oacute;n de la atenci&oacute;n y la memoria en modelos animales de d&eacute;ficit cognitivo por envejecimiento o lesi&oacute;n cerebral.</strong><br />\n	Nuestro grupo de investigaci&oacute;n&nbsp; tiene como principal objetivo investigar en ratas de diferentes edades, tanto adultas como envejecidas, los efectos de tratamientos moduladores de la actividad glutamat&eacute;rgica (a trav&eacute;s de receptores AMPA o NMDA) sobre el aprendizaje y la memoria y los mecanismos neurofisiol&oacute;gicos subyacentes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>2.</strong> <strong>Efectos del ejercicio f&iacute;sico sobre el d&eacute;ficit de memoria en un modelo animal de da&ntilde;o cerebral traum&aacute;tico.</strong><br />\n	El objetivo de esta investigaci&oacute;n es establecer las condiciones (demora despu&eacute;s de la lesi&oacute;n, duraci&oacute;n del tratamiento, etc) en las que el ejercicio f&iacute;sico es capaz de reducir el d&eacute;ficit cognitivo producido por da&ntilde;o cerebral traum&aacute;tico, y determinar los mecanismos neurobiol&oacute;gicos asociados a esta recuperaci&oacute;n.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>3. Potenciaci&oacute;n cognitiva mediante estimulaci&oacute;n cerebral reforzante (AEIC): conducta, plasticidad sin&aacute;ptica y neurog&eacute;nesis.</strong><br />\n	El objetivo general de nuestro grupo de investigaci&oacute;n incluye, por una parte, seguir explorando el potencial terap&eacute;utico de la AEIC en diferentes tipos de memoria en ratas sanas y en modelos&nbsp; experimentales de amnesia y, por otra, profundizar en el estudio de los mecanismos moleculares, morfol&oacute;gicos y neuroqu&iacute;micos en estructuras como el hipocampo, la am&iacute;gdala o la neocorteza cerebral,&nbsp; que pudieran explicar los efectos potenciadores de la AEIC sobre la memoria.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-0511</strong></span></p>\n',13,2,1),(391,52,0,'Xavier Navarro- Neuroplasticidad y Regeneración','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref SGR2009-1509</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Coordinador del Grupo:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(461,1); \">-Xavier Navarro Acebes</a><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	- Caty Casas Louzao<br />\n	- Rub&egrave;n L&oacute;pez Vales<br />\n	- Esther Udina Bonet</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/XNavarro2014.JPG\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n',14,2,1),(393,52,0,'José Rodríguez- Grupo de investigación biomédica en Neurodegeneración- REBINE','<p>\n	<strong>Coordinador del Grupo:</strong> Jos&eacute; Rodr&iacute;guez &Aacute;lvarez<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(441,1); \">- Jos&eacute; Aguilera &Aacute;vila</a><br />\n	- <a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/Castellano/index.php#!/Carlos%20BARCIA%20GONZ%C3%81LEZ_663_1\" target=\"_self\">Carlos Barcia Gonz&aacute;lez</a><br />\n	- <a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(584,1); \">Elena Galea y Roser Masgrau Juanola</a><br />\n	-<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(467,1); \"> Carlos A. Saura Antol&iacute;n</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(466,1);\">- Jos&eacute; Rodr&iacute;guez &Aacute;lvarez</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/sgr pepe.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Nuestro grupo de investigaci&oacute;n est&aacute; interesado en los mecanismos que controlan la disfunci&oacute;n sin&aacute;ptica y la muerte /&nbsp; supervivencia neuronal en las&nbsp; enfermedades neurodegenerativas y otras patolog&iacute;as con la p&eacute;rdida neuronal. Conocer estos mecanismos es un requisito fundamental para dise&ntilde;ar nuevas estrategias terap&eacute;uticas para estas enfermedades. En nuestro grupo hemos centrado nuestra investigaci&oacute;n asociada a enfermedades neurodegenerativas mediante un proyecto global que se divide en tres aspectos: 1) El desarrollo y el uso de modelos animales y cultivos celulares para el estudio de las enfermedades neurodegenerativas; 2) B&uacute;squeda de nuevas dianas moleculares con inter&eacute;s terap&eacute;utico; 3) Desarrollo de nuevas estrategias terap&eacute;uticas. Para los pr&oacute;ximos a&ntilde;os estaremos centrados principalmente en la enfermedad de Alzheimer.<br />\n	La enfermedad de Alzheimer (AD) es la forma m&aacute;s com&uacute;n de demencia senil. Es una enfermedad compleja, posiblemente multifactorial en la que la disfunci&oacute;n cognitiva precede y acompa&ntilde;a a la neurodegeneraci&oacute;n. Por lo tanto, es de vital importancia conocer tanto las causas moleculares que desencadenan la enfermedad en las primeras etapas, ya que esto podr&iacute;a conducir a un mejor enfoque terap&eacute;utico y un diagn&oacute;stico m&aacute;s precoz y eficaz, como la identificaci&oacute;n de los elementos clave que participan en la respuesta inflamatoria y la neurodegeneraci&oacute;n. La investigaci&oacute;n de los mecanismos implicados as&iacute; como la b&uacute;squeda de nuevas dianas moleculares se centra en los siguientes aspectos:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>La desregulaci&oacute;n de los receptores sin&aacute;pticos para el&nbsp; glutamato es un mecanismo implicado en las alteraciones sin&aacute;pticas observadas en las primeras etapas de la enfermedad de Alzheimer.<br />\n	<strong>2. </strong>CRTC1 y otros factores de transcripci&oacute;n est&aacute;n asociados con alteraciones gen&eacute;ticas en los trastornos cognitivos asociados con la enfermedad de Alzheimer.<br />\n	<strong>3. </strong>Fortalecimiento del papel de los astrocitos como elemento neuroprotector en la EA.<br />\n	<strong>4. </strong>La v&iacute;a de NO/cGMP es clave en la reactividad glial y la neuroinflamaci&oacute;n asociada con la AD.<br />\n	<strong>5.&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>La modulaci&oacute;n de la fagocitosis&nbsp; de las neuronas degeneradas por la microgl&iacute;a.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong><strong><span style=\"color:#800000;\">Ref SGR2014-0984</span></strong></strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',16,2,1),(394,52,0,'Patrocinio Vergara- Estudio de la Motilidad Digestiva y su Alteración en las Enfermedades Crónicas','<p>\n	<strong>Coordinadora del Grupo:</strong> Patrocinio Vergara Esteras<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>GRUPOS DE INVESTIGACI&Oacute;N:</strong><a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(456,1);\"><br />\n	-&nbsp; Marcel Jim&eacute;nez Farrerons</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(459,1)\">-&nbsp; Vicente Mart&iacute;nez Perea y Patrocinio Vergara Esteras</a><a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=185:vicente-martinez-patrocinio-vergara&amp;catid=46:grupos&amp;Itemid=112&amp;lang=es\" target=\"_blank\"><br />\n	</a></p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/sgrmartnez vergara325.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	El Grupo de&nbsp; Investigaci&oacute;n para el Estudio de la Motilidad Digestiva, reconocido como grupo de investigaci&oacute;n consolidado des del a&ntilde;o 1999, centra su actividad en el estudio de la motilidad digestiva y las alteraciones motores (dismotilidad) asociadas a diferentes patolog&iacute;as de car&aacute;cter cr&oacute;nico, como son la Enfermedad Inflamatoria Intestinal, el S&iacute;ndrome del Intestino Irritable, la diverticulosis, enfermedades neurodegenerativas o los trastornos motores de la degluci&oacute;n o la defecaci&oacute;n. Los estudios, realizados tanto en modelos animales como en muestras de tejido humano, as&iacute; como los estudios cl&iacute;nicos tienen como objetivo profundizar en el conocimiento de la etiopatogenia de la dismotilidad y el desarrollo de nuevas dianas terap&eacute;uticas. Objetivos espec&iacute;ficos del grupo son: la influencia de la microbiota y del sistema inmune en la sensibilidad visceral, el estudio de la inervaci&oacute;n purin&eacute;rgica, los trastornos de la degluci&oacute;n en el anciano y en pacientes con enfermedades neurol&oacute;gicas y los trastornos motores cr&oacute;nicos en el colon.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-0789</strong></span></p>\n',17,2,1),(395,46,0,'Antonio Armario- Neurobiology of Stress and Addiction','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2009-0019</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Group coordinator:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Antonio Armario Garc&iacute;a<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(409,1); \"><br />\n	- Antonio Armario Garc&iacute;a &amp; Roser Nadal Alemany</a></p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/armsgr325.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n',5,2,2),(396,46,0,'Bernardo Castellano- Research Group in Glial Cells','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-1464</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Group coordinator:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Bernardo Castellano L&oacute;pez<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(412,1); \">- Bernardo Castellano L&oacute;pez &amp; Berta Gonz&aacute;lez de Mingo</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/sgr b.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n',6,2,2),(399,46,0,'Alberto Fernández Teruel- Animal and Human Models in Mental Disorders','<p>\n	<strong>Group coordinator:&nbsp; </strong>Alberto Fern&aacute;ndez Teruel<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(417,1); \">- Alberto Fern&aacute;ndez Teruel</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(436,1); \">- Rafael Torrubia Beltri</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/SGRAFernandezA1_opt.jpg\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 266px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	Our interests and research activity are focussed, in general, on the study of the psychological, neurobiological and neurogenetics processes related to mental disorder&rsquo;s vulnerability, especially those involving anxiety, attention or impulsivity. Aiming to give a translational approach to our research group-SGR, we study -both in animal models and in human- the mechanisms involved in the genesis, maintenance and treatment of these disorders. An example of this translational approach is the confirmation of the relation between the gen CTNND2 and the anxiety disorder in human (Nivard et al. GENES, BRAIN and BEHAVIOR, 13: 195-201, 2014), after this gen had been proposed, in a previous study we did in rates, as a quantitative gen for anxiety (Baud et al &ndash;Rat Genome Sequencing and Mapping Consortium- , NATURE GENETICS, 45: 767-775, 2013).</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-1587</strong></span></p>\n',9,2,2),(400,46,0,'Jesús Giraldo- Laboratory of Molecular Neuropharmacology and Bioinformatics','<p>\n	<strong>Group coordinator:</strong> Jes&uacute;s Giraldo<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	- <a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(420,1);\">Jes&uacute;s Giraldo </a><br />\n	- <a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(429,1)\">Jordi Ortiz, Josefa Sabri&agrave; and Carles Gil</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/DSC00227.JPG\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	The Laboratory of Molecular Neuropharmacology and Bioinformatics is composed of two branches: computational (Dr. Giraldo, Dr. Dalton and Dr. Roche) and experimental (Dr. Ortiz, Dr. Sabri&agrave; and Dr. Gil). The computational branch develops mathematical and molecular modelling of G protein-coupled receptor allosterism and oligomerization. This work is contributing to drug design of metabotropic glutamate receptor modulators, in particular photomodulators. The experimental branch studies the lipid raft environment of receptors and obtains evidence of their assembly forming oligomers in tissue and their functional role. The combination of these two approaches constitutes a powerful strategy of self-feedback within the group oriented to provide solid science of the highest impact and quality for transfer to academy and industry. Metabotropic glutamate receptor oligomers are relevant for the development of treatments for neuropathic pain, schizophrenia, drug addiction and other psychiatric and neurological disorders.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-1226</strong></span><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',10,2,2),(401,46,0,'Juan Hidalgo- Neuroinflammation and Oxidative Stress','<p>\n	<strong>Group coordinator:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Juan Hidalgo Pareja<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"index.php#!/Juan Hidalgo_422_1\">- Juan Hidalgo Pareja</a><br />\n	<a href=\"index.php#!/Albert QUINTANA ROMERO_674_1 \">- Albert Quintana Romero</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	The expression of several cytokines in the brain is altered in a number of human pathologies with a clear neuroinflammatory component such as multiple sclerosis (MS) and Alzheimer disease (AD). If the presence and/or alterations of cytokines in these pathologies are a cause or a consequence, or if they are important in the development and progression of the clinical alterations, are poorly known aspects but of critical importance in the diagnosis, treatment and prevention. In order to gain insight in these studies, experiments carried out in animal models of MS (EAE) and AD (Tg2576 and others) are essential. Our grup is interested in studying the role of one of the main cytokines, interleukin-6 (IL-6), by means of several models of transgenic mice. Another objective is the study of selective inhibitors of the cGMP phosphodiesterase type 5 (PDE5-Is), such as sildenafil (Viagra &reg;), treatments that combine immunomodulatory and neuroprotective effects and that are beneficial for MS. Finally, we are also interested in the mitochondrial diseases in general and the Leigh Syndrome (LS) in particular, by means of transgenic mice models with alterations of mitochondrial proteins and the development of terapeutic strategies such as the use of inhibitors of the mTOR kinase.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-0709</strong></span></p>\n',11,2,2),(402,46,0,'José M. Lizcano- Cell Signalling mechanisms in health and metabolic, mental and cancer diseases','<p>\n	<strong>Group coordinator:</strong>&nbsp; Jos&eacute; M. Lizcano de Vega<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(411,1); \">- Jos&eacute; R. Bayascas Ram&iacute;rez</a><br />\n	- Enrique Claro &amp; Fernando Picatoste<br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(424,1); \">- Jos&eacute; M. Lizcano de Vega &amp; N&eacute;stor G&oacute;mez Trias</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(425,1); \">- Jos&eacute; M. L&oacute;pez Blanco</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/SGRJMLizcano_para_INc(1).jpg\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 219px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-1621</strong></span></p>\n',12,2,2),(403,46,0,'Margarita Martí- Memory Potentiation and Recovery in Normal and Brain damaged Rats','<p>\n	<strong>Group coordinator:</strong> Margarita Mart&iacute;<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(421,1); \">- Gemma Guillazo Blanch</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(432,1);\">- Isabel Portell Cort&eacute;s</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(435,1); \">- Pilar Segura Torres</a><br />\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/sgr imorg.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>1. Attentional and memory enhancement in animal models of cognitive impairment resulting from the normal process of ageing or induced by brain lesions. </strong><br />\n	By using rats with different ages, both young and old, the main goal of our research group is to study the effects that glutamate modulating treatments (via AMPA or NMDA receptors) have on learning and memory as well as the underlying neurophysiologic substrates.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>2. Effects</strong><strong>of physical exercise on memory deficits in an animal model of traumatic brain injury.</strong><br />\n	The objectiveof this research is to establish the conditions (delay after injury, duration of treatment, etc.) in which physical exercise can reduce cognitive deficits produced by traumatic brain injury, and to determine the neurobiological mechanisms associated with this recovery.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>3. Cognitive enhancement by deep brain rewarding stimulation (ICSS): behavior, synaptic plasticity and neurogenesis.</strong><br />\n	Our research group intends, on the one hand, further explore the therapeutic potential of ICSS treatment in different kind of memory in healthy rats and in experimental models of amnesia and, secondly, further study of the molecular, morphological and neurochemical mechanisms in structures such as the hippocampus, amygdala or the neocortex, which may explain the potentiating effect of ICSS on memory.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-0511</strong></span></p>\n',13,2,2),(404,46,0,'Xavier Navarro- Neuroplasticity and Regeneration','<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref SGR2009-1509</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Group coordinator:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(428,1); \"><br />\n	- Xavier Navarro Acebes</a><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	- Caty Casas Louzao<br />\n	- Rub&egrave;n L&oacute;pez Vales<br />\n	- Esther Udina Bonet</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/XNavarro2014.JPG\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n',14,2,2),(406,46,0,'José Rodríguez- Biomedical research group in Neurodegeneration REBINE','<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong> Jos&eacute; Rodr&iacute;guez &Aacute;lvarez<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(408,1); \">- Jos&eacute; Aguilera &Aacute;vila</a><br />\n	- <a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/index.php#!/Carlos%20BARCIA%20GONZ%C3%81LEZ_664_1\" target=\"_self\">Carlos Barcia Gonz&aacute;lez</a><br />\n	- <a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(585,1); \">Elena Galea and Roser Masgrau Juanola</a><br />\n	- <a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(434,1); \">Carlos A. Saura Antol&iacute;n</a><a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(433,1); \"><br />\n	- Jos&eacute; Rodr&iacute;guez &Aacute;lvarez</a><br />\n	<br />\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/sgr pepe.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Our research group is interested in the mechanisms that control synaptic dysfunction and death / neuronal survival in neurodegenerative diseases and other pathologies with neuronal loss. Knowing these mechanisms is a fundamental requirement to design new therapeutic approaches for these diseases. In our group we have focused our research associated to neurodegenerative diseases with an overall project that is divided into three aspects that the main focus of our research: 1) Development and use of animal models and cell cultures for the study of neurodegenerative diseases; 2) Search for new molecular targets with therapeutic interest; 3) Development of new therapeutic strategies. For the next years, we will continue to work in these last areas with focus on Alzheimer&#39;s disease.<br />\n	Alzheimer&#39;s disease (AD) is the most common form of senile dementia. It is a complex disease, possibly multifactorial in which cognitive dysfunction precedes and accompanies neurodegeneration. Therefore, it is vital to know both the molecular causes that trigger the disease in early stages, as this would lead to a better therapeutic approach and an earlier diagnosis and effective, and to identify the key elements involved in the inflammatory response and neurodegeneration. The investigation of the mechanisms involved as the search of new molecular targets is focused on the following aspects:<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>1. </strong>The deregulation of synaptic glutamate receptors is a mechanism involved in synaptic alterations observed in early stages of Alzheimer&#39;s disease.<br />\n	<strong>2. </strong>CRTC1 and other transcription factors regulators are associated with genetic alterations in cognitive disorders associated with Alzheimer&#39;s disease.<br />\n	<strong>3. </strong>Strengthening the role of astrocytes as neuroprotective element in the EA.<br />\n	<strong>4. </strong>NO/cGMP pathway is key in glial reactivity and neuroinflammation associated with AD.<br />\n	<strong>5.&nbsp; </strong>Modulation of phagocytosis by microglia of degenerating neurons.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong><span style=\"color:#800000;\">Ref SGR2014-0984</span></strong></p>\n',16,2,2),(407,46,0,'P.Vergara- Research Group for the Study of Digestive Motility and its Alteration in Chronic diseases','<p>\n	<strong>Group coordinator:</strong> Patrocinio Vergara Esteras<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>RESEARCH GROUPS:</strong><a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(423,1); \"><br />\n	-&nbsp; Marcel Jim&eacute;nez Farrerons</a><br />\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(426,1); \">-&nbsp; Vicente Mart&iacute;nez Perea&nbsp; &amp; Patrocinio Vergara Esteras</a><a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=185%3Avicente-martinez-patrocinio-vergara&amp;catid=46%3Agrupos&amp;Itemid=112&amp;lang=en&amp;phpMyAdmin=6504f225ad58155cb3ac9c08159f566e\" target=\"_blank\"><br />\n	</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/sgrmartnez vergara325.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	The Research Group for the Study of Gastrointestinal Motility, recognized as a research group since 1999, focuses on the study of gastrointestinal motility and its disorders (dismotility) associated with different chronic pathologies, such as Alzheimer, Inflammatory Bowel Disease, Irritable Bowel Syndrome, diverticulosis, neurodegenerative diseases or disorders &nbsp;of swallowing or defecation. The studies conducted both in animal models and in human tissue samples, as well as clinical studies aim to deep in the understanding of the pathogenesis of dismotility and the development of new therapeutic targets. Specific objectives of the group are: the influence of the microbiota and the immune system in visceral sensitivity, the study of purinergic innervation, swallowing disorders in the elderly and in patients with neurological pathologies and motor disorders in chronic colon.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Ref: SGR2014-0789</strong></span></p>\n',17,2,2),(408,45,0,'José Aguilera','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Molecular Neuroprotection Group</span></h2>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Jose Aguilera</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:jose.aguilera@uab.cat\">jose.aguilera@uab.cat&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 811 673</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-9906-8034\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6507775989\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jose_Aguilera3/publications\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"26\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"26\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/GrupJAguilera.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong><strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	</strong>Ana Candalija Iserte<br />\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/profile.php?id=212\">Laura Ortega</a><br />\n	Victoria <span>Palafox S&aacute;nchez</span></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Past members:</strong><br />\n	Roger Cub&iacute; Piqu&eacute;<br />\n	Carles Gil Gir&oacute;<br />\n	Daniel A. Mart&iacute;nez Quintero<br />\n	Natalia Moreno Galarza</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	Clostridial neurotoxins produce severe pathologies, such as tetanus and botulism. In spite of this, our Group studies the pharmacological potential of the most unexplored member of the family, tetanus toxin, and, especially, of the non-toxic C-terminal fragment of its heavy chain (Hc-TeTx). The Hc-TeTx, due to its characteristics of binding, internalization and retroaxonal transport, can be used as a vehicle to deliver compounds to the SNC. Moreover, our group described the neurotrophic action of this fragment, as well as the selective modulation of the serotonin transport fragment by Hc TeTx, therefore having a potential as antidepressant. Thus, our objective is to fully describe its protective capacity in front of stress-inducing agents in neuronal systems. In vivo and in vitro results lead us to propose Hc-TeTx as a neuroprotector agent in neurodegenerative pathologies and to study the signaling mechanisms related to the trophic capacity of the fragment.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	1. Identification of the high affinity receptors of the clostridial neurotoxins, their subcellular localization and their dynamic association with the cholesterol- and sphingolipid-enriched lipid domains (lipid rafts).<br />\n	<br />\n	2. Structural and compositional characterization of lipid rafts in different neuronal models and of their role in different events of the neuronal physiology.<br />\n	<br />\n	3. Determination of the pharmacological kinetics of the Hc-TeTx fragment as a proserotoninergic agent.<br />\n	<br />\n	4. Determination of the neuroprotective capacity of the Hc-TeTx in degenerative processes associated with mental diseases.<br />\n	<br />\n	5. Characterization of the neurotrophic action conducted by the Hc-TeTx fragment: evaluation of its therapeutic capacity in the treatment of neurodegenerative diseases.<br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>LATEST PUBLICATIONS&nbsp;</strong></span><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patricio-Mart&iacute;nez A,&nbsp;Mendieta L,&nbsp;Mart&iacute;nez I,&nbsp;Aguilera&nbsp;J,&nbsp;Lim&oacute;n ID.<br />\n	<em>The recombinant C-terminal fragment of tetanus toxin protects against cholinotoxicity by intraseptal injection of &beta;-amyloid peptide (25-35) in rats.</em> Neuroscience.&nbsp;<strong>2016</strong> Feb 19;315:18-30</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Candalija A, Cub&iacute; R,&nbsp; Ortega A, Aguilera J, and Gil C.<br />\n	<em>Trk receptors need neutral sphingomyelinase activity to promote cell viability.</em><br />\n	FEBS Letters<strong> </strong><strong>2014</strong>, 588: 167-174.(ISSN 0014-5793, Elsevier)</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mart&iacute;nez D, Garc&iacute;a L, Aguilera J and Ortega A.<br />\n	<em>An acute Glutamate exposure induces long-term down regulation of GLAST/EAAT1 uptake activity in cultured Bermann glia cells.</em><br />\n	Neurochemistry Research (In press <strong>2014</strong>).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Balderas A., Guillem A.M., Mart&iacute;nez-Lozada Z., Hern&aacute;ndez-Kelly L.C., Aguilera J. and Ortega A.<br />\n	<em>GLAST/EAAT1 regulation in cultured Bergmann glia cells: Role of the NO/cGMP signalling pathway.</em><br />\n	Neurochemistry International , In press<strong> 2014</strong>( ISSN 0197-0186, Elsevier BV, Netherlands &ndash; Scopus 2009: 74/303)</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp; &nbsp; Cub&iacute; R, Matas L.A. , Pou M. , Aguilera J. and C. Gil.<br />\n	<em>Differencial sensitivity to detergents of actin cytoskeleton from nerve endings.</em><br />\n	Biochimica et Biophysica Acta (Biomembranes) 1828: 2385-2393,<strong>2013</strong>(ISSN 0005-2736, Elsevier)<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830283/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more J. Aguilera in PubMed. </a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',18,2,2),(409,45,0,'Antonio Armario, Roser Nadal & Raül Andero','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(374,1)\">Neurobiology of the normal and disturbed mind</a></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Neurobiology of Stress and Addiction</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group Leaders:</strong><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<table style=\"width: 100%;\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Antonio Armario</td>\n			<td>\n				Roser Nadal</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 811 840</td>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 868 535</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:antonio.armario@uab.cat\">antonio.armario@uab.cat</a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:roser.nadal@uab.cat\">roser.nadal@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0001-9524-3635\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/ProfileView.action?SID=S1VOcsKWWHF8mvCPi46&amp;returnCode=ROUTER.Success&amp;queryString=KG0UuZjN5WkTEMnGFsnbmvjTPBd2a4rriGfK3U1Twjc%253D&amp;SrcApp=CR&amp;Init=Yes\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7005836750\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Antonio_Armario\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0001-8972-2525\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/C-7977-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6701731005\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Roser_Nadal2\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.mendeley.com/profiles/roser-nadal/\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"28\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/mendeley.png\" width=\"28\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<p>\n					&nbsp;</p>\n				<div>\n					Ra&uuml;l Andero Gal&iacute;</div>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:Raul.Andero@uab.cat\">Raul.Andero@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 813 342</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<table>\n									<tbody>\n										<tr>\n											<td>\n												<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0003-3641-8903\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n											<td>\n												&nbsp;</td>\n											<td>\n												<a href=\"https://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.uri?authorId=16066765200\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n											<td>\n												<a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Rauel_Andero_Gali\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n											<td>\n												<a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/ra%C3%BCl-andero-gal%C3%AD-2a177a46/en\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Linkedin.jpg\" style=\"width: 35px; height: 29px;\" /></a><a href=\"https://scholar.google.es/citations?view_op=list_works&amp;hl=es&amp;user=ORHEFhUAAAAJ\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/googlescholar.jpg\" width=\"31\" /></a></td>\n										</tr>\n									</tbody>\n								</table>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Untitled design(1).jpg\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 375px;\" /></p>\n<div>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong></div>\n<div>\n	Francesc Xavier Belda</div>\n<div>\n	In&eacute;s Cord&oacute;n</div>\n<div>\n	Silvia Fuentes</div>\n<div>\n	Humberto Gagliano</div>\n<div>\n	Juan Antonio Ortega</div>\n<div>\n	Jordi Pastor</div>\n<div>\n	Mar&iacute;a Sanch&iacute;s</div>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	Visit also: <a href=\"http://www.nea-uab.org/en/\">Neurobiology of Stress and Addiction&#39;s</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	1. Understanding brain processing of stressors and the usefulness of different biological markers of neuronal activation.<br />\n	2. Processes and mechanisms involved in adaptation to chronic stress.<br />\n	3. The impact of stress in psychopathology and the underlying neurobiological mechanisms.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	1. To identify brain areas and neuronal phenotypes activated by exposure to emotional and pharmacological (i.e. addictive drugs) stressors. We use expression of immediate early genes (IEGs) such as c-fos and arc and epigenetic changes (i.e. histone phosphorylation and acetylation). Our hypothesis is that epigenetic changes are more restricted that expression of IEGs and can help identifying critical brain areas and neurons. With these tools we are exploring how simultaneous exposure to two stressors or to stressors and addictive drugs interact in the brain.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	2.&nbsp; After repeated exposure to a wide range of predominantly emotional stressors, there is a reduction of the response to the same (homotypic) stressor that is observed at physiological (i.e. hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal hormones) and behavioural levels. Adaptation is also observed in brain expression of IEGs. Our main purposes are to identify cognitive/emotional processes involved in adaptation as well as the brain areas and neurochemical mechanisms involved. One of our main hypotheses is that adaptation to repeated stress is not a simple habituation process, as usually assumed, but a complex brain process that may involve cognitive aspects and associative signals. A second one is that adaptation to stress is so difficult to block pharmacologically or by brain lesions because it likely involves several different brain pathways and neurochemical processes acting in a parallel and redundant way.<br />\n	<br />\n	3.&nbsp; It has been known for decades that exposure to stress in humans is involved in the development of psychopathologies including anxiety, depression and drug addiction. More recently, it has been demonstrated that a single exposure to certain severe stressors can result in long-lasting neuroendocrine, cognitive and emotional changes, reminiscent of post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD). Our purpose is to characterize the characteristics of stressors that determine their psychopathological impact, as well as the biological basis of individual differences in resilience or vulnerability to the consequences of stress. In this regard, one of our main focuses is the activation of the HPA axis and its key brain regulator, the corticotropin-releasing factor/hormone (CRF o CRH), which has been demonstrated to constitute a critical biological link between stress and psychopathology. In addition, we have obtained evidence that activation of BNDF-trkB pathways in critical areas such as the hippocampal formation and the amygdala may also be important to limit the negative consequences of severe stressors.</p>\n<table align=\"left\" border=\"2\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td style=\"background-color: rgb(204, 0, 51);\">\n				<span style=\"color:#000000;\"><strong>SGR GROUP 2014-1020</strong></span></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td style=\"background-color: rgb(204, 0, 51);\">\n				<span style=\"color:#000000;\"><strong>Coordination: Antonio Armario</strong></span></td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>\n	&nbsp;</h2>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>LATEST PUBLICATIONS&nbsp; </strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Souza Queiroz J, Mar&iacute;n Blasco I, Gagliano H, Daviu N, G&oacute;mez Rom&aacute;n A, Belda X, Carrasco J, Rocha MC, Palermo Neto J, Armario A. <em>Chlorella vulgaris reduces the impact of stress on hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis and brain c-fos expression</em>. Psychoneuroendocrinology. <strong>2015</strong>;65:1-8.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Lalanza JF, Sanchez-Roige S, Cigarroa I, Gagliano H, Fuentes S, Armario A, Capdevila L, Escorihuela RM. <em>Long-term moderate treadmill exercise promotes stress-coping strategies in male and female rats.</em> Sci Rep. <strong>2015</strong>;5:16166.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Aguil&oacute; J, Ferrer-Salvans P, Garc&iacute;a-Rozo A, Armario A, Corb&iacute; &Aacute;, Cambra FJ, Bail&oacute;n R, Gonz&aacute;lez-Marcos A, Caja G, Aguil&oacute; S, L&oacute;pez-Ant&oacute;n R, Arza-Vald&eacute;s A, Garz&oacute;n-Rey JM. <em>Project ES3: attempting to quantify and measure the level of stress</em>. Rev Neurol. <strong>2015</strong>;61(9):405-15.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Belda X, Fuentes S, Daviu N, Nadal R, Armario A. <em>Stress-induced sensitization: the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis and beyond</em>. Stress, <strong>2015</strong>, 18:269-79.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; L&oacute;pez-Moreno JA, Marcos M, Calleja-Conde J, Echeverry-Alzate V, B&uuml;hler K, Costa-Alba P, Bernardo E, Laso FJ, Rodr&iacute;guez de Fonseca F, Nadal R, Viveros MP, Maldonado R, Gin&eacute; E. <em>Histone deacetylase gene expression following binge alcohol consumption in rats and humans</em> Alcohol Clin Exp Res. <strong>2015</strong>, 39:1939-50.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830297/public/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>See more A. Armario in PubMed.</strong></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48831252/public/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>See more R. Nadal in PubMed.</strong></a></p>\n<p>\n	<strong><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=andero+r\">See more R. Andero in </a><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=andero+r\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed</a></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',19,2,2),(410,45,0,'Albert Badia & Victoria Clos','<h2>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Neuropharmacology Group</span></h2>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group Leaders:</strong></p>\n<table style=\"width: 100%;\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Albert Badia Sancho</td>\n			<td>\n				Vict&ograve;ria Clos Guill&eacute;n</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:albert.badia@uab.cat\">albert.badia@uab.cat</a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:victoria.clos@uab.cat\">victoria.clos@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				+34 93 581 1964</td>\n			<td>\n				+34 93 581 1963</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/F-9693-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7005737400\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Albert_Badia2\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"28\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"28\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=35582392100\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Closdef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	Bel&eacute;n P&eacute;rez Fern&aacute;ndez<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES&nbsp;</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	The main goal of the Neuropharmacology Grup is to study the activity and fucntions of Acetilcolinesterase (AChE) and its inhibition by acetylcholinesterase inhibidors, currently, the most successful treatment for Alzheimer disease. Considering the mechanism of action for the acetylcholinesterase inhibitors (AChEI), they are expected only to temporarily mitigate some of the symptoms. However, some clinical studies have shown that AChEI not only are able to increase ACh viability in AD patients but also could act as modifying-disease drugs. On the other hand,&nbsp; AChE occurs in neuronal and non-neuronal tissue developing non-canonical functions as well. These not-catalytic functions are involved in morphogenesis, hematopoiesis, osteogenesis, apoptosis, and in neurogenesis. These functions have been ascribed to a two variant of AChE: &#39;Synaptic&#39; AChE-S a membrane multimeric enzyme and the soluble monomeric &#39;readthrough&#39; AChE-R. In general, both AChE isoforms are inducible by neural injury or by cholinesterase inhibitors, however, the expression of AChE-R appears to be related to neuroprotection and repair, whereas AChE-S is more highly associated with injury and increasing neurotoxicity. Accordingly, the main aim of the present project is to analyze the effect of AChE inhibitors (huprines and heterodimers) on the two variants of AChE (-S and &ndash;R) expression under different experimental conditions and approaches, in vivo and in vitro, taking into account both neurotoxic and neurogenesis process. This objective will allow us to go more deeply into the mechanism of action of AChEIs and also to get additional information about role and functions of AChE isoforms.<br />\n	On the other had, and in colaboration with the Chemical Pharmaceutic group of Faculty of Pharmacy at Barcelona University, we characterize the pharmacological profile of new heterodimers compound with multitarged functions, related all of them to the neuropathological factors involved in the Alzheimer disease.<br />\n	&nbsp;<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES&nbsp;</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	Neuropharmacology of neurodegenarative disorders:<br />\n	<br />\n	- Cholinergic system in the development of Alzheimer&rsquo;s&nbsp; disease: Role of different AChE variants and anticholinesterasic drugs in neurogenesis and neurodegeneration processes.<br />\n	- Pharmacological evaluation of new multifunctional drugs<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>LATEST PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; Di Pietro O, Viayna E, Vicente-Garc&iacute;a E, Bartolini M, Ram&oacute;n R, Ju&aacute;rez-Jim&eacute;nez J, Clos MV, P&eacute;rez B, Andrisano V, Luque FJ, Lavilla R, Mu&ntilde;oz-Torrero D.<em><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24389509\"><br />\n	1,2,3,4-Tetrahydrobenzo[h][1,6]naphthyridines as a new family of potent peripheral-to-midgorge-site inhibitors of acetylcholinesterase: Synthesis, pharmacological evaluation and mechanistic studies.</a></em><br />\n	Eur J Med Chem. <strong>2014</strong>;73:141-52.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; Viayna E, Sola I, Bartolini M, De Simone A, Tapia-Rojas C, Serrano FG, Sabat&eacute; R, Ju&aacute;rez-Jim&eacute;nez J, P&eacute;rez B, Luque FJ, Andrisano V, Clos MV, Inestrosa NC, Mu&ntilde;oz-Torrero D.<em><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24568372\"><br />\n	Synthesis and multi-target biological profiling of a novel family of rhein derivatives as disease-modifying anti-Alzheimer agents.</a></em><br />\n	J Med Chem. <strong>2014</strong> . [Epub ahead of print]</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pera M.,&nbsp; Camps P.,&nbsp; Munoz-Torrero D., Perez B., Badia A.,Clos MV.<br />\n	<em>Undifferentiated and Differentiated PC12 Cells Protected by Huprines Against Injury Induced by Hydrogen Peroxide.</em><br />\n	PloS ONE 8(9): e74344. <strong>2013</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ratia M, Gim&eacute;nez-Llort L, Camps P, Mu&ntilde;oz-Torrero D, P&eacute;rez B, Clos MV, Badia A.<br />\n	<em>Huprine X and Huperzine A Improve Cognition and Regulate Some Neurochemical Processes Related with Alzheimer&#39;s Disease in Triple Transgenic Mice (3xTg-AD).</em><br />\n	Neurodegener Dis.&nbsp;<strong>2013</strong>;11(3):129-40.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Galdeano C, Viayna E, Sola I, Formosa X, Camps P, Badia A, Clos MV, Relat J, Ratia M, Bartolini M, Mancini F, Andrisano V, Salmona M, Minguill&oacute;n C, Gonz&aacute;lez-Mu&ntilde;oz GC, Rodr&iacute;guez-Franco MI, Bidon-Chanal A, Luque FJ, Mu&ntilde;oz-Torrero D.<br />\n	<em>Huprine-tacrine heterodimers as anti-amyloidogenic compounds of potential interest against Alzheimer&#39;s and prion diseases.</em><br />\n	J Med Chem.&nbsp;<strong>2012</strong>&nbsp; 26;55(2):661-9.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/49667007/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more A. Badia in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830631/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more V. Clos in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',20,2,2),(411,45,0,'José Ramón Bayascas','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1);\">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Signalling in the Central Nervous System</span></h2>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group Leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Jos&eacute; Ram&oacute;n Bayascas</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:joseramon.bayascas@uab.cat\">joseramon.bayascas@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 813 762</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-6096-2151\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/C-9450-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6602348616\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jose_Bayascas/publications\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"28\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://scholar.google.com/citations?user=49L6LNQAAAAJ&amp;hl=es\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/googlescholar.jpg\" width=\"31\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"https://es.linkedin.com/pub/jose-r-bayascas/34/6b6/357\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"33\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Linkedin.jpg\" width=\"42\" /></a></td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/bayascas2014.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Current Lab:</strong><br />\n	LLu&iacute;s Cord&oacute;n Barris<br />\n	Xiangyu Zhou<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Past Lab:</strong><br />\n	Tinatin Zurashvili<br />\n	Patricia Ortega<br />\n	Juuli Lamberg<br />\n	Esther Caba&ntilde;as<br />\n	Natalia Gorska<br />\n	Laura Kempainnen &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\n	Anna Santaella<br />\n	Shaobin Yang</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	1) To generate by genetic crosses PDK1 conditional knock-in mice expressing the PDK1 Lys465Glu and Leu155Glu mutant alleles in neurone-specific manner.<br />\n	2) To analyse the PDK1 conditional knock-in mice phenotype.<br />\n	3) To investigate the relative contribution of the PKB isoforms, when compared to the rest of the PDK1 substrates, to neuronal survival and differentiation of neuronal primary cultures upon stimulation with neurotrophic factors and under cellular stress.<br />\n	4) To elucidate the involvement of the PDK1 substrates in the intracellular signalling pathways induced by neurotrophic factors. The activation and phosphorylation of those PKB physiologic targets involved in cellular survival, as well as of the p70S6K targets involved in protein synthesis and cell growth control, will be evaluated.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	The role of the PDK1 signalling pathway in neuronal survival: Generation of neuronal-specific PDK1 conditional knock-in mice.<br />\n	The main goal of this project is to characterise two mice strains that expresses two PDK1 conditional knock-in alleles containing the Lys465Glu (K465E) and the Leu155Glu (L155E) mutations. These alleles produce PDK1 mutant forms which are not longer able to activate the PKB isoforms, or substrates other than PKB (p70S6K, SGK, p90rsk and PKC), respectively. The PDK1 conditional allele will be expressed in specific neuronal populations by means of the Cre-Recombinase technology to evaluate the relative contribution of the PKB isoforms, compared with that of the other PDK1 substrates, to the cell survival of those specific neurons.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>FEATURED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Zurashvili T, Cord&oacute;n-Barris L, Ruiz-Babot G, Zhou X, Lizcano JM, G&oacute;mez N, Gim&eacute;nez-Llort L, Bayascas JR.&nbsp;<br />\n	<em>Interaction of PDK1&nbsp;with&nbsp;phosphoinositides is essential for neuronal differentiation, but dispensable for neuronal survival.&nbsp;</em><br />\n	Mol Cell Biol. <strong>2013</strong> Mar;33(5):1027-40.<br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bayascas JR.&nbsp;<br />\n	<em>PDK1: the major transducer of PI 3-kinase actions.&nbsp;</em><br />\n	Curr Top Microbiol Immunol.&nbsp;<strong>2010</strong>; 346: 9-29.&nbsp;<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<div>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Zhou X, Cordon-Barris L, Zurashvili T, Bayascas JR.&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Fine-tuning the intensity of the PKB/Akt signal enables diverse physiological responses. Cell Cycle.&nbsp;2014;13(20):3164-8.</div>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bayascas JR, Wullschleger S, Sakamoto K, Garc&iacute;a-Mart&iacute;nez JM, Clacher C, Komander D, van Aalten DM, Boini KM, Lang F, Lipina C, Logie L, Sutherland C, Chudek JA, van Diepen JA, Voshol PJ, Lucocq JM, Alessi DR.&nbsp;<br />\n	<em>Mutation of the PDK1 PH domain inhibits protein kinase B/Akt, leading to small size and insulin resistance.</em><br />\n	Mol Cell Biol.&nbsp;<strong>2008</strong> ;28(10):3258-72.&nbsp;<br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bayascas JR.&nbsp;<br />\n	<em>Dissecting the role of the 3-phosphoinositide-dependent protein kinase-1 (PDK1) signalling pathways.&nbsp;</em><br />\n	Cell Cycle.&nbsp;<strong>2008</strong>;7(19):2978-82.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830639/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more JR. Bayascas in PubMed. </a><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',21,2,2),(412,45,0,'Bernardo Castellano & Berta González','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">BBG- Glial Research Team</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leaders:</strong></p>\n<table style=\"width: 100%;\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Bernardo Castellano L&oacute;pez</td>\n			<td>\n				Berta Gonz&aacute;lez de Mingo</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:bernardo.castellano@uab.cat\">bernardo.castellano@uab.cat</a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:berta.gonzalez@uab.cat\">berta.gonzalez@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 811 875</td>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 811 875</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table height=\"25\" width=\"40\">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0003-1976-971X\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/G-1428-2010\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7003547186\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Bernardo_Castellano?ev=hdr_xprf\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/pub/bernardo-castellano-l%C3%B3pez/2a/218/7a8?trk=pub-pbmap\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"32\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Linkedin.jpg\" width=\"41\" /></a></td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7102739324\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" width=\"29\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Castdef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Beatriz Almolda<br />\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/profile.php?id=21\">Isabella Appiah</a><br />\n	Anna Camps<br />\n	Miguel A. Martil<br />\n	Filip Petkovic<br />\n	Mireia Recasens<br />\n	Nadia Villacampa</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;To identify the signals modulating the activation of glial cells in different paradigms.<br />\n	&bull;To identify the signaling pathways that may be a putative interaction-target to prevent neurodegeneration and promote regeneration.<br />\n	&bull;To identify the presence of antigen presenting cells (APCs) in the CNS under both normal and pathological conditions.<br />\n	&bull;To identify the signals involved in regulating the inflammatory and immune responses in the CNS.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	1)Study of differential signalling and molecular mechanisms involved in modulating the activation, proliferation and glial cell death in different experimental models of innate and acquired immunity: excitotoxic injury, facial nerve axotomy, deafferentation of the dentate fascia of the hippocampus, induction experimental autoimmune encephalopathy (EAE), etc.<br />\n	2) Characterization of the putative involvement of glial cells in the modulation of the inflammatory and immune responses. We are especially interested in studying the regulation exerted by microglial cells, macrophages and dendritic cells in the regulation of the infiltration, activation, proliferation, anergy and apoptosis of lymphocytes. These studies were developed in Lewis rats and in transgenic mice that over-express inflammatory (IL6) and anti-inflammatory (IL10) cytokines.<br />\n	3) Study of changes in the expression of extracellular matrix molecules and their cellular receptors, integrins in neurons and glial cells in different paradigms of brain damage including exctotoxicity, axotomy and EAE in normal rats and mice, as well as in transgenic mice over-expressing IL6 and IL10.<br />\n	4) Interaction with the mechanisms that regulate CNS expression of enzymes and inflammatory cytokines from glial origin through the use of drugs that inhibit the transcription factors involved in the activation of microglia and astroglia, in order to reduce secondary neuronal death subsequent to experimental injury.<br />\n	5) Evaluation of the possible use of molecular complexes from non-viral origin as vectors in gene therapy strategies to promote neuroprotection.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Almolda B, Villacampa N, Manders P, Hidalgo J, Campbell IL, Gonz&aacute;lez B and Castellano B.<br />\n	<em>Effects of astrocyte-targeted production of interleukin-6 in the mouse on the host response to nerve injury.</em><br />\n	Glia, 62: 1142- 1161 (<strong>2014</strong>)</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Almolda B., Gonz&aacute;lez B. and B. Castellano<br />\n	<em>Microglia detection by enzymatic histochemistry.</em><br />\n	Methods Mol Biol 1041: 243-59 (<strong>2013</strong>)</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp; Gonzalez P., Peluffo H., Acarin L., Villaverde A., Gonzalez B.&nbsp; and Castellano B.<br />\n	<em>Interleukin-10 overexpression does not synergize with the neuroprotective action of RGD-containing vectors after postnatal brain excitotoxicity but modulates the main inflammatory cell&nbsp;responses.</em><br />\n	J Neurosci Res. 90:143-59 (<strong>2012</strong>)</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Almolda B., Costa M., Montoya M., Gonz&aacute;lez B. and Castellano B.<br />\n	<em>Increase in Th17 and T-reg lymphocytes and decrease of IL22 correlate with the recovery phase of acute EAE in rat.</em><br />\n	PLoS One,&nbsp;2011;6(11):e27473. (<strong>2011</strong>)</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Almolda B., Gonz&aacute;lez B. and Castellano B<br />\n	<em>Antigen presentation in EAE: role of microglia, macrophages and dendritic cells.</em><br />\n	Frontiers in Biosciences, 16:1157-71,&nbsp;Review (<strong>2011</strong>)</p>\n<table align=\"left\" border=\"2\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td style=\"background-color: rgb(204, 0, 51);\">\n				<strong><span style=\"color:#000000;\">SGR GROUP 2014 1464</span></strong></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td style=\"background-color: rgb(204, 0, 51);\">\n				<span style=\"color:#000000;\"><strong>Coordination: Bernardo Castellano</strong></span></td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830665/public/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>See more B. Castellano in PubMed.</strong></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830680/public/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>See more B. Gonz&aacute;lez in PubMed. </strong></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',22,2,2),(413,45,0,'Enrique Claro & Fernando Picatoste','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Lipid Metabolism and Cell Death</span></h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group Leaders:</strong></p>\n<table style=\"width: 100%;\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Enrique Claro</td>\n			<td>\n				Fernando Picatoste</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:enrique.claro@uab.es\">enrique.claro@uab.es</a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:fernando.picatoste@uab.cat\">fernando.picatoste@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				+34 935814150</td>\n			<td>\n				+34 935811574</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-7592-7906\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/D-5612-2009\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"https://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7003847422\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Enrique_Claro\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" style=\"width: 27px; height: 27px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"https://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6701819691\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/ClaPidef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	Meritxell Asensio<br />\n	Ainara G. Cabodevilla<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Former group members:</strong><br />\n	Alberto G. Andreolotti<br />\n	Miquel Barcel&oacute;<br />\n	David Barneda<br />\n	Albert Gubern<br />\n	Eleni Nintou<br />\n	Ra&uuml;l Pardo<br />\n	Bel&eacute;n Ramos<br />\n	Laura S&aacute;nchez<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	We want to explain some roles of phospholipid metabolism in physiological processes such as programmed cell death, autophagy, and secretion. Phosphatidylcholine (PtdCho) is the major phospholipid in cell membranes, but its implication in many aspects of physiology and pathology, some of them relevant to the nervous system, is just beginning to be unraveled.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	<em>1.- Mec1.- Mechanisms of cell death associated to the inhibition of PtdCho synthesis</em><br />\n	A variety of drugs inhibit PtdCho synthesis after their interaction with CTP:phosphocholine cytidylyltransferase (CCT), one of the three enzymes of the CDP-choline pathway, and this results in the induction of cell death. We are currrently studying CHO-MT58 cells, which possess a mutated, thermosensitive CCT&alpha; enzyme. The process of cell death does not imply apoptotic mechanisms, and apparently takes place with typical autophagic traits.<br />\n	<br />\n	<em>2.- The biogenesis of lipid droplets and their role in cell survival</em><br />\n	Lipid droplets (LD) are triglyceride and cholesterylester-storing organelles, somehow similar to the big droplet of adipocytes, but found in virtually all cell types including neurons and astrocytes. LD are very dynamic organelles that appear in the cytosol when cells take up lipoproteins or free fatty acids from the medium. LD also appear in the absence of external lipid sources when cells are under stress: in this case, LD confer resistance to stress, and triglycerides contained in LD derive from the cell&#39;s own membrane phospholipids in a process depending on Group VIA phospholipase A2 (iPLA2-VIA).&nbsp; We have also identified Group IVA phospholipase A2 (cPLA2&alpha;) as a necessary enzyme for the biogenesis of LD after triglycerides synthesized in the ER. We are currently exploring mechanisms up- and downstream of cPLA2&alpha; accounting for LD biogenesis under different physiological situations.<br />\n	<br />\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/ld-fl.jpg\" style=\"width: 50%; float: left;\" /><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/ld-tem.jpg\" style=\"float: right; width: 50%;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Investigacio/1.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>FEATURED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cabodevilla AG, S&aacute;nchez-Caballero L, Nintou E, Boiadjieva VG, Picatoste F, Gubern A, Claro E.<br />\n	<em>Cell survival during complete nutrient deprivation depends on lipid droplet-fueled &beta;-oxidation of fatty acids.</em><br />\n	J Biol Chem. 2013 Sep 27;288(39):27777-88.Epub <strong>2013</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A. Gubern, M. Barcel&oacute;-Torns, D. Barneda, R. Masgrau, F. Picatoste, J. Casas, J. Balsinde, M.A. Balboa, E. Claro.<br />\n	<em>Lipid droplet biogenesis induced by stress involves triacylglycerol synthesis that depends on Group VIA phospholipase A2.</em><br />\n	J Biol Chem. <strong>2009</strong>;284(9):5697-708.<br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A. Gubern, M. Barcel&oacute;-Torns, D. Barneda, J.M. L&oacute;pez, R. Masgrau, F. Picatoste, C.E. Chalfant, J. Balsinde, M.A. Balboa, E. Claro.<br />\n	<em>JNK and ceramide kinase govern the biogenesis of lipid droplets through activation of Group IVA phospholipase A2.</em><br />\n	J Biol Chem. <strong>2009</strong>;284(47):32359-69.<br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A. Gubern, J. Casas, M. Barcel&oacute;-Torns, D. Barneda, X. de la Rosa, R. Masgrau, F. Picatoste, J. Balsinde, M.A. Balboa, E. Claro.<br />\n	<em>Group IVA phospholipase A2 is necessary for the biogenesis of lipid droplets.</em><br />\n	J Biol Chem. <strong>2008</strong>;283(41):27369-82.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830780/public/\">See more E. Claro in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830787/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more F. Picatoste in PubMed.</a><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',23,2,2),(415,45,0,'Rosa Maria Escorihuela','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(374,1)\">Neurobiology of the normal and disturbed mind</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Lifestyles and Mental Health</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Rosa M. Escorihuela Agull&oacute;</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:RosaMaria.Escorihuela@uab.cat\">RosaMaria.Escorihuela@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 813 296</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"https://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=16938862000\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/RMescdef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	Igor Ivan Cigarroa Cuevas<br />\n	Oier Pastor</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGICS OBJECTIVES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	The principal aim of our research program is to evaluate the long-term impact of rearing conditions and lifestyle habits on brain and mental health. We have used environmental enrichment and handling manipulation and, more recently, exercise as a tool for improving brain functioning in adulthood and ageing. Our rats (males and females) are subjected to a 30-min sessions of low-moderate treadmill training (12m/min, 5 days/week) in order to reproduce a protocol widely recommended to humans. We are also introducing a high fat high sugar diet to our studies in order to investigate whether the practice of regular low-moderate exercise can interact with the negative effects of the bad eating. As a second strategy we use a model of senescence accelerated mice, where mice are housed in cages containing a running wheel for performing voluntary exercise. The long term effects of the different forms of exercise are evaluated on behavioural, physiological and biochemical parameters in adulthood and at advanced ages. The impact of the exercise protocols on the cardiovascular function is also studied through telemetric devices implanted in the animals.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	1. To determine the effects of long-term low-moderate exercise on brain health, in terms of anxiety, stress responsiveness, mood and cognition in males and females.<br />\n	2. To evaluate whether exercise can diminish the impact of the deterioration processes associated with ageing and neurodegenerative diseases.<br />\n	3. To investigate the interaction of the regular moderate exercise with the bad eating habits, in terms of behavioral changes.<br />\n	4. To characterize the behavioral profiles predisposed for practicing regular exercise and for eating the high fat high sugar diet.<br />\n	5. To examine the effects of exercise as a treatment to diminish motor impulsivity and enhance the attentional performance.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>FEATURED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Lalanza, J.F., Caimari, A., Del Bas, J.M., (...), Arola, L., Escorihuela, R.M.<br />\n	<em>Effects of a post-weaning cafeteria diet in young rats: Metabolic syndrome, reduced activity and low anxiety-like behaviour</em><br />\n	PLoS ONE, <strong>2014</strong>, 9 (1), e85049</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Lalanza, J.F., Sanchez-Roige, S., Gagliano, H., (...), Armario, A., Escorihuela, R.M.<br />\n	<em>Physiological and behavioural consequences of long-term moderate treadmill exercise</em><br />\n	Psychoneuroendocrinology, <strong>2012</strong> , 37 (11), pp. 1745-1754</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Bayod, S., del Valle, J., Lalanza, J.F., (...), Escorihuela, R.M., Pall&agrave;s, M.<br />\n	<em>Long-term physical exercise induces changes in sirtuin 1 pathway and oxidative parameters in adult rat tissues</em><br />\n	Experimental Gerontology ,<strong>2012</strong> ,47 (12), pp. 925-935</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Kaliman P, P&aacute;rrizas , Lalanza JF, Camins A,Escorihuela RM, Pall&agrave;s M.<br />\n	<em>Neurophysiological and epigenetic effects of physical exercise on the aging process.</em><br />\n	Ageing Res Rev. <strong>2011</strong> ;10(4):475-86.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Garc&iacute;a-Gonz&aacute;lez MA, Fern&aacute;ndez-Chimeno M, Ferrer J, Escorihuela RM, Parrado E, Capdevila L, Ben&iacute;tez A, Angulo R, Rodr&iacute;guez FA, Iglesias X, Besc&oacute;s R, Marina M, Padull&eacute;s JM, Ramos-Castro J.&nbsp;<br />\n	<em>New indices for quantification of the power spectrum of heart rate variability time series without the need of any frequency band definition.</em><br />\n	Physiol Meas. <strong>2011</strong>;32(8):995-1009.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830790/public/\">See more RM. Escorihuela in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',25,2,2),(416,45,0,'Ester Fernández','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Research Group on Inflammation and Tolerance: New therapeutic approaches</span></h2>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Ester Fern&aacute;ndez Gimeno</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:Ester.Fernandez@uab.cat\">Ester.Fernandez@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				+34 93 581 3282</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7402179023\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Eferdef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	Joan Francesc Burgue&ntilde;o Ban&uacute;s<br />\n	Elena Eyre S&aacute;nchez<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To gain knowledge on the functions of enteric neurons and glia and their interactions with other cell types found in the intestine. We intend to progress in the understanding the role of the enteric nervous system in the innate immune response, the maintenance of tolerance and the switch between tolerance and inflammation and between inflammation and tumorigenesis.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To explore the cross talk of toll-like receptors and other pattern recognition receptors with other signalling pathways.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our research combines molecular, cellular and whole animal approaches using a variety of techniques and models.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Through these studies we intend to propose new strategies for therapeutic intervention based on the use of new tools, vehicles and targets including gene therapy vectors.&nbsp;<br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Therapeutic&nbsp; efficacy&nbsp; of gene knocking down in vitro and in vivo in animal models of inflammation&nbsp; (IBD) and colon cancer.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Therapeutic&nbsp; efficacy&nbsp; of gene overexpression in vitro and in vivo in animal models of inflammation&nbsp; (IBD) and colon cancer.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Immunomodulatoy&nbsp; functions of enteric glial cells and&nbsp; enteric neurons.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Pattern recognition receptors and Toll like receptor signalling. Cross talk with other signalling cascades.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Mechanisms involved in acquired chemoresistance.<br />\n	&nbsp;<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>PUBLICATIONS</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;Ocampo SM, Romero C, Avi&ntilde;&oacute; A, Burgue&ntilde;o J, Gassull MA, Berm&uacute;dez J, Eritja R, Fernandez E, Perales JC.<br />\n	<em>Functionally enhanced siRNA targeting TNF&alpha;attenuates DSS-induced colitis and TLR-mediated immunostimulation in mice.</em><br />\n	Mol Ther.&nbsp;<strong>2012</strong> ;20(2):382-90.<br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;Aul&iacute; M, Nasser Y, Ho W, Burgue&ntilde;o JF, Keenan CM, Romero C, Sharkey KA, Fern&aacute;ndez E.<br />\n	<em>Neuromuscular changes in a rat model of colitis.</em><br />\n	Auton.&nbsp; Neurosci-Basic Clin.&nbsp;<strong>2008 </strong>;141(1-2):10-21.&nbsp;<br />\n	<br />\n	&bull; R&iacute;o A, Gassull MA, Aldeguer X, Ojanguren I, Cabr&eacute; E, Fern&aacute;ndez E.<br />\n	<em>Reduced liver injury in the interleukin-6 knockout mice by chronic carbon tetrachloride administration.</em><br />\n	Eur J Clin Invest.&nbsp;<strong>2008</strong>;38(5):306-16.<br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;Aul&iacute; M, Fern&aacute;ndez E.<br />\n	<em>Time course of neural and contractile disturbances in a rat model of colitis induced by Trichinella spiralis.</em><br />\n	Life Sci.&nbsp;<strong>2007</strong> 81(14):1117-29.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>PATENTS</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	<strong> </strong>T&iacute;tle: Methods and Reagents of efficient and targeted gene transfer to monocytes and&nbsp; macrophages.&nbsp; Inventors:&nbsp; Chillon, M, Rio A, Fern&aacute;ndez E, Gassull MA. European Patent application: EP09159001.8 Priority: EUROPE. Priority date: 29-04-2009.Extended to:&nbsp; PCT, Argentina, Uruguay. Ownership: Universitat Autonoma de Barcelona, Fundaci&oacute; Institut de Recerca Hospital Univ. Germans Trias i Pujol, Institut Catal&agrave; de Recerca i Estudis Avan&ccedil;ats (ICREA), Gr&iacute;fols S.A. Licensed to:&nbsp; Nanotherapix S.L.<br />\n	<br />\n	T&iacute;tle: Derivados de peque&ntilde;os ARN de interferencia y su uso. Inventors: Eritja R, Ocampo S.M., Perales J.C., Fern&aacute;ndez, E. Romero, C., Burgue&ntilde;o J.F. P201031622&nbsp; Pa&iacute;s de prioridad: Espa&ntilde;a.&nbsp; Priority date: 04-11-2010. Extended to:&nbsp; PCT, Argentina, Uruguay.&nbsp; Ownership: Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient&iacute;ficas (CSIC); Universitat de Barcelona; Universitat Autonoma de Barcelona. Licensed to: ( Dealing)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830799/public/\" target=\"_blank\"><br />\n	See more E. Fern&aacute;ndez in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',26,2,2),(417,45,0,'Alberto Fernández Teruel','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(374,1)\">Neurobiology of the normal and disturbed mind</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Neurobiological and Genetic Basis of Mental and Neurological Diseases</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Alberto Fern&aacute;ndez Teruel</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:Albert.Fernandez.Teruel@uab.cat\">Albert.Fernandez.Teruel@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 813 456</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/F-9374-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7003727625\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Alberto_Fernandez-Teruel\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"30\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"30\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/AFernandezA3_opt.jpg\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 266px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	Gloria Bl&aacute;zquez Romero<br />\n	Antoni Ca&ntilde;ete Ram&iacute;rez<br />\n	Crist&oacute;bal del R&iacute;o Alamos<br />\n	Carme Mont Cardona<br />\n	Ignasi Oliveras Puigdelivol<br />\n	Ana S&aacute;nchez Gonz&aacute;lez<br />\n	Adolf Tobe&ntilde;a Pallar&eacute;s</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	Current and future research of our group/laboratory is aimed at improving knowledge on the psychological, neurobiological and genetic basis of several psychological and neurological diseases. Progress towards these objectives is based on the use of several resources and experimental approaches, namely: 1) The psychogenetically-selected RHA-I and RLA-I inbred rats, which markedly differ in anxious/stress (behavioural and hormonal) responses and incentive/drug-seeking, are a good model to study the neurobiological and genetic basis of anxiety and drug addiction. 2) Besides the use of these RHA-I and RLA-I strains, the N/Nih-HS genetically heterogeneous rat stock (maintained at our lab) is a powerful resource which is being used for fine (high resolution) genetic mapping of complex disease-related phenotypes like anxiety/fearfulness/depression, multiple esclerosis, blood pressure, diabetes-related traits and other endocrine and immunological traits. 3) The triple transgenic 3xTgAD mice are also a powerful model for Alzheimer dementia, which is used at our lab to investigate the possibilities of preventing or delaying the appearance of neuropathological and behavioural symptoms of dementia following infantile/juvenile environmentally-enriched treatments.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	<em>Neurogenetics of anxiety and genetics of disease-related neural (and non neural) phenotypes in rats.</em><br />\n	Using the N/Nih-HS and RHA/RLA rats, and funded by SAF-2003-03480 (IP: A. Fernandez-Teruel), by the Welcome Trust (J. Flint, UK) and by a FP6 european grant (IP: Timothy Aitman, London. IP Partner 11: A. Fernandez-Teruel), this research line is carried out in collaboration with the groups of Drs. Jonathan Flint (Oxford), Peter Driscoll (Switzerland), Tomas Olsson (Sweden), Dominique Gauguier (Oxford), Norbert Hubner (Berlin), Rickard Holdmdal (Sweden), Anna Dominizak (Scottland) and 10 other european research labs.<br />\n	<br />\n	<em>Effects of postnatal stimulation (neonatal handling) and environmental enrichment on neuromorphological, neurochemical and behavioural anomalies related with aging and dementia.</em><br />\n	In collaboration with Dr. F.M. LaFerla (California, USA) a colony of 3xTgAD mice (a very recent Alzheimer model) has been established in our lab. Funding for this research line has been obtained from I+D (Spanish Ministery of Education and Science, 2006-2008) and &ldquo;Marat&oacute; de TV3&rdquo; (IP: Lydia Gim&eacute;nez-Llort; Collaborators: Dr. F.M. LaFerla, UCI, USA i Dr. B. Johansson, Karolinska Institute, Stockholm; Dr. C. Sanfeliu, CSIC, Barcelona, Spain).<br />\n	<br />\n	<em> <em>Environmental enrichment, physical exercise and/or special diets in rodents: Long term behavioral and biochemical effects.</em></em><br />\n	This research line is being developed in collaboration with Prof. Margarita Prunell ( Universidad de La Laguna, Spain), Dr. Yolanda Pe&ntilde;a (University of Essex, UK), Prof. Mercedes Unzeta (Dept. Bioqu&iacute;mica, UAB), Profs. Juan Hidalgo and Antonio Armario (Dept. Biologia Cel.lular i Fisiologia), and Prof. Roser Nadal (Area Psicobiologia, Facultat de Psicologia, UAB).<br />\n	<br />\n	<em> </em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>LATEST PUBLICATIONS</strong></span><br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Bl&aacute;zquez G, Ca&ntilde;ete T, Tobe&ntilde;a A, Gim&eacute;nez-Llort L, Fern&aacute;ndez-Teruel A.<br />\n	<em>Cognitive and emotional profiles of aged Alzheimer&#39;s disease (3&times;TgAD) mice: Effects of environmental enrichment and sexual dimorphism.</em><br />\n	Behav Brain Res. <strong>2014</strong> Jul 15;268:185-201.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Alam I, Koller DL, Ca&ntilde;ete T, Bl&aacute;zquez G, L&oacute;pez-Aumatell R, Mart&iacute;nez-Membrives E, D&iacute;az-Mor&aacute;n S, Tobe&ntilde;a A, Fern&aacute;ndez-Teruel A, Stridh P, Diez M, Olsson T, Johannesson M, Baud A, Econs MJ, Foroud T.<br />\n	<em>High-Resolution Genome Screen for Bone Mineral Density in Heterogeneous Stock Rat.</em><br />\n	J Bone Miner Res. <strong>2014</strong> [Epub ahead of print]</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Tuncel J, Haag S, Yau AC, Norin U, Baud A, L&ouml;nnblom E, Maratou K, Ytterberg AJ, Ekman D, Thordardottir S, Johannesson M, Gillett A; EURATRANS Consortium, Stridh P, Jagodic M, Olsson T, Fern&aacute;ndez-Teruel A, Zubarev RA, Mott R, Aitman TJ, Flint J, Holmdahl R.<br />\n	<em>Natural polymorphisms in Tap2 influence negative selection and CD4?CD8 lineage commitment in the rat.</em><br />\n	PLoS Genet. <strong>2014</strong> ;10(2):e1004151.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Klein AB, Ultved L, Adamsen D, Santini MA, Tobe&ntilde;a A, Fernandez-Teruel A, Flores P, Moreno M, Cardona D, Knudsen GM, Aznar S, Mikkelsen JD.<br />\n	<em> 5-HT(2A) and mGlu2 receptor binding levels are related to differences in impulsive behavior in the Roman Low- (RLA) and High- (RHA) avoidance rat strains.</em><br />\n	Neuroscience. <strong>2014</strong> ;263:36-45.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; &nbsp;&nbsp; Manzo L, G&oacute;mez MJ, Callejas-Aguilera JE, Fern&aacute;ndez-Teruel A, Papini MR, Torres C.<br />\n	<em>Anti-anxiety self-medication induced by incentive loss in rats.</em><br />\n	Physiol Behav. <strong>2014</strong>;123:86-92.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830803/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more A. Fern&aacute;ndez-Teruel in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',27,2,2),(419,45,0,'Lydia Gimenez Llort','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1);\">Neurodegeneration and Ageing</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Behavioral Neuroscience</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group Leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Lydia Gim&eacute;nez-Llort</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:lidia.gimenez@uab.cat\" target=\"_blank\">lidia.gimenez@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 812 378</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6701506831\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Lydia_Gimenez-Llort\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"29\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.saberenvejecer.es\">www.saberenvejecer.es</a><br />\n	<a href=\"http://www.neurodeg.net\">www.neurodeg.net</a><br />\n	<a href=\"http://www.4th5.net\">www.4th5.net</a></p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Gimdef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group Members:</strong><br />\n	Adriana Serrano<br />\n	Aida Muntsant Soria<br />\n	Anna Roquer</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	Modeling and characterizing behavioral and neuroinmunoendocrine phenotypes related to the process of aging or those characteristic of neurodegenerative or neurological disorders is a challenge but it is relevant in order to provide research tools to study the mechanisms underlying the pathophysiological events and to assess the potential of preventive and therapeutical strategies.?Our research is focused on behavioral neuroscience (behavioral screening, behavioral pharmacology and non-pharmacological approaches) with a &#39;bed-to-bench&#39; and &#39;bench-to-bed&#39; translational view. We are also interested in the social and intergenerational relationships in the human being and their impact on the well-being of the elderly. An issue that we also try to address from basic research.?We are members of SGR1354 2014 (Coordinador: Miguel Chill&oacute;n), RETICEF (RD06/0013/0003), UCM-CM ENEROINN 910379 (UCM, PI: M&oacute;nica De la Fuente), Network 4the5. (CEO:Lydia Gim&eacute;nez-Llort), Neurogenet Consortium (IGTP, CSIC, UAB, Coordinador: Antonio Matillas). Lydia Gimenez Llort is the representative for Spain at the European Cooperation in the Field of Scientific and Technical Research COST-action TD1005 &lsquo;Pain Assessmment in Patients with Impaired Cognition, especially Dementia&rsquo;?.?The translational approach is achieved thanks to research agreements with Karolinska Hospitals of Karolinska Institute, Stockholm, Sweden (PI: Bj&ouml;rn Johansson), UVAMID Hospital Santa Katerina, Salt, Girona (PI: Secund&iacute; L&oacute;pez-Pousa), Neurogenet Consortium (IGTP, CSIC, UAB; Coordinator: Antoni Matilla) and Hospital Sagrat Cor de Martorell (PI: Manel S&aacute;nchez).<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	&nbsp;<br />\n	1. Establisment of the colonies of 3xTg-AD and wild-type mice. Behavioral characterization of cognitive and BPSD-like symptoms in animal models of aging and dementia.?<br />\n	2. Behavioral assessment of non-pharmacological (handling, enrichment, exercice)&nbsp;&nbsp; preventive and therapeutical strategies in animal models of aging and neurodegenerative disorders, with special focus in our colonies of 3xTg-AD mice.?<br />\n	3. Behavioral pharmacology of NMDA-DA-Adenosine interactions?in animal models for psychitaruc and neurologic disorders.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>Spanish colony of 3xTgAD-mice</strong></span><br />\n	Lydia Gim&eacute;nez-Llort established the Spanish colonies of triple-transgenic 3xTg-AD mice and their wild-type strain thanks to MTAs (2004; 2007) with Dr. F.M. LaFerla (University of California Irvine, USA). The triple-transgenic 3xTg-AD mice (Oddo et al, 2003, Neuron, 39, 409-421) harboring PS1M146V, APPSwe and tauP301L transgenes progressively develop &beta;A plaques and neurofibrillary tangles with a temporal- and regional-specific profile that closely mimics their development in the human AD brain. Synaptic and cognitive disfunction are manifested in an age and gender-dependent manner, but before plaque and tangle pathology. Nowadays, this model is one of the most promising tools to study the mechanisms of action of the pathophysiological contribution of intracellular &beta;A in AD, and try to determine how extensive plaque, as well as tangle pathologies may contribute to late-stage cognitive deficits, assess second generation therapeutical strategies and to which extent preventive approaches are able to improve both behavioral and pathological phenotypes.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>SELECTED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Johansson, B.,&nbsp; Halldner, L., Dunwiddie, T.V., Masino, S.A., Poelchen, W., Gim&eacute;nez-Llort, L., Escorihuela, R.M., Fern&aacute;ndez-Teruel, A., Wiesenfeld-Hallin, Z., Xu X.-J., H&aring;rdemark, A., Betsholtz, Ch., Herlenius, E., Fredholm, B.<br />\n	<em>Hyperalgesia, anxiety, and decreased hypoxic neuroprotection in mice lacking the adenosine A1 receptor.</em><br />\n	Proc. Nat. Acad. Sciences98 (16), 9407-9412.<strong>2001</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Gim&eacute;nez-Llort, L.*, Bl&aacute;zquez, G., Ca&ntilde;ete, T., Johansson, B., Oddo,S., Tobe&ntilde;a,A, LaFerla, F.M., Fern&aacute;ndez-Teruel, A.<br />\n	<em>Modeling behavioral and neuronal symptoms of Alzheimer disease in mice: a role for intraneuronal&nbsp; amyloid.</em><br />\n	Neurosci Biobehav Rev. 31(1):125-47,<strong>2007</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Espa&ntilde;a J, Gim&eacute;nez-Llort L, Valero J, Mi&ntilde;ano A, R&aacute;bano A, Rodriguez-Alvarez J, LaFerla FM, Saura CA<br />\n	<em>Intraneuronal beta-Amyloid Accumulation in the Amygdala Enhances Fear and Anxiety in Alzheimer&#39;s Disease Transgenic Mice.</em><br />\n	Biol Psychiatry.67(6): 513-521, <strong>2010</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Sol&eacute;-Dom&egrave;nech S, Sj&ouml;vall P, Vukojevi? V, Fernando R, Codita A, Salve S, Bogdanovi? N, Mohammed AH, Hammarstr&ouml;m P, Nilsson KP, Laferla FM, Jacob S, Berggren PO, Gim&eacute;nez-Llort L, Schalling M, Terenius L, Johansson B.<br />\n	<em>Localization of cholesterol, amyloid and glia in Alzheimer&#39;s disease transgenic mouse brain tissue using time-of-flight secondary ion mass spectrometry (ToF-SIMS) and immunofluorescence imaging.</em><br />\n	Acta Neuropathol. 125(1):145-57. <strong>2013</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Gim&eacute;nez-Llort L, Torres-Lista V, De la Fuente M.<br />\n	<em>Crosstalk between the nervous and the immune system during the prodromal stages of Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease. </em>In: Special Issue &ldquo;Crosstalk between the nervous and the immune system in health and in sicknes&rdquo;. Curr Pharm Des. <strong>2014</strong>;20(29):4723-32</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830910/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more L. Gimenez-Llort in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',29,2,2),(420,45,0,'Jesús Giraldo','<h2>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Laboratory of Systems Pharmacology and Bioinformatics</span></h2>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Jes&uacute;s Giraldo Arjonilla</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:Jesus.Giraldo@uab.cat\">Jesus.Giraldo@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 813 813</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0001-7082-4695\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/F-9881-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7003797712\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jesus_Giraldo\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" style=\"width: 27px; height: 27px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/DSC00222.JPG\" style=\"width: 100%;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	James Dalton,PhD<br />\n	David Roche, PhD<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>PhD students: </strong><br />\n	Agustin Bruzzese<br />\n	Martha Iv&oacute;n C&aacute;rdenas<br />\n	Joan Font<br />\n	Xavier G&oacute;mez<br />\n	Juan Serra<br />\n	Bin Zhou</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<strong><span style=\"color:#800000;\">STRATEGIC&nbsp; OBJECTIVES</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	The Laboratory of Systems Pharmacology and Bioinformatics is an interdisciplinary team composed of chemists, biologists and mathematicians. Our general goal is investigating through computational methods the functional mechanisms responsible for biological responses to gain novel knowledge with potential therapeutic impact. To this end, the <strong>G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs)</strong> superfamily has been selected as our major research area. GPCRs are involved in many physiological processes and diseases, as they are one of the main targets of current pharmaceutical research. We follow an <strong>integrative approach including molecular and mathematical models and simulations</strong> at various scales of complexity. This research is shared with experimentalists (Drs. J Ortiz, J Sabri&agrave; and C Gil) within our parent SGR group: the Laboratory of Molecular Neuropharmacology and Bioinformatics.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong><span style=\"color:#800000;\">MAIN RESEARCH LINES</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>1. Molecular modeling and dynamics simulations of GPCRs. </strong>Our objective is to provide a better understanding of the molecular mechanisms associated with the complexity of receptor structure and function, in particular <strong>receptor homo- and heteromerization, allosteric modulation, receptor constitutive activity </strong>and<strong>functional selectivity</strong>. In particular we focus on <strong>class C metabotropic glutamate receptors</strong>, their heteromeric interactions with class A GPCRs and their proposed involvement in different neurological diseases including <strong>chronic pain, schizophrenia and depression</strong>. Of special relevance, this investigation also includes the control of receptor activity by <strong>photoswitchable ligands</strong>. State-of-the-art <em>in silico </em>techniques include <strong>receptor homology modeling, induced-fit docking, protein-protein interactions </strong>and<strong>molecular dynamics simulations</strong>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>2. Mathematical modeling of GPCRs. </strong>This research line runs in parallel with our molecular research and with mutual feedback. Our objective is to construct mathematical models which include in their expressions the current receptor main topics such as <strong>inverse agonism, superagonism, allosteric modulation </strong>and<strong>receptor oligomerization</strong>. We are developing mathematical models in the framework of the <strong>operational model of agonism and allosterism</strong> (see Roche et al. Br J Pharmacol. 2013;169(6):1189-202 for review) focusing on the mechanistic aspects of drug action.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>3. Computer science, bioinformatics and biostatistics. </strong>Our objective is the construction of new bioinformatics tools for more rigorous and efficient data analysis. Currently, we have developed an <strong>evolutionary optimization algorithm</strong>, which can successfully obtain parameter estimates of equations with many parameters and various local minima (typical of complex pharmacological conditions). We collaborate with artificial intelligence specialists (Alfredo Vellido and Ren&eacute; Alqu&eacute;zar, UPC) in the systematic analysis of GPCR classification by <strong>machine learning</strong> methods. We are also active in <strong>data mining</strong> and <strong>big data </strong>analyses in biology and pharmacology.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>CURRENT PROJECTS</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Title of the Project:</strong> Integrated mathematical, computational and biochemical investigation of the crosstalk between metabotropic glutamate receptor 5 and dopamine D2 receptor: Relevance for the treatment of schizophrenia<br />\n	<strong>Funding Entity:</strong> Ministerio de Econom&iacute;a y Competitividad (REF. SAF2014-58396-R)<br />\n	<strong>Participant entities</strong>: Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Title of the Project:</strong> Deciphering the role of peripheral and central nervous system metabotropic glutamate receptors in neuropathic pain with photoactivable ligands<br />\n	<strong>Funding Entity:</strong> ERA-NET NEURON Call for transnational research projects 2012 (REF. PCIN-2013-018-C03-02)<br />\n	<strong>Participant entities:</strong> The coordinated project includes 5 subprojects whose Principal Investigators are: Amadeu Llebaria, SP1 (Institut de Qu&iacute;mica Avan&ccedil;ada de Catalunya (IQAC-CSIC), Barcelona); Jes&uacute;s Giraldo, SP2 (Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona (UAB), Barcelona); Francisco Ciruela, SP3 (Universitat de Barcelona (UB), Barcelona; Ferdinando Nicoletti, SP4 (IRCCS Neuromed, University La Sapienza, Rome) and Jean-Philippe Pin, SP5 (Institut de G&eacute;nomique Fonctionnelle (IGF), CNRS, Universit&eacute; de Montpellier, INSERM, Montpellier)</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>COLLABORATIVE RESEARCH</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	We are currently collaborating with the following researchers:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Jean-Philippe Pin</strong> and <strong>Cyril Goudet</strong>. Institut de G&eacute;nomique Fonctionnelle, CNRS UMR 5203, Universit&eacute; de Montpellier, Montpellier, France; INSERM, U661, Montpellier, France.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Michael Conn</strong>. Department of Internal Medicine, Center for Membrane Protein Research, Texas Tech University Health Sciences Center, Lubbock, TX, USA; Department of Cell Biology/Biochemistry, Center for Membrane Protein Research, Texas Tech University Health Sciences Center, Lubbock, TX, USA.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Katja Schmitz.</strong> Technische Universit&auml;t Darmstadt, Clemens-Sch&ouml;pf-Institut, Alarich-Weiss-Stra&szlig;e 4, 64287 Darmstadt, Germany.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Nuska Tschammer.</strong> Department of&nbsp; Chemistry and Pharmacy, Medicinal Chemistry,&nbsp; Emil Fischer Center, Friedrich Alexander University Schuhstra&szlig;e 19, 91052 Erlangen, Germany.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Amadeu Llebaria.</strong> Department of Biomedicinal Chemistry, Institut de Qu&iacute;mica Avan&ccedil;ada de Catalunya (IQAC-CSIC), Jordi Girona 18-26, 08034 Barcelona, Spain.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Pau Gorostiza.</strong> Institute for Bioengineering of Catalonia (IBEC) , Baldiri Reixac 15-21, Barcelona 08028, Spain.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Francisco Ciruela.</strong> Unitat de Farmacologia, Departament Patologia i Terap&egrave;utica Experimental, Facultat de Medicina, IDIBELL-Universitat de Barcelona, Barcelona, Spain.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>Alfons Macaya.</strong> Grup de Recerca en Neurologia Pedi&agrave;trica, Institut de Recerca Vall d&#39;Hebron, Universitat Aut&ograve;noma de Barcelona, Barcelona, Spain.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong><span style=\"color:#800000;\">FEATURED PUBLICATIONS</span></strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Giraldo J.<br />\n	<em>Operational models of allosteric modulation: caution is needed.</em><br />\n	Trends in Pharmacological Sciences <strong>2015</strong>;36(1):1-2</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Rovira X, Malhaire F, Scholler P, Rodrigo J, Gonzalez-Bulnes P, Llebaria A, Pin JP, Giraldo J, Goudet C<br />\n	<em>Overlapping binding sites drive allosteric agonism and positive cooperativity in type 4 metabotropic glutamate receptors</em><br />\n	The FASEB Journal <strong>2015</strong>;29(1):116-30</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp; Lans I, Dalton JA, Giraldo J<br />\n	<em>Helix 3 acts as a conformational hinge in Class A GPCR activation: An analysis of interhelical interaction energies in crystal structures.</em><br />\n	Journal of Structural Biology <strong>2015</strong>. pii: S1047-8477(15)30096-4.<em> </em></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pittolo S, G&oacute;mez-Santacana X, Eckelt K, Rovira X, Dalton J, Goudet C, Pin J-P, Llobet A, Giraldo J, Llebaria A, Gorostiza P<br />\n	<em>An allosteric modulator to control endogenous G protein-coupled receptors with light</em><br />\n	Nature Chemical Biology <strong>2014</strong>;10(10):813-5</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dalton JA, G&oacute;mez-Santacana X, Llebaria A, Giraldo J.<br />\n	<em>Computational Analysis of Negative and Positive Allosteric Modulator Binding and Function in Metabotropic Glutamate Receptor 5 (In)Activation.</em><br />\n	J Chem Inf Model. <strong>2014</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; Roche D, Gil D, and Giraldo J<br />\n	<em>Multiple active receptor conformation, agonist efficacy and maximum effect of the system: The conformation-based operational model of agonism</em><br />\n	Drug Discovery Today <strong>2013</strong>;18:365-371&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830921/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more J. Giraldo in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',30,2,2),(421,45,0,'Gemma Guillazo','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(374,1)\">Neurobiology of the normal and disturbed mind</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Neurobiology of learning and Memory</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Gemma Guillazo-Blanch</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:Gemma.Guillazo@uab.cat\">Gemma.Guillazo@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Tel:93 5812543</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-8297-7100\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/E-9765-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=6602654496\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Gemma_Guillazo-Blanch\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"29\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.mendeley.com/profiles/gemma-guillazo/\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"29\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/mendeley.png\" width=\"29\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"https://es.linkedin.com/pub/gemma-guillazo-blanch/17/492/b85\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"31\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Linkedin.jpg\" width=\"39\" /></a></td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/gemma guill.jpg\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 285px;\" /></p>\n<div>\n	<strong>Group Members:</strong></div>\n<div>\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/Catala/profile.php?id=91\">Margarita Mart&iacute;-Nicolovius</a></div>\n<div>\n	Divka Rojic&nbsp;&nbsp;Becker</div>\n<div>\n	Anna Vale Mart&iacute;nez</div>\n<div>\n	Joan Visa Bombardo</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	Our research &nbsp;project aims to investigate different brain treatments which could fundamentally enhance attention and memory processes in animal models of cognitive impairment. Such a deficit will derive from the ageing and cerebral lesions or inactivations which copy certain alterations observed in certain neurodegenerative diseases, such as Alzheimer&rsquo;s and Parkinson&rsquo;s, and clinical syndromes such as diencephalic amnesia. To this end we will use cognitive deficit models in old rats and cognitive deficit models in young rats by the infusion of cholinergic or glutamatergic antagonists in target structures of the basal forebrain (BF) or by lesions or reversible inactivations of the intralaminar thalamic nuclei (ILN). The main objective will be to revert the cognitive deterioration resulting from the normal process of ageing or induced by a lesion through intracerebral infusion, in target regions of BF and ILN, of drugs that are currently being assessed as possible cognitive enhancers: d-cycloserine or S18986 (glutamatergic enhancers) or FG7142 (GABAergic inhibitor). The effectiveness of such treatments will be assessed in behavioral models based on olfactory tasks of ethological and clinical relevance, and also in paradigms of instrumental conditioning which will allow us to evaluate attention processes, working memory and cognitive flexibility. Apart from the advance in the development of possible treatments aimed at improving certain cognitive functions, the achievement of the proposed objectives will allow us to explain the neurophysiological bases of the effects of such treatments. This information is relevant in discovering possible cerebral targets or neurochemical mechanisms on which new therapeutic methods effective in enhancing attention, memory or behavioral flexibility, among other cognitive functions, can act.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	Our main project entitled &ldquo;Attentional and memory enhancement in animal models of cognitive impairment resulting from the normal process of ageing or induced by brain lesions&rdquo; &nbsp;includes different experiments aimed at:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	1) To investigate the ability of glutamate modulators to reverse cognitive deficits in young animals with lesion or inactivation of key structures in certain neurodegenerative diseases.<br />\n	2) To investigate the ability of glutamatergic and GABAergic modulators to reverse cognitive deficits in older animals with functional alterations associated with normal aging.<br />\n	3) To study the neurophysiological mechanisms underlying the potentiation treatments of cognitive functions.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>TECHNIQUES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	The research questions stated above are investigated through c-fos expression assays, electrical stimulation, neurochemical lesions, intracerebral infusions, receptor autoradiography and in situ hybridization. The behavioral tasks are, among others, the social transmission of food preference, odor-reward discrimination, Morris water maze, visual attention and working memory in the skinner-box.<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Collaborations:</span><strong> </strong><br />\n	-Laboratorio de Psicobiolog&iacute;a, UNED, Madrid (Emilio Ambrosio, Miguel Migu&eacute;ns)<br />\n	-Divisi&oacute;n de Neurociencias, Universidad Pablo de Olavide (UPO),&nbsp;Sevilla (Dr. Delgado-Garc&iacute;a, Dra.&nbsp;Gruart)<br />\n	-IDIBAPS (Barcelona) (Dra. S&aacute;nchez-Vives)</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong><strong>LATEST PUBLICATIONS</strong></strong></span></p>\n<br />\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp; Portero-Tresserra M, Crist&oacute;bal-Narv&aacute;ez P, Mart&iacute;-Nicolovius M, Guillazo-Blanch , G, Vale-Mart&iacute;nez A. <em>D-cycloserine in prelimbic cortex reverses scopolamine-induced deficits in olfactory memory in rats. </em>PLoS One. <strong>2013</strong>, 2;8(8):e70584.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;Yefimenko N, Portero-Tresserra M, Mart&iacute;-Nicolovius M, Guillazo-Blanch G, Vale-Mart&iacute;nez A.&nbsp;(2013). <em>The AMPA receptor modulator S18986 in the prelimbic cortex enhances acquisition and retention of an odor-reward association. </em>Neurosci Lett.&nbsp;<strong>2013</strong> pii: S0304-3940(13)00467-9.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;Villarejo-Rodr&iacute;guez I, Boadas-Vaello P, Portero-Tresserra M, Vale-Mart&iacute;nez A, Mart&iacute;-Nicolovius M, Guillazo-Blanch G.<em> Learning deficits in an odor reward-task induced by parafascicular thalamic lesions are ameliorated by pretraining D-cycloserine in the prelimbic cortex. </em>Behav Brain Res.&nbsp;<strong>2013</strong> ;238:289-92.&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;Portero-Tresserra M, Mart&iacute;-Nicolovius M, Guillazo-Blanch G, Boadas-Vaello P, Vale-Mart&iacute;nez A.<em> D-cycloserine in the basolateral amygdala prevents extinction and enhances reconsolidation of odor-reward associative learning in rats.</em> Neurobiol Learn Mem.&nbsp;<strong>2013</strong>;100:1-11.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Portero-Tresserra M, Crist&oacute;bal-Narv&aacute;ez P, Mart&iacute;-Nicolovius M, Guillazo-Blanch G, Vale-Mart&iacute;nez A. D-cycloserine in prelimbic cortex reverses scopolamine-induced deficits in olfactory memory in rats. PLoS One. <strong>2013</strong>; 8(8):e70584. PMCID: PMC3732227</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830176/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more G. Guillazo in PubMed. </a></p>\n',31,2,2),(422,45,0,'Juan Hidalgo','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Neuroinflammation and Oxidative Stress</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Juan Hidalgo Pareja</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:Juan.Hidalgo@uab.cat\">Juan.Hidalgo@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 812 037</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0003-0921-1122\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/C-9082-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7101787664\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Juan_Hidalgo5\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/JHidalgoFotogrupo.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	Gemma Comes Orpinell<br />\n	Merc&egrave; Giralt Carbonell<br />\n	Amalia Molinero Egea<br />\n	Olaya Fern&aacute;ndez Gayol<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Former group members:</strong><br />\n	Mar&iacute;a Erta Caba&ntilde;ate<br />\n	Beatriz Ferrer Villahoz<br />\n	Javier Carrasco Trancoso<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	The fundamental objectives&nbsp; of the Group are centred in the study of the basic mechanisms underlying neuroinflammation and oxidative stress, with a particular emphasis in the role of the cytokine interleukin 6 (IL-6) in animal models of neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer disease and multiple sclerosis (MS) and in animal models of traumatic brain lesion.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	1. Traumatic brain injury (TBI) is one of the main causes of death and disability, especially among young people. Cytokines such as IL-6 and TNF&alpha; are involved in the response of the CNS to brain injury; by means of conditional KO mice produced in our laboratory we will analyze the importance of the cellular sources of IL-6 in a model of TBI. Moreover, by using conditional KO mice for the receptor of IL-6 we will also determine the importance of the specific cellular response to IL-6. At this time we are focusing in the main glial cell, the astrocyte.<br />\n	2. Alzheimer disease models. One of the animal models of Alzheimer disease more often used in the APP2576 mouse; the importance of oxidative stress in this model is being evaluated by analyzing the phenotype of the APP mice crossed with mice with altered expression of the antioxidant protein metallothionein.<br />\n	3. Animal models of Multiple Sclerosis (MS). There are a number of models of MS, being Experimental Autoimmune Encephalytis (EAE) one of the more studied. We will evaluate the importance of the cytokine IL-6 in this model by using transgenic mice (see 1).<br />\n	4. Exercise and obesity. The importance of IL-6 in the response to exercise and diet-induced obesity.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>LATEST PUBLICATIONS </strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull; Giralt M, Ramos R, Quintana A, Ferrer B, Erta M, Castro-Freire M, Comes G, Sanz E, Unzeta M, Pifarr&eacute; P, Garc&iacute;a A, Campbell IL, <strong>Hidalgo J</strong>. Induction of atypical EAE mediated by transgenic production of IL-6 in astrocytes in the absence of systemic IL-6. Glia 61 (<strong>2013</strong>) 587-600.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>&bull; </strong>Pifarr&eacute; P, Gutierrez-Mecinas M, Prado J, Usero L, Roura-Mir C, Giralt M, <strong>Hidalgo J</strong>, Garc&iacute;a A. Phosphodiesterase 5 inhibition at disease onset prevents experimental autoimmune encephalomyelitis progression through immunoregulatory and neuroprotective actions. Exp. Neurol. 251 (<strong>2014</strong>) 58-71.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<strong>&bull; </strong>Campbell IL, Erta M, Lim SL, Frausto R, May U, Rose-John S, Scheller J, <strong>Hidalgo J</strong>. Trans-signaling is a dominant mechanism for the pathogenic actions of interleukin-6 in the brain. J. Neurosci. 34 (<strong>2014</strong>) 2503-2513.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp; Ferrer B, Navia B, Giralt M, Comes G, Carrasco J, Molinero A, Quintana A, Se&ntilde;ar&iacute;s R, <strong>Hidalgo J.</strong> Muscle-specific interleukin-6 deletion influences body weight and body fat in a sex-dependent manner. Brain, Behav. Immun. 40 (<strong>2014</strong>) 121-130.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp; Manso Y, Comes G, L&oacute;pez-Ramos JC, Belfiore M, Molinero A, Giralt M, Carrasco J, Adlard PA, Bush AI, Delgado-Garc&iacute;a JM, <strong>Hidalgo J</strong>. Overexpression of metallothionein-1 modulates the phenotype of the Tg2576 mouse model of Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease. J. Alzheimer&rsquo;s Dis. 51 (<strong>2016</strong>) 81-95.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830937/public/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>See more J.Hidalgo in PubMed.</strong></a></p>\n',32,2,2),(423,45,0,'Marcel Jiménez','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Neurogastroenterology</span></h2>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Marcel &nbsp;Jim&eacute;nez Farrerons</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:Marcel.Jimenez@uab.cat\">Marcel.Jimenez@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 811 566</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-6602-7332\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://:%20http://www.researcherid.com/rid/C-6995-2008\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=35551030000\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Marcdef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	M&ordf; Teresa Mart&iacute;n Ib&aacute;&ntilde;ez</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	Our goal of research is focussed on the study of gastrointestinal motility in physiologic conditions and in several pathologic states. Our studies are performed in human tissue and in animal models of disease. Our main research is based on the study of neurogastroenterology from different point of views including neurotransmission in the enteric nervous system, pacemaker activity and relationship between the immune system and the enteric nervous system.<br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	&bull; Gastrointestinal motility: Study of gastrointestinal motility and its hormonal and nervous regulation. Pharmacologic studies.<br />\n	&bull; Neurogastroenterology: Pacemaker function, relation-ship between motor neurons and smooth muscle. Interstitial Cells of Cajal (ICC).<br />\n	&bull; Nitric Oxide. Role of NO in the regulation of gastrointestinal motility in normal and inflamed tissue. Mechanism of action. Inhibitors of NO synthesis.<br />\n	&bull; Mast Cells. Study of mast cells from intestinal mucosa and its role in inflammatory processes and allergy in the gastrointestinal tract.<br />\n	&bull; Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS). Development of animal models to study the impairment of gastrointestinal motility in IBS. Pharmacological approach of treatment of IBS.<br />\n	&bull; Inflammatory bowel disease: Development of animal models to study the impairment of gastrointestinal motility in intestinal inflammation. Pharmacological approach of the treatment of altered motor patterns during intestinal inflammation.<br />\n	&bull; Diabetic Neuropathy. Impairment of gastrointestinal motility in Diabetes, histopathological approach and study of relationship between motor neurons and smooth muscle in animal models of diabetes.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Gallego D, Gil V, Martinez-Cutillas M, Mane N, Martin MT, Jimenez M. <em>Purinergic neuromuscular transmission is absent in the colon of P2Y(1) knocked out mice.</em><br />\n	J Physiol <strong>2012</strong>;590(Pt 8):1943-1956.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Lies B, Gil V, Groneberg D, Seidler B, Saur D, Wischmeyer E, Jimenez M, Friebe A.<br />\n	<em>Interstitial cells of Cajal mediate nitrergic inhibitory neurotransmission in the murine gastrointestinal tract. </em><br />\n	Am J Physiol Gastrointest Liver Physiol <strong>2014</strong>;307(1):G98-106.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Mane N, Gil V, Martinez-Cutillas M, Martin MT, Gallego D, Jimenez M. <em>Dynamics of inhibitory co-transmission, membrane potential and pacemaker activity determine neuromyogenic function in the rat colon. </em>Pflugers Arch <strong>2014</strong>.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Mane N, Gil V, Martinez-Cutillas M, Clav&eacute; P, Gallego D, Jimenez M. <em>Differential functional role of purinergic and nitrergic inhibitory cotransmitters in human colonic relaxation.</em><br />\n	Acta Physiologica (Oxf) <strong>2014</strong> Dec;212(4):293-305.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Jim&eacute;nez M, Clav&eacute; P, Accarino A, Gallego D.<br />\n	<em>Purinergic neuromuscular transmission in the gastrointestinal tract; functional basis for future clinical and pharmacological studies</em>. &nbsp;<br />\n	Br J Pharmacol. <strong>2014</strong> Oct;171(19):4360-75</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830944/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more M. Jimenez in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',33,2,2),(424,45,0,'José M. Lizcano & Nestor Gómez','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Protein kinases and signal transduction</span></h2>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leaders:</strong></p>\n<table style=\"width: 100%;\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Jose Miguel Lizcano&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				N&eacute;stor Gomez</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:josemiguel.lizcano@uab.cat\">josemiguel.lizcano@uab.cat </a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"http://nestor.gomez@uab.cat\">Nestor.gomez@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 813 076&nbsp;</td>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 935 813 076</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table align=\"left\">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-3154-5383\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/E-6080-2010\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=55226571500\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jose_Lizcano?ev=prf_highl\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/profile/view?trk=tab_pro&amp;id=106361868\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Linkedin.jpg\" style=\"width: 31px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7102745796\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Imagen_grupo_con_logos_para_Web_INC.jpg\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 351px;\" /></p>\n<div>\n	<strong>Group members:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><br />\n	Dra. Tatiana Erazo&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\n	Pau Mu&ntilde;oz Guardiola&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Nora Di&eacute;guez&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Rub&eacute;n Melgarejo &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Elisabet Meg&iacute;as</div>\n<div>\n	Valeria Rizzuto</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Past members:</strong><br />\n	Dra. Ana Moreno Iglesias<br />\n	Dra. Margarita Espona</div>\n<div>\n	Dra. Arantza Rodr&iacute;guez Asia&iacute;n</div>\n<div>\n	Dr. Gerad Ruiz Babot</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<em>Protein kinases and signal transduction in cancer</em></p>\n<p>\n	Nearly all aspects of cell life are controlled by the reversible phosphorylation of proteins. Therefore, our understanding of the molecular control of cell physiology requires the identification of the substrates targeted by specific protein kinases. Many studies have identified alterations in genes that encode kinases, which cause diseases such cancer or neurodegenerative diseases. Our research is focused on dissecting new cellular signaling pathways that control cancer cell proliferation and differentiation. We study the new protein kinases ERK5 (a MAP kinase) and the tumor suppressor LKB1, but we are also interested in the Akt-mTORC1 pathway.We collaborate with BioPhama Companies in the preclinical development of new antitumoral drugs.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	We use two different perspectives to approach fundamental problems:<br />\n	<br />\n	1) Basic Research. Dissection of the mechanisms by which LKB1, Akt and ERK5 kinases exert a control on the proliferation and survival of tumor cells. We have contributed to propose new molecular mechanism for regulation of protein kinase Akt; discovered that tumor suppressor kinase LKB1 functions as a master kinase; or more recently, we have established a new mechanism by which ERK5 translocates to the nucleus and regulates the proliferation of tumor cells regardless of its enzymatic activity.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	2) Research directed to pharmacological intervention in cancer. We are involved in potentiating translational aspects of our resources. We actively collaborate with Ability Pharmaceuticals SL in the preclinical/clinical development of the new antitumor drug ABTL0812, which it just finished Clinical Trial Phase I/Ib, first-in-humans (NCT02201823) in cancer patients with solid tumors. We have discovered a new cellular signaling pathway by which ABTL0812 exerts its antitumor action: ABTL0812 activates PPARa/g-mediated transcription of TRIB3 pseudokinase, which in turn binds and inhibits Akt resulting in mTORC1 inhibition, growth arrest and autophagy-mediated cancer cell death. Finally we actively collaborate with other academic laboratories characterizing new ERK5 inhibitors that show anti-tumor activity.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>FEATURED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Erazo T, Lorente M, L&oacute;pez-Plana A, Mu&ntilde;oz-Guardiola P&hellip;, Lizcano JM.<em> The New Antitumor Drug ABTL0812 Inhibits the Akt/mTORC1 Axis by Upregulating Tribbles-3 Pseudokinase. </em>Clinical Cancer Research 2015 Dec 15. [Epub ahead of print]. <strong>2016&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Erazo T, Moreno A, Ruiz-Babot G, Rodr&iacute;guez-Asiain A, Morrice NA, Espadamala J, Bayascas JR, G&oacute;mez N, Lizcano JM. <em>Canonical and kinase activity-independent mechanisms for extracellular signal-regulated kinase 5 (ERK5) nuclear translocation require dissociation of Hsp90 from the ERK5-Cdc37 complex. </em>Molecular&nbsp;and Cellular Biology&nbsp;33:1671-86. <strong>2013&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Elkins JM, Wang J, Deng X, Pattison MJ, Arthur JS, Erazo T, Gomez N, Lizcano JM, Gray NS, Knapp S. <em>X-ray crystal structure of ERK5 (MAPK7) in complex with a specific inhibitor. </em>Journal of Medicinal Chemistry&nbsp;56:4413-21. <strong>2013 </strong></p>\n<p>\n	&bull;&nbsp; Villagrasa P, D&iacute;az VM, Vi&ntilde;as-Castells R, Peir&oacute; S, Del Valle-P&eacute;rez B, Dave N, Rodr&iacute;guez-Asiain A, Casal JI, Lizcano JM, Du&ntilde;ach M, Garc&iacute;a de Herreros A. <em>Akt2 interacts with Snail1 in the E-cadherin promoter. </em>Oncogene 31:4022-33. <strong>2012</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp; Lizcano JM, Goransson O, Toth R, Deak M, Morrice NA, Boudeau J, Hawley SA, Udd L, Makela TP, Hardie DG, Alessi DR. <em>LKB1 is a master kinase that activates 13 kinases of the AMPK subfamily,including MARK/PAR1 </em>EMBO Journal 23: 833-43. <strong>2004</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830948/public/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>See more JM. Lizcano in PubMed.</strong></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830954/public/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>See more N. G&oacute;mez in PubMed. </strong></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong><span style=\"color:#800000;\">ONGOING PROJECTS</span></strong></p>\n<div>\n	<em>Nuevas aproximaciones terap&eacute;uticas basadas en derivados de &aacute;cidos grasos esenciales dirigidos a enfermedades oncol&oacute;gicas y neurol&oacute;gicas no cubiertas.</em></div>\n<div>\n	Ministerio de Econom&iacute;a y Competitividad. Programa INNPACTO&nbsp; (Ref IPT-2012-0614-010000)</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<em>Desarrollo de nuevas herramientas farmacol&oacute;gicas antitumorales que dirijan su acci&oacute;n al silenciamiento o a la inhibici&oacute;n de la MAP kinasa ERK5. </em></div>\n<div>\n	Ministerio de Econom&iacute;a y Competitividad. Plan Nacional de I+D+I 2016-2018. Programa Biomedicina (Ref SAF2015-64237-R).</div>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n',34,2,2),(425,45,0,'José Manuel López','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Stress protein Kinases</span></h2>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Jos&eacute; Manuel L&oacute;pez</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:josemanuel.lopez@uab.es\">josemanuel.lopez@uab.es</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Tel: 935 814 278</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-4104-6262\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"28\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" width=\"28\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/D-1654-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"28\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" width=\"28\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=55685078300&amp;amp;eid=2-s2.0-84865604296\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/JMBladef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	Nabil Ben Messaoud<br />\n	Jicheng Yue</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	Functioning as sensors and switches, protein kinases play a critical role in the regulation of cell fate decisions. Our research group is interested in the control of apoptosis and meiosis by stress protein kinases and we use Xenopus oocytes as a cell model to study the mechanisms that govern these irreversible biological processes. We also want to investigate how the accumulation of a nucleotide (ZMP) and the activation of a stress protein kinase (AMPK) can influence the development of Lesch Nyhan disease, a severe neurological disorder in the man.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	1) To study the function of stress protein kinases in cell death and meiosis.&nbsp;The aim of this project is to determine the role of the stress protein kinases AMPK, JNK and p38 during oocyte death induced by osmotic shock and during meiotic progression induced by progesterone. We will study in detail the regulation of citochrome c release and caspase activation by these protein kinases. We will also investigate the role of AMPK and JNK in translational control during meiotic progression. We use as a model system Xenopus oocytes, which have great advantages for biochemical manipulation.<br />\n	2) To study the role of ZMP accumulation and AMPK activation on the development of Lesch-Nyhan disease. Lesch-Nyhan disease is an illness with severe neurological effects as a consequence of a deficiency in the purine savage enzyme hypoxanthine-guanine phosphoribosyltransferase (HPRT). How a simple alteration in the purine metabolism produces dramatic effects in human behaviour is still a mystery. HPRT deficiency is associated with a relatively selective dysfunction of brain dopamine systems. Different hypotheses have been suggested, some of them claiming for the accumulation of a toxic metabolite in the brain. We propose that ZMP is the toxic agent, and acting by a pleiotropic effect would induce several changes in the cell, accounting for brain dysfunction. One of the initial changes would be the activation of the stress sensor AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK).<br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>FEATURED PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Yue J, L&oacute;pez JM. <em>JNK does not regulate meiotic progression in</em>&nbsp;<em>Xenopus</em>&nbsp;<em>oocytes: The strange case of pJNK and pERK. </em>Dev Biol. 416: 42-51, <strong>2016</strong>.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Yue J, Ben Messaoud N, L&oacute;pez JM. <em>Hyperosmotic Shock Engages Two Positive Feedback Loops through Caspase-3-dependent Proteolysis of JNK1-2 and Bid. </em>J Biol Chem. 290: 30375-89, <strong>2015</strong>.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Ben Messaoud N, Katzarova I, L&oacute;pez JM. <em>Basic Properties of the p38 Signaling Pathway in Response to Hyperosmotic Shock. </em>PLoS One. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0135249, <strong>2015</strong>.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Ben Messaoud N, Yue J, Valent D, Katzarova I, L&oacute;pez JM. <em>Osmostress-induced apoptosis in</em>&nbsp;<em>Xenopus</em>&nbsp;<em>oocytes: role of stress protein kinases, calpains and Smac/DIABLO. </em>PLoS One. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0124482, <strong>2015</strong>..</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;L&oacute;pez JM.<br />\n	<em>Digital kinases: A cell model for sensing, integrating and making choices.</em><br />\n	Communicative &amp; Integrative Biology. 3: 146-150,&nbsp;<strong>2010</strong>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marti&aacute;&ntilde;ez T, Franc&egrave;s S, L&oacute;pez JM.&nbsp;<br />\n	<em>Generation of digital responses in stress sensors.&nbsp;</em><br />\n	Journal of Biological Chemistry. 284: 23902-23911,&nbsp;<strong>2009</strong>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;Piqu&eacute; M, L&oacute;pez JM, Sylvain F, Guig&oacute; R, M&eacute;ndez R.&nbsp;<br />\n	<em>A combinatorial code for CPE-mediated translational control.&nbsp;</em><br />\n	Cell. 132: 434-448,<strong>2008</strong>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830965/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more JM. L&oacute;pez in PubMed.</a></p>\n',35,2,2),(426,45,0,'Vicente Martínez & Patrocinio Vergara','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(372,1); \">Neurodegeneration and ageing</a></p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Neuroinmunogastroenterology and Gut Microbiota</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leaders:</strong></p>\n<table style=\"width: 100%;\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Vicente Mart&iacute;nez&nbsp; Perea</td>\n			<td>\n				Patrocinio Vergara Esteras</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:vicente.martinez@uab.cat\">vicente.martinez@uab.cat</a></td>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:patri.vergara@uab.cat\">patri.vergara@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 93 581 3834</td>\n			<td>\n				TEL: +34 93 581 1848</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table height=\"25\" width=\"40\">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n				<table>\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0002-9220-6406\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"28\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" width=\"28\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/M-6468-2013\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"27\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" width=\"27\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=7006757890\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"30\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" width=\"30\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/Martvergdef.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group members:</strong><br />\n	Sergio Berd&uacute;n Mar&iacute;n<br />\n	Eva Maria Cepeda Romero<br />\n	Javier Est&eacute;vez Medina<br />\n	Marina Ferrer Clotas<br />\n	Sergio L&oacute;pez Est&eacute;vez<br />\n	Emma Mart&iacute;nez P&eacute;rez<br />\n	Maria Asunci&oacute;n Molina Romero</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	Our research interests are focussed on the field of enteric neurosciences, particularly on the study of neuro-immune interactions within the gastrointestinal tract, including interactions with gut commensal microbiota. Our final goal is to understand the pathophysiological mechanisms that underlay human functional and inflammatory gastrointestinal disorders and to identify and characterize potential sites and targets for intervention.<br />\n	We have a multidisciplinary approach that integrates in vivo work in animal models with cellular/molecular techniques.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	- Development and characterization of animal models of gastrointestinal disorders: Inflammatory Bowel Disease and Irritable Bowel Syndrome.<br />\n	- Implications of mast cells in the neuro-endocrine control in inflammatory and allergy-related gastrointestinal disorders.<br />\n	- Mast cells and neuronal remodelling within the gastrointestinal tract.<br />\n	- Mechanisms and pharmacology of visceral pain arising from the gut.<br />\n	- Intestinal microbiota: Relationship with visceral sensory mechanisms and intestinal barrier function.<br />\n	- Brain-gut axis: Effects of stress on gastrointestinal function.<br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>REPRESENTATIVE PUBLICATIONS</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Jard&iacute; F, Fern&aacute;ndez-Blanco JA, <strong>Mart&iacute;nez V</strong>, <strong>Vergara P</strong>. Persistent alterations in colonic afferent innervation in a rat model of postinfectious gut dysfunction: Role for changes in peripheral neurotrophic factors. Neurogastroenterol Motil. <strong>2016 </strong>Gen; <span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial, helvetica, clean, sans-serif; font-size: 11.999px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 16.6138px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 1; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">28(5):693-704. doi: 10.1111/nmo.12766. Epub 2016</span>.</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Fern&aacute;ndez-Blanco JA, Est&eacute;vez J, Shea-Donohue T, <strong>Mart&iacute;nez V</strong>, <strong>Vergara P</strong>. Changes in Epithelial Barrier Function in Response to Parasitic Infection: Implications for IBD Pathogenesis. J Crohns Colitis. <strong>2015 </strong>Jun; 9(6):463&ndash;76. doi: 10.1093/ecco-jcc/jjv056. Epub 2015.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Berd&uacute;n S, Rychter J, <strong>Vergara P</strong>. Effects of nerve growth factor antagonist k252a on peritoneal mast cell degranulation: implications for rat postoperative ileus. American Journal of Physiology - Gastrointestinal and Liver Physiology&nbsp;<strong>2015 </strong>Sep; 309 G801-6. doi:10.1152/ajpgi.00152.2015</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Jardi F, Aguilera M, <strong>Vergara P, Martinez V</strong>. Lipopolysaccharides facilitate colonic motor alterations associated to the sensitization to a luminal antigen in rats. J Neurogastroenterol Motil. <strong>2015 </strong>Mar; 21(2):222&ndash;35. doi: 10.5056/jnm14136</p>\n<p>\n	&bull; Rychter J, Ortega O, Berdun S, Arenas C, Lopez I, Espin F, <strong>Vergara P</strong>, et al. Mast cell degranulation inhibits motor patterns of human ileum and sigmoid colon in vitro: relevance for postoperative ileus. Neurogastroenterol Motil. <strong>2015</strong> Aug; 27(8):1098&ndash;109. doi: 10.1111/nmo.12589. Epub 2015</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830977/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more V, Mart&iacute;nez in PubMed.</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/myncbi/14Q9ynJ9y7CAT/collections/48830981/public/\" target=\"_blank\">See more P. Vergara in PubMed.</a></p>\n',36,2,2),(428,45,0,'Xavier Navarro','<p>\n	<a href=\"javascript:MostraPage(373,1); \">Neuroregeneration and repair</a></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\">Neuroplasticity and Regeneration</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<strong>Group leader:</strong></p>\n<table>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				Xavier Navarro</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<a href=\"mailto:xavier.navarro@uab.cat\">xavier.navarro@uab.cat</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				TEL. +34 93 581 1966</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n				<table height=\"63\" width=\"94\">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://orcid.org/0000-0001-9849-902X\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/orcid.png\" style=\"width: 26px; height: 26px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researcherid.com/rid/C-9577-2011\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/RID.jpg\" style=\"width: 25px; height: 25px;\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href=\"http://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.url?authorId=22944812800\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/scopus.jpg\" style=\"width: 29px; height: 29px;\" /></a></p>\n							</td>\n							<td>\n								<a href=\"http://www.researchgate.net/profile/Xavier_Navarro\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"32\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/researchgate.jpg\" width=\"29\" /></a></td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n							<td>\n								&nbsp;</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pagines/XNavarro2014.JPG\" style=\"width: 75%; float: left;\" /></h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">\n	<strong>Senior researchers:</strong><br />\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/profile.php?id=38\"><span style=\"color:#000000;\">Caty Casas</span></a><br />\n	Jordi Cuadras<br />\n	Guillermo Garc&iacute;a-Alias<br />\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/profile.php?id=88\"><span style=\"color:#000000;\">Ruben L&oacute;pez-Vales</span></a><br />\n	<span style=\"color:#000000;\"> </span><a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/profile.php?id=135\"><span style=\"color:#000000;\">Esther Udina</span></a><br />\n	<strong>Associated teachers:</strong><br />\n	Jordi Bruna<br />\n	Roser Velasco<br />\n	Jorge J.Vilches<br />\n	<strong>Posdoctoral researchers:</strong><br />\n	<span style=\"color:#000000;\">&nbsp; </span><a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/Castellano/profile.php?id=54\"><span style=\"color:#000000;\">Jaume Del Valle</span></a><br />\n	Ignacio Delgado&nbsp;<br />\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/profile.php?id=78\"><span style=\"color:#000000;\">Joaquim Hern&aacute;ndez</span></a><br />\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/profile.php?id=78\">Mireia Herrando</a><br />\n	<strong>Pre PhD researchers:</strong><br />\n	Jes&uacute;s Amo<br />\n	Ariadna Arbat<br />\n	Isaac Francos<br />\n	Tatiana Leiva<br />\n	V&iacute;ctor L&oacute;pez<br />\n	Clara L&oacute;pez<br />\n	Anna Mart&iacute;nez<br />\n	Guillem M&ograve;dol<br />\n	Natalia de la Oliva<br />\n	Maria Puigdom&egrave;nech<br />\n	David Romeo<br />\n	Alba Sanchez<br />\n	Irene Sanchez<br />\n	Daniel Santos<br />\n	<strong>Collaborator researchers:</strong><br />\n	Jordi Badia<br />\n	Joaquim For&eacute;s<br />\n	<strong>Technicians:</strong><br />\n	Israel Blasco<br />\n	M&oacute;nica Espejo<br />\n	J&egrave;sica Jaramillo</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES</strong></span><br />\n	<span id=\"cke_bm_264E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n	The Group of Neuroplasticity and Regeneration of the UAB is a multidisciplinary research group working on regeneration and recovery after peripheral nerve and spinal cord lesions and neurodegenerative diseases. The members of the group have combined expertise in microsurgery, neurophysiology, morphology, cell culture, molecular neurobiology and bioelectronics. The research projects of the group during the last years have dealt with: regeneration and reinnervation after peripheral nerve injuries, biocompatible artificial nerve grafts, glial cell transplants for the repair of injuries in the peripheral and central nervous system, and neural electrodes for interfacing the injured nervous system. The group has established cooperative research in clinical neurosciences, particularly on new nerve repair therapies with the Hospital Clinic of Barcelona, and in modulation of neural plasticity after brain and spinal cord lesions with the Institute Guttmann of Neurorehabilitation.<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"> <span id=\"cke_bm_265S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>MAIN RESEARCH LINES</strong></span><br />\n	<span id=\"cke_bm_265E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Regeneration and reinnervation after peripheral nerve injuries.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Physiopathology and treatment of neuropathic pain.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Evaluation and physiopathology of peripheral neuropathies.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Molecular and cellular mechanisms in motoneuron degeneration.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Development of biocompatible artificial nerve grafts.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Glial cell and stem cell transplants for the repair of spinal cord injuries.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Modulation of the inflammatory response in CNS injuries.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Evaluation of neural interfaces for neuroprostheses in rehabilitation of the injured nervous system.<br />\n	<br />\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><span id=\"cke_bm_266S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span> </span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>RESEARCH PROJECTS IN THE LAST 4 YEARS</strong></span><br />\n	<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project PI060201, <em>Fondo de Investigaci&oacute;n Sanitaria, Inst Salud Carlos III</em>, 2007-09. &ldquo;Transplantes gliales combinados con neuroprotecci&oacute;n y restituci&oacute;n neuronal para la reparaci&oacute;n de lesiones de ra&iacute;ces espinales&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project SAF2006-08682, <em>Ministerio de Educaci&oacute;n y Ciencia,</em> 2007-09. &ldquo;Terapia f&aacute;rmaco-celular para la reparaci&oacute;n de la m&eacute;dula espinal lesionada&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project 070210, <em>Fundaci&oacute; La Marat&oacute;TV3,</em> 2008-2010. &quot;Trasplantes celulares y tratamiento farmacol&oacute;gico para reducir el dolor neurop&aacute;tico en lesiones de m&eacute;dula espinal&quot;<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Group member of<em> Centro de Investigaci&oacute;n Biom&eacute;dica en Red sobre Enfermedades Neurodegenerativas (CIBERNED)</em>, <em>Inst Salud Carlos III</em>, 2008-2014. CB06/05/1105.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Group member of <em>Red de Terapia Celular</em> RD06/0010/1004, <em>Instituto de Salud Carlos III,</em> 2008-2012.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project FP7 ICT-224012, <em>Comission of the European Communities</em>, 2008-2012. &ldquo;Transverse, Intrafascicular Multichannel Electrode system for induction of sensation and treatment of phantom limb pain in amputees (TIME)&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Marie Curie Initial Training Network, FP7- MC-214003-2, <em>European Commission</em>, 2008-2012. &ldquo;Axonal regeneration, plasticity and stem cells (AXREGEN)&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project PI080598, <em>Fondo de Investigaci&oacute;n Sanitaria, Inst Salud Carlos III</em>, 2008-10. &ldquo;Efectos de la estimulaci&oacute;n el&eacute;ctrica del nervio perif&eacute;rico sobre la plasticidad de los circuitos espinales y la regeneraci&oacute;n axonal despu&eacute;s de lesiones nerviosas o medulares&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research grant, <em>Fundaci&oacute;n Mapfre</em>, 2009. &ldquo;Administraci&oacute;n de AB-cristalina como terapia protectora de las lesiones de la m&eacute;dula espinal&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project WFL-SE-008/09, <em>Wings for Life Foundation</em>, 2009-10. &ldquo;Role of lysophosphatidic acid in the pathophysiology of spinal cord injury&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project SAF2009-12495, <em>Ministerio de Ciencia e Innovacion</em>, 2010-12. &ldquo;Respuesta medular al trasplante de glia envolvente y de c&eacute;lulas estromales de la m&eacute;dula &oacute;sea: estudios in vitro e in vivo&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project PIRG05-GA-2009-249274, <em>Marie-Curie International Reintegration Grant</em>, European Commission FP7, 2010-2014. &ldquo;Role of lysophosphatidic acid in the pathophysiology of spinal cord injury (ROLPASCI)&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bolsas de Doutoramento e P&oacute;s-Doutoramento 2011, <em>Funda&ccedil;&atilde;o para a Ci&ecirc;ncia e a Tecnologia, Minist&eacute;rio da Ci&ecirc;ncia, Tecnologia e Ensino Superior de Portugal</em>, 2011-2013. &ldquo;Dissecting the mechanisms of microglia response, determinants and biomarkers in Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project SAF2010-17851, <em>Ministerio de Ciencia e Innovacion</em>, 2011-13. &ldquo;Activaci&oacute;n de los programas de resoluci&oacute;n de la inflamaci&oacute;n como nueva terapia neuroprotectora para tratar las lesiones agudas de la m&eacute;dula espinal&rdquo;.<br />\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; Research project IRP Research Grant P123, <em>International Foundat