\'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">Centre for Biological Sciences</span></span></div>\n				<div>\n					<span style=\"font-size: 10px;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'lucida sans unicode\', \'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">University of Southampton, UK</span></span></div>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td style=\"text-align: center; vertical-align: top;\">\n				<p>\n					<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Pin end.jpg\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 130px;\" /></p>\n				<div>\n					<span style=\"font-size: 11px;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'lucida sans unicode\', \'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">Dr. Jean-Philippe Pin</span></span></div>\n				<div>\n					<span style=\"font-size: 9px;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'lucida sans unicode\', \'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">D&eacute;partement Neuroscience</span></span></div>\n				<div>\n					<span style=\"font-size: 10px;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'lucida sans unicode\', \'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">Institut de G&eacute;nomique Fonctionnelle</span></span></div>\n				<div>\n					<span style=\"font-size: 10px;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'lucida sans unicode\', \'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">Montpellier, France</span></span></div>\n			</td>\n			<td style=\"text-align: center; vertical-align: top;\">\n				<p>\n					<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/John Salamone end.jpg\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 130px;\" /></p>\n				<div>\n					<span style=\"font-size: 11px;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'lucida sans unicode\', \'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">Dr. John Salamone</span></span></div>\n				<div>\n					<span style=\"font-size: 9px;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'lucida sans unicode\', \'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">Department of Psychology</span></span></div>\n				<div>\n					<span style=\"font-size: 10px;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'lucida sans unicode\', \'lucida grande\', sans-serif;\">University of Connecticut, NJ, USA</span></span></div>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	It is the first time that members of the Board visited us and this is a great opportunity for our Institute to improve our future plans. The fact that their visit coincides with our&nbsp;<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/English/index.php#!/12-13th%20May%202016_747_1\" target=\"_blank\">Scientific Conferences</a>&nbsp;will facilitate them to know more closely the work we do. Given his wide experience, they can offer us advice on many aspects to improve:</p>\n<p>\n	In terms of research, we want to promote synergies with other research centres and, therefore, our internationalization. Regarding teaching, we plan to promote exchanges with other institutions and increase the mobility of our Master and PhD students and Postdocs. In terms of transfer, we are encouraging translation of experimental results to clinical and productive sectors. Finally, we want to enhance our outreach to society and improve communication strategies.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	During their stay, the members of the board will attend some sessions of the conferences and will meet with the management team and with other levels of the organization: group leaders, young researchers recently incorporated, lab technicians, administrative staff and students of Master and PhD. We welcome the Board to our Institute.</p>\n',100,2,2),(771,30,0,'Pint of Science 2016','<p>\n	El festival<u> <a href=\"https://pintofscience.es/events/barcelona\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Pint of science</em></a> </u>es celebra en diferents ciutats de diversos pa&iuml;sos del m&oacute;n. <em>Pint of science</em> va n&eacute;ixer l&rsquo;any 2013 com una forma d&rsquo;apropar la ci&egrave;ncia i els cient&iacute;fics als ciutadans; per aix&ograve; les trobades es fan en bars, facilitant en aquest ambient m&eacute;s relaxat una m&eacute;s gran complicitat entre els investigadors i el p&uacute;blic.</p>\n<p>\n	Enguany, l&rsquo;Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies s&rsquo;ha afegit&nbsp; a aquesta festa i cinc dels seus investigadors participaran en tres trobades que reben el nom gen&egrave;ric de <em>Ment meravellosa</em>.</p>\n<p>\n	Les trobades es faran al <u><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/BaliusBar/\" target=\"_blank\">Balius Bar</a></u>, a les 20 hores, al carrer de Pujades, 196 de Barcelona, al Poble Nou.</p>\n<p>\n	Dilluns, 23, el<span id=\"cke_bm_661S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span id=\"cke_bm_657S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span id=\"cke_bm_655S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span> <strong>Dr. Albert Quintana</strong><span id=\"cke_bm_661E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span id=\"cke_bm_657E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span id=\"cke_bm_655E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span> (@quintanalab) i el<span id=\"cke_bm_662S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span id=\"cke_bm_658S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span> <strong>Dr. Ra&uacute;l Delgado </strong><span id=\"cke_bm_662E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span id=\"cke_bm_658E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span>(de l&rsquo;IDIBELL), ens parlaran a &ldquo;Decons<span id=\"cke_bm_656E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span>truyendo el cerebro&rdquo; del funcionament b&agrave;sic del cervell i de com estem aprenent a desxifrar-lo.</p>\n<p>\n	Dimarts, 24, la <span id=\"cke_bm_663S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span id=\"cke_bm_659S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><strong>Dra. Roser Nadal</strong><span id=\"cke_bm_663E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span id=\"cke_bm_659E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span> (@RoserNadal) i el<strong> <span id=\"cke_bm_664S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span>Dr. Antonio Armario</strong> <span id=\"cke_bm_664E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span>ens explicaran a &ldquo;Cerebros al bo<span id=\"cke_bm_660E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span>rde de un ataque de estr&eacute;s&rdquo; de qu&egrave; &eacute;s l&rsquo;estr&egrave;s, quins factors el provoquen i quines conseq&uuml;&egrave;ncies negatives pot tenir.</p>\n<p>\n	Dimecres, 25, el<span id=\"cke_bm_665S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span> <strong>Dr. Jos&eacute; Agu<span id=\"cke_bm_665E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span>ilera</strong> i la <strong>Dra.&nbsp;Ana Candalija</strong>, a &ldquo;Botox y <span id=\"cke_bm_666E\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span>otras toxinas, algo m&aacute;s que est&egrave;tica&rdquo; ens donaran a con&egrave;ixer toxines bacterianes que tamb&eacute; tenen un gran potencial com a f&agrave;rmacs, m&eacute;s enll&agrave; dels usos que coneixem m&eacute;s popularment.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<span style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/0001.jpg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 492px;\" /><span style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n',105,2,0),(772,45,0,'Pint of Science 2016','<p>\n	<u><a href=\"https://pintofscience.es/events/barcelona\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Pint of science</em></a></u>&nbsp;have been celebrated around the world since 2013 as a way to bring science closer to people. For this, the talks are in pubs, in a relaxing atmosphere to create more complicity between researchers and the audience.</p>\n<p>\n	This year, thanks to the <em>CORE de Salut Mental</em>, the Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies has joined to the party and five researchers will participate at the <u><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/BaliusBar/\" target=\"_blank\">Balius Bar</a></u> (20h, c/Pujades, 196. Poble Nou, Barcelona.</p>\n<p>\n	Monday 23th <strong>Dr Albert Quintana</strong> (@quintanalab) and <strong>Dr Ra&uacute;l Delgado </strong>(IDIBELL), will talk in &ldquo;Deconstruyendo el cerebro&rdquo; about how the brain works and how researchers are deciphering it.</p>\n<p>\n	Tuesday 24th, <strong>Dr Roser Nadal</strong> (@RoserNadal) and <strong>Dr Antonio Armario</strong> in &ldquo;Cerebros al borde de un ataque de estr&eacute;s&rdquo; will explain what stress, what aret he cause factors and what consequences can involve.</p>\n<p>\n	Wednesday 25<sup>th</sup>, <strong>Dr. Jos&eacute; Aguilera</strong>and <strong>Dra.&nbsp;Ana Candalija</strong>, in &ldquo;Botox y otras toxinas, algo m&aacute;s que est&egrave;tica&rdquo; will talk about botox and other neurotoxines which can be used to treat diseases.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/0001.jpg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 492px;\" /></p>\n',101,2,2),(773,30,0,'El Dr. Andero aconsegueix augmentar la memòria en ratolins a través de l\'optogenètica','<p>\n	Ra&uuml;l Andero Gal&iacute;, un dels l&iacute;ders del grup &ldquo;Neurobiologia de l&rsquo;Estr&egrave;s i l&rsquo;Addicci&oacute;&rdquo; de l&rsquo;Institut i investigador de la Universitat de Harvard, ha publicat unes investigacions en les que per primera vegada a Espanya s&rsquo;ha estudiat com, a trav&eacute;s de l&rsquo;optogen&egrave;tica, es pot augmentar la mem&ograve;ria en ratolins.</p>\n<p>\n	Com explicava el director del nostre Institut, el Dr. Ignacio Morgado en un <u><a href=\"http://www.uab.cat/web/detalle-noticia-1345680342040.html?noticiaid=1345702313691\" target=\"_blank\">article per l&rsquo;UAB Divulga</a></u>, l&rsquo;optogen&egrave;tica &eacute;s una t&egrave;cnica que permet activar o desactivar volunt&agrave;riament determinades neurones mitjant&ccedil;ant l&rsquo;estimulaci&oacute; per un feix de llum. En els experiments que ha estat fent el Dr. Andero, s&rsquo;activaven en concret un grup de neurones de l&rsquo;am&iacute;gdala cerebral, les anomenades Tac2, que s&rsquo;encarreguen de la mem&ograve;ria del perill.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Tac2 amigdala.jpg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 280px;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<em><span style=\"font-size:10px;\">Microfotografia de l&#39;am&iacute;gdala cerebral. En verd s&#39;assenyalen les neurones Tac2, implicades en la mem&ograve;ria de la por. En blau s&#39;observa el nucli de les neurones de l&#39;am&iacute;gdala.</span></em></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	Els ratolins sotmesos al tractament tenien augmentada la mem&ograve;ria de la por a llarg termini, pel que eren capa&ccedil;os de recordar, al cap de m&eacute;s temps, un perill determinat. Per arribar a aquestes conclusions, els investigadors observaven el comportament de dues poblacions de ratolins: una que tenia les neurones Tac2 estimulades per optogen&egrave;tica i l&rsquo;altra, no. A ambdues poblacions se les feia escoltar un to i, despr&eacute;s, rebien un est&iacute;mul el&egrave;ctric desagradable. Els ratolins estimulats per optogen&egrave;tica recordaven a m&eacute;s llarg termini que el to precedia l&rsquo;est&iacute;mul i presentaven una conducta m&eacute;s poruga quan, dies despr&eacute;s, escoltaven nom&eacute;s el to.</p>\n<p>\n	&ldquo;Aquest descobriment ressalta la import&agrave;ncia de les neurones Tac2 en la regulaci&oacute; de la por i obre la porta a noves dianes terap&egrave;utiques en el tractament de desordres relacionats amb la por, com les f&ograve;bies, el trastorn obsessiu compulsiu o el trastorn per estr&egrave;s posttraum&agrave;tic&rdquo;, ens explica el Dr. Andero. El mateix investigador t&eacute; la patent d&rsquo;un f&agrave;rmac capa&ccedil; de bloquejar les neurones Tac2 que permetria disminuir les conseq&uuml;&egrave;ncies emocionals negatives que un succ&eacute;s traum&agrave;tic pot produir en el futur. &ldquo;A m&eacute;s, con&egrave;ixer la funci&oacute; i el funcionament de les neurones Tac2 podria ajudar a trobar maneres de millorar la mem&ograve;ria en persones sanes o amb problemes de mem&ograve;ria&rdquo;, conclou.</p>\n<p>\n	Les <u><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27238620\" target=\"_blank\">investigacions han estat publicades</a></u> recentment a la revista <em>Neuropsychopharmacology</em> i s&oacute;n el resultat de m&eacute;s de dos anys de treball al laboratori de Kerry Ressler, de la Universitat de Harvard, que van finalitzar-se a la UAB. L&rsquo;experi&egrave;ncia en l&rsquo;&uacute;s d&rsquo;aquesta t&egrave;cnica situa a l&rsquo;<em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies de la UAB</em> com un dels centres de refer&egrave;ncia del pa&iacute;s, i obre les portes a m&uacute;ltiples col&middot;laboracions internacionals.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/Catala/#!/_534_1\"><u>Fes una ullada</u></a> o <u><a href=\"https://soundcloud.com/user-872279367/entrevista-raul-andero\" target=\"_blank\">escolta</a></u> l&rsquo;entrevista que vam fer-li fa uns dies per Incentivem el coneixement.</p>\n',106,2,0),(774,52,0,'El Dr. Raül Andero consigue aumentar la memoria en ratones a través de la optogenética','<p>\n	El Dr. Ra&uuml;l Andero, uno de los l&iacute;deres del grupo &ldquo;Neurobiolog&iacute;a del Estr&eacute;s y la Adicci&oacute;n&rdquo; del Instituto e investigador de la Universidad de Harvard, ha publicado unes investigaciones en las que por primera vez en Espa&ntilde;a se ha estudiado c&oacute;mo, a trav&eacute;s de la optogen&eacute;tica se puede aumentar la memoria en ratones.</p>\n<p>\n	Como explicaba el director de nuestro Instituto, el Dr. Ignacio Morgado en un <span style=\"color:#000000;\"><u>ar</u></span><u><a href=\"http://www.uab.cat/web/detalle-noticia-1345680342040.html?noticiaid=1345702313691\" target=\"_blank\">t&iacute;culo para la UAB Divulga</a></u>, la optogen&eacute;tica es una t&eacute;cnica que permite activar o desactivar voluntariamente determinadas neuronas mediante la estimulaci&oacute;n por luz. En los experimentos que ha estado haciendo el Dr. Andero, se activaban en concreto un grupo de neuronas de la am&iacute;gdala cerebral, las llamadas Tac2, que se encargan de la memoria del peligro.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/Tac2 amigdala.jpg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 280px;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<em><span style=\"font-size:10px;\">Microfotograf&iacute;a de la am&iacute;gdala cerebral. En verde se se&ntilde;alan las neuronas Tac2, implicadas en la memoria del miedo. En azul se observa el n&uacute;cleo de las neuronas de la am&iacute;gdala.</span></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	Los ratones sometidos a este tratamiento ten&iacute;an aumentada la memoria del miedo a largo plazo, por lo que eran capaces de recordar, despu&eacute;s de m&aacute;s tiempo, un peligro determinado. Para llegar a estas conclusiones, los investigadores observaban el comportamiento de dos poblaciones de ratones: una que ten&iacute;a las neuronas Tac2 estimuladas por optogen&eacute;tica y la otra, no. A las dos poblaciones se les hac&iacute;a escuchar un tono y, despu&eacute;s, recib&iacute;an un est&iacute;mulo el&eacute;ctrico desagradable. Los ratones estimulados por optogen&eacute;tica recordaban m&aacute;s a largo plazo que el tono preced&iacute;a el est&iacute;mulo y presentaban una conducta m&aacute;s miedosa cuando, d&iacute;as despu&eacute;s, escuchaban el tono.</p>\n<p>\n	&ldquo;Nuestro descubrimiento resalta la importancia de las neuronas Tac2 en la regulaci&oacute;n del miedo y abre la puerta a nuevas dianas terap&eacute;uticas en el tratamiento de des&oacute;rdenes relacionados con el miedo, como las fobias, el trastorno obsesivo-compulsivo o el trastorno por estr&eacute;s postraum&aacute;tico&rdquo;, explica Ra&uuml;l Andero. El mismo investigador tiene la patente de un f&aacute;rmaco capaz de bloquear las neuronas Tac2 que permitir&iacute;a disminuir las consecuencias negativas que un suceso traum&aacute;tico puede producir en el futuro. &ldquo;Adem&aacute;s, entender la funci&oacute;n y el funcionamiento de las neuronas Tac2 tambi&eacute;n podr&iacute;a ayudar a encontrar maneras de mejorar la memoria en personas sanas o con problemas de memoria&rdquo;, concluye.</p>\n<p>\n	Las <u><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27238620\" target=\"_blank\">investigaciones publicadas</a></u> ahora son resultado de m&aacute;s de dos a&ntilde;os de trabajo de Ra&uuml;l Andero en el laboratorio de Kerry Ressler, del McLean Hospital en la Universidad de Harvard y finalizadas en la UAB. La experiencia del uso de esta t&eacute;cnica sit&uacute;a al <em>Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies </em>de la UAB como uno de los centros de referencia del pa&iacute;s y abre las puertas a m&uacute;ltiples colaboraciones internacionales.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<u><a href=\"http://inc.uab.cat/Castellano/#%21/_535_1\" target=\"_blank\">Echa un vistazo</a></u> o <a href=\"https://soundcloud.com/user-872279367/entrevista-raul-andero\" target=\"_blank\"><u>escucha</u></a> a la entrevista que le hicimos hace unos d&iacute;as para Incentivem el coneixement.</p>\n',103,2,1),(775,45,0,'Dr. Raül Andero used optogenetics to increase the memory in mice','<p>\n	Ra&uuml;l Andero Gal&iacute;, one of the heads of the &ldquo;Neurobiology of Stress and Addiction&rdquo; research group at the Institut and researcher at Harvard University, published an article in which, for the first time in Spain, optogenetics was used to increase memory.</p>\n<p>\n	The technique, tested in mice, consists in the stimulation of a group of neurones in the cerebral amygdala, named Tac2, using a laser. These neurones need to be previously made sensitive to light by introducing a virus in a specific cerebral area. There, the neurones are necessary to store memories related to fear. Mice which received this treatment saw their long-term memory increased and therefore were better at remembering danger.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"http://inc.uab.cat/DocsCKeditor/images/Tac2%20amigdala.jpg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 280px;\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<em><span style=\"font-size:10px;\">Microphotography of the cerebral amygdala. Tac2 neurons, involved in the memory of fear, are marked in green. In blue, the nucleus of amygdala neurones.</span></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	This is the first time in the world that light stimulation has been used to activate this specific group of memory neurones &ndash; in previous studies other types of memory neurones had been stimulated. The study, published in <em>Neuropsychoparhamacology</em> (Nature Publishing Group), helps to understand the mechanism by which fear is learned and represents a large step to finding treatments for fear-related diseases.</p>\n<p>\n	&ldquo;Our discovery stresses the importance of Tac2 neurones in the regulation of fear, and opens the door to new therapeutical targets for the treatment of diseases related to fear such as phobias, obsessive-compulsive disorder and post-traumatic stress disorder. Moreover, it can also help to find new ways to improve the memory of healthy people or people with memory problems&rdquo;, Ra&uuml;l Andero said.</p>\n<p>\n	To reach these conclusions, researchers observed the behavior of two mice populations: one under optogenetics treatment and the other under no treatment. They both were exposed to a tone and then received an unpleasant electrical stimuli. Mice stimulated by optogenetics remembered that the tone preceded the stimuli longer and showed more signs of fear when they heard the tone days after.</p>\n<p>\n	The <u><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27238620\" target=\"_blank\">published study</a></u> is the result of Raul Andero&rsquo;s work conducted during more than two years at Kerry Ressler&rsquo;s laboratory in McLean Hospital, Harvard University, and completed at the UAB. Two years ago, Ressler and Andero patented a drug that modulates this type of memory. The drug, and other analogues, may be capable of decreasing the emotional consequences a traumatic event can cause in the future and minimise the risk of suffering mental diseases related to the trauma.</p>\n<p>\n	In future studies, Andero and his collaborators will continue to study the cerebral mechanisms by which fear is learned. &ldquo;Next steps will be to study, by optogenetics, how the amygdala communicates with other parts of the brain also related to fear learning&rdquo; said the researcher.</p>\n<p>\n	The experience using this technique positions the UAB&rsquo;s Institut de Neuroci&egrave;ncies as a leading centre in the country and opens the door to multiple international collaborations.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	You can also <u>look at this interview</u> we did a few days ago.</p>\n',102,2,2),(776,30,0,'Enfermedad de Parkinson','<p>\n	<strong>&iquest;Qu&eacute; es la Enfermedad de Parkinson?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	La enfermedad de Parkinson es una enfermedad neurodegenerativa progresiva caracterizada por la p&eacute;rdida gradual de motilidad, enlentecimiento de movimientos, rigidez, temblor y trastornos posturales.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/2000px-Sir_William_Richard_Gowers_Parkinson_Disease_sketch_1886_svg.png\" style=\"width: 200px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>&iquest;Qu&eacute; ocurre en el cerebro de los pacientes con enfermedad de Parkinson?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Los pacientes sufren la desaparici&oacute;n de una peque&ntilde;a poblaci&oacute;n de unas neuronas espec&iacute;ficas, denominadas neuronas dopamin&eacute;rgicas, las cuales sintetizan dopamina, un neurotransmisor involucrado en importantes funciones motoras.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>&iquest;Es curable o tratable?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Desafortunadamente, la enfermedad de Parkinson no es curable, aunque los tratamientos farmacol&oacute;gicos son muy efectivos por largos periodos de tiempo. Para algunos pacientes, la intervenci&oacute;n quir&uacute;rgica puede ser efectiva. Sin embargo, estos tratamientos solamente reducen los s&iacute;ntomas de forma temporal mientras el proceso degenerativo sigue progresando.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>&iquest;Es hereditario?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	La forma m&aacute;s com&uacute;n de la enfermedad de Parkinson, no es trasmisible gen&eacute;ticamente. Sin embargo, existen algunas alteraciones gen&eacute;ticas raras en algunas familias que causan un s&iacute;ndrome parkinsoniano pr&aacute;cticamente id&eacute;ntico.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>&iquest;Los pacientes mueren de la enfermedad de Parkinson?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	La enfermedad de Parkinson no es mortal por si misma. Los pacientes con enfermedad de Parkinson mueren por complicaciones derivadas. En las fases m&aacute;s avanzadas de la enfermedad, los problemas respiratorios son una de las causas m&aacute;s frecuentes de fallecimiento, debido a la debilitaci&oacute;n de los m&uacute;sculos tor&aacute;cicos.</p>\n',107,2,0),(777,45,0,'Parkinson\'s disease','<p>\n	<strong>What is Parkinson&rsquo;s disease?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Parkinson&rsquo;s disease is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder characterized by the gradual loss of motility, slowness of movements, rigidity, tremor and postural alterations.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"/DocsCKeditor/images/2000px-Sir_William_Richard_Gowers_Parkinson_Disease_sketch_1886_svg.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 362px;\" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>What is wrong in the brain of Parkinson&rsquo;s disease patients?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Patients suffer the disappearance of a small population of particular neurons, called dopaminergic neurons, which synthetize dopamine a neurotransmitter involved in important motor functions.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Is Parkinson&rsquo;s disease curable or treatable?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Unfortunately Parkinson&rsquo;s disease is not curable today, although pharmacological treatments are very effective for long periods of time. For some electable patients, surgical interventions may also be effective. However, these treatments temporally reduce the symptoms as the degenerative process progresses over time.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Is Parkinson&rsquo;s disease hereditary?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	The most common form of Parkinson&rsquo;s disease is not genetically transmissible. However, there are rare genetic alterations in few families that generate an almost identical Parkinsonian syndrome.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Do people die of Parkinson&rsquo;s disease?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Parkinson&rsquo;s disease is not deadly by itself. People with Parkinson&rsquo;s disease die from derived complications. In latest stages of the disease, respiratory problems are a common cause of death due to thoracic muscle weakness.</p>\n',103,2,2),(778,30,0,'Articles','<div>\n	<span style=\"color:#800000;\"><strong>JANUARY</strong></span></div>\n<div>\n	G&oacute;mez-Rom&aacute;n A, Ortega-S&aacute;nchez JA, Rotllant D, Gagliano H, Belda X, Delgado-Morales R, Mar&iacute;n-Blasco I, Nadal R, Armario A,<strong>The neuroendocrine response to stress under the effect of drugs: Negative synergy between amphetamine and stressors. </strong>Psychoneuroendocrinology. 2016 Gen;63:94&ndash;101. <strong><u><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26433325\" target=\"_blank\">V&eacute;s a l&#39;article</a></u></strong></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Meyer C, Stenberg L, Gonzalez-Perez F, Wrobel S, Ronchi G, Udina E, Suganuma S, Geuna S, Navarro X, Dahlin LB, Grothe C, Haastert-Talini K, <strong>Chitosan-film enhanced chitosan nerve guides for long-distance regeneration of peripheral nerves. </strong>Biomaterials. 2016 Gen;76:33&ndash;51. <strong><u><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26517563\" target=\"_blank\">V&eacute;s a l&#39;article</a></u></strong></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Jard&iacute; F, Fern&aacute;ndez-Blanco JA, Mart&iacute;nez V, Vergara P. <strong>Persistent alterations in colonic afferent innervation in a rat model of postinfecti